<DOCNO> AP890105-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 0151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Libya-WorldReax Bjt   01-05 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya-World Reax, Bjt,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arabs Denounce Downing of Libyan Jets; Europe ``Concerned''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The shock waves ran from Syria to Switzerland after U.S. Navy
planes shot down two Libyan jet fighters over the Mediterranean,
with only Israel's top leadership cheering the U.S. fliers' feat.
   U.S. allies in Europe for the most part reserved comment after
Wednesday's action, although some expressed ``great concern'' and
regret. Arab nations were unanimous in their denunciation.
   In Zurich, the dollar closed sharply higher in interbank trading
Wednesday. Today, it was up 1.28 yen in Tokyo.
   One dealer in Zurich, who spoke on condition of not being
identified, said the rise was in reaction to the U.S.-Libyan
confrontation. He said the dollar always gains strength in times of
international tension.
   A White House spokesman said U.S. F-14s shot down the two
Soviet-built MiG-23s about 40 miles off Libya after the U.S.
warplanes were ``threatened while conducting routine operations.''
The Navy said the U.S. jets returned safely to the aircraft carrier
John F. Kennedy.
   Tensions have heightened between the Tripoli government and
Washington in recent weeks over claims by the Reagan administration
that Col. Moammar Gadhafi's government has built a chemical weapons
plant south of the capital in Rabta. The United States said,
however, that the incident over the Mediterranean had nothing to do
with that issue.
   The Kremlin withheld immediate comment on the incident, but
Soviet news media quickly reported the air action. The official news
agency Tass called it ``U.S. aggression against Libya.''
   In London, Michael Mates, of Britain's governing Conservative
Party and chairman of the parliamentary committee on defense, told
the British Broadcasting Corp.:
   ``If the Libyans have made an offensive gesture toward the United
States, I'm not surprised they've been shot down, because they're
not a friendly nation, they have committed many aggressive acts
against the United States.''
   Washington accuses Libya of sponsoring international terrorism.
   No official British comment was forthcoming and in Bonn, West
German Foreign Ministry spokesman Hanns Schumacher said in declining
to comment that the Bonn government was not officially informed of
the action.
   Roland Dumas, the French foreign minister, said, ``It is still
too early to know the exact circumstances of the incident.''
   President Francois Mitterrand of France has called an
international conference for Jan. 7-11 to discuss expanding a 1925
treaty banning chemical weapons use and Dumas said he hoped
Wednesday's episode would not dominate it. President Reagan said
last month his advisors were considering a military strike on the
Rabta plant, but The Washington Post today quoted senior
administration officials as saying he now opposes attacking the
plant because Washington's European allies are against the idea.
   The Italian government expressed ``deep concern'' about
Wednesday's incident.
   ``We believe that the situation in the Mediterranean area imposes
on everybody the obligation to be moderate and to renounce any act
of violence which may cause a further use of military strength,''
said a government spokesman, who commented on condition of anonymity.
   In Spain, Foreign Ministry spokesman Juan Lena said: ``The
Spanish government considers with serious concern any kind of
measure that leads to an increase in tension in the Mediterranean.''
   About 3,000 leftist Greek demonstrators marched to the U.S.
Embassy in Athens, shouting anti-U.S. slogans, and a government
spokesman said Greece believes both sides ``at this moment should
cool it and avoid actions that would endanger peace in this
sensitive region.''
   Arab League Secretary-General Chedli Klibi demanded Washington
end acts of ``provocation near the Libyan coasts.''
   In Tunisia, which borders Libya, he said the attack amounted to
an ``extremely serious aggression'' dictated by a ``false perception
by the United States of its role in regulating international
problems.'' Klibi said any escalation would have ``negative
consequences'' on U.S.-Arab relations.
   In Syria, state-run television called it ``flagrant U.S.
aggression.''
   Yasser Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization,
told Cable News Network in an interview from Cairo, Egypt ``It will
affect negatively the Middle East peace process.'' He termed the
incident ``very serious.''
   The few kind words came mainly from Jerusalem.
   Finance Minister Shimon Peres of Israel said, ``We congratulate
the American Navy for shooting down two planes that were threatening
it.''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's spokesman, Avi Pazner, said:
``Based on previous Libyan behavior, we have no reason to doubt the
official American explanation of this incident.''
   Benjamin Netanyahu, the deputy foreign minister, told Parliament
that Israel has evidence Libya is capable of producing chemical arms.
</TEXT>
