<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 0315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-OilSpill-Hospital Bjt   01-05 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill-Hospital, Bjt,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil-Soaked Seabirds Get Care At Dirty Bird Hospital</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID AMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OCEAN SHORES, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Welcome to Dirty Bird Hospital. Like
television's St. Elsewhere, the accommodations aren't much, but the
care is great.
   Ocean Shores Convention Center, the seaside hall usually teeming
with conventioneers and banquets, has been redubbed Oil Spill
Command Center in the wake of one of the Pacific Northwest's worst
oil spills.
   The focal point is Dirty Bird Hospital. Thousands of oil-soaked
sea birds get tender loving care and rest in the wards of the
makeshift veterinary hospital complex staffed by hundreds of
volunteers.
   Alice Berkner, a Vancouver, Wash., bird expert who heads the
effort, is a gracious, if exhausted, host to visitors, including
Gov. Booth Gardner, who stopped by Wednesday.
   She said more volunteers are needed to augment the effort and to
relieve some of those now working. More than 1,000 have helped out.
   ``This is not some emotional commitment to help `the poor little
birdies,''' she said. ``It's more a matter of we made the mess and
let's clean it up and develop a technology for heading this off.''
   More than 3,200 birds are known to have died since a tug and a
barge collided Dec. 22 off Grays Harbor near here, causing a spill
estimated at up to 231,000 gallons. Gobs of heavy bunker oil have
dirtied more than 300 miles of coast from Oregon to British Columbia.
   An estimated 5,200 birds wound up at Dirty Bird Hospital, and
2,700 lived, according to Don Kane of the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service. Smaller cleanup operations were set up at Astoria, Ore.,
and Neah Bay.
   The barge's owners, Sause Bros. Ocean Towing of Coos Bay, Ore.,
has agreed to pay for the cleanup, including the $50,000 spent on
Dirty Bird Hospital and other command center operations. No estimate
has been made on the overall cost.
   Following Berkner's design, the massive convention hall has been
transformed into hospital wards and stations.
   A visitor's first stop is the pens where the newly received birds
are housed. Huddled, black with oily goo, the birds show little
spark of life as they sleep or stare blankly from bedsheets atop
crumpled newspapers.
   Volunteers tube-feed the birds, pass out raw fish four times a
day and try to help the birds regain their strength.
   From the pens, birds are carried to the washing room, where they
get three or four warm, soapy baths. One volunteer holds and the
other scrubs, sometimes using a toothbrush. Most of the oil comes
off with one good washing, but the additional baths are necessary to
take off the rest.
   Then comes a vigorous, long rinse, the process the birds seem to
resent most.
   ``It's all traumatic to these birds,'' said Berkner. Pointing to
one protesting murre, she shook her head and said, ``It probably
thinks it's about to be eaten, that it's under attack. It's all a
shock. Getting oiled was a shock.''
   After drying and recovering a bit, the seabirds are placed in a
flotation pond to check their buoyancy and wing action. If they
sink, they're washed and rinsed again.
   Some of the birds don't make it through the cleaning.
   ``You can't imagine what it feels like to be washing a precious
little bird and then having it die right in your hands,'' one woman
said.
   The survivors will be released far from their normal habitat so
they won't run the risk of being oiled again. Twenty-seven have been
released so far, according to Kane.
   ``That's the best part,'' said Berkner. She said her crews would
try to get the birds through the cleaning process as soon as
possible.
   ``These are wild animials. Certainly the longer they're here, the
harder it is on them,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
