<HEAD>Contra Rebels Attack Army Headquarters, Two Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra rebels attacked a Sandinista
army post, killing two brothers and injuring another soldier and a
government official, military sources said.
   Army sources said late Wednesday that about 30 Contra rebels
attacked an 18-man military command in Muan, a town 136 miles east
of the capital.
   The attack Tuesday night was led by rebel commanders known as
``Pipilacha'' and ``Capulina'', the sources said.
   They said the rebel leaders, who entered Nicaragua from Costa
Rica last December with about 200 men, have established themselves
in the country's southeastern region.
   The government and U.S.-supported rebels reached a cease-fire
agreement March 23, but talks on a permanent truce to the 8-year
civil war broke down in September. Each side accuses the other of
frequent cease-fire violations.
   Killed in the attack were soldiers Miguel and Ismael Maltez
Hernandez, whom town residents said were recent draftees.
   The injured were identified as Lt. Roger Miranda Martinez and
Julio Aguilar, a delegate of the governing Sandinista National
Liberation Front.
   No rebel injuries or deaths were reported.
   The Defense Ministry late Tuesday reported that three farmworkers
were killed and another three injured in a similar rebel attack Jan.
2 in La Maranosa, 8 miles south of Wiwili near the Honduran border.
   The Sandinista party newspaper Barricada recently reported that
rebel forces were planning ``sensational attacks'' in hopes of
convincing President-elect Bush to renew military support for the
rebels, which expired last year.
