<FIRST>r a PM-Catbuster     01-05 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Catbuster,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catbuster Nabs First Feline For Violating New Leash Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAPERVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Animal control officer Kim Johnsen has
apprehended this city's first feline felon, but she says publicity
about the Chicago suburb's cat leash law makes her out to be just
what she isn't _ a cat hater.
   Weeks of news reports, interviews and telephone calls _ many of
them hostile _ preceded the first cat-nabbing, which Ms. Johnsen
describes as a pretty routine affair.
   ``The cat was sitting in the street and I almost ran it over,''
Ms. Johnsen said late Wednesday. ``I got out and called to it, and
it came over to me, but then it ran off ... the second time I
called, it came over again, and I just picked it up and put it in a
cage.''
   The arrest last Friday had a happy ending, Ms. Johnsen said.
   ``It was a very clean, pretty, cat _ an orange tabby, 1 to 2
years old and declawed,'' she said. ``It had its shot tag and an
identification tag on its collar, so I got in touch with the owner
right away.''
   ``He was informed that he had the dubious honor of being the
first one caught under the new law. When he stopped laughing, he
came over and picked up his cat,'' she said.
   The owner, who asked not to be identified, paid a $10 fine, a $15
pound fee and an $8 cat license fee, Ms. Johnsen said. Under the new
law, he could have been fined $200 if there had been public
complaints about his cat.
   Publicity was spreading about the Naperville cat control
ordinance even before it took effect Dec. 2.
   ``I understand stories about the cat law appeared in about 65
countries and in every part of the United States,'' Ms. Johnsen
said. ``I was even on a radio talk show from Arizona for about 45
minutes last month. I took a lot of flak and a lot of telephone
calls.''
   Naperville cats must now be inoculated and wear identifying
collars. If they go outdoors and set foot on any street, alley or
other public place, they must be on leash.
   ``Some people have been calling me the queen of the cat-haters,
but that's not at all true,'' said Ms. Johnsen. ``I've got three
cats of my own at home _ all neutered and declawed _ and they don't
go outside. It's too dangerous for a cat out there.''
</TEXT>
