<HEAD>Possible Clue In Girl's Disappearance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASTRO VALLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who told school children at a
bus stop he would ``get them next'' resembled the kidnapper of
Michaela Garecht, who was abducted in November from a supermarket
parking lot, according to authorities.
   Four elementary school children were at the stop on Wednesday
when the man drove by and warned them through a loudspeaker,
Sheriff's Deputy Gordon Altman said.
   The man did not attempt to grab any of the children.
   ``We're taking it seriously because his description is similar to
the general description of the suspect in the Michaela Garecht
kidnapping case,'' Altman said. ``The kids are about her age, too.''
   Michaela, 9, of Hayward, was abducted Nov. 19 by a man with long
blond hair and acne. The Hayward girl was with a friend when she was
grabbed. The other girl got away.
   Hundreds of volunteers spent hours stuffing envelopes and placing
posters around the San Francisco Bay area to try to find clues. Even
San Francisco 49ers quarterback Joe Montana went on TV with his wife
and pleaded for girl's return. No demands were made to Michaela's
parents.
   Altman would not describe the vehicle involved in Wednesday's
incident or be specific about the man's description, saying the
information might damage the investigation.
   ``When you're looking for a needle in the haystack, you can't
overlook anything,'' Altman said. ``Anything could be the clue that
leads us to the guy.''
