<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--Beer-Fire     01-05 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Beer-Fire,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beer Douses Blaze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALAMEDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tops on bottles in 10 cases of beer
popped during a restaurant fire, sending out a stream of suds that
quenched the blaze before firefighters arrived.
   ``It was the best smelling fire I've ever been at,'' fire
department Lt. Dennis Jennings said of Wednesday's fire at the
Kamakura Restaurant.
   Two or three rags soaked in linseed oil spontaneously ignited
near the beer cases that had been left on a newly laid linoleum
floor to help the adhesive stick, fire officials said.
   When the beer reached the boiling point, the bottles exploded.
   No one was in the restaurant when the fire broke out and no
injuries were reported.
   ``It burned a 1-foot hole in the flooring and went up the wall.
We opened the wall, but the fire hadn't reached it,'' Jennings said.
   Fire officials estimated the loss of contents _ the beer _ at
$300 and the structural damage at $1,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
