<DOCNO> AP890105-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 0557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TreeMemorial     01-05 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tree Memorial,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supporters of Vietnam Forest Memorial Raise Funds To Save Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CUSHING, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A forest planted in the nation's heartland
to honor Americans killed in Vietnam was saved from a bank
foreclosure sale by veterans of that war and other supporters around
the country.
   ``What we're trying to do is heal the people,'' said Vietnam
veteran Geoffrey Steiner, 39, who started the project nine years
ago. ``This is a living memorial.''
   Fruth Companies Inc., a Coors beer distributor in Brainerd, gave
$5,400 Wednesday on behalf of Adolph Coors Co. and Coors
distributors in Minnesota toward the $6,033.53 needed to keep the
100-acre forest near Cushing, a tiny town about 120 miles north of
Minneapolis, from being sold.
   The remainder of the money to save the Veterans National Living
Memorial came from Vietnam Veterans of America chapters and
individuals around the country.
   ``I think the good Lord sent them,'' said Steiner, who said he is
more than halfway toward his goal of planting a tree for every one
of the approximately 58,000 Americans who died in Vietnam.
   VVA chapters in Dayton, Ohio, and Junction City, Kan., also have
raised several hundred dollars to pay property taxes on the tract,
said Terry Thompson, legislative coordinator for the Dayton chapter.
   There also are plans to place the property in a trust so it
cannot be encroached upon again, said Thompson, who arrived in
Minnesota earlier this week to help raise money.
   The forest stands on a little hilltop about three miles off a
highway at the dead end of a country road.
   At the center of the stand of small trees that has been planted
over the past eight years is a wooden flagpole flying an American
flag and a stone marker.
   Thompson, who is not a veteran but volunteers in the Dayton
chapter, said she decided to help Steiner after reading a newspaper
article last month on his plight and the unusual memorial.
   She called the memorial ``part of that healing process that will
be beneficial to Vietnam vets and their families.''
   Steiner, a Marine in Vietnam in 1967-68 who now counsels
veterans, said he paid $23,000 in cash for the land in 1980 after
selling his Minneapolis home. Since then, he has planted more than
30,000 trees.
   He was about to lose the land for failing to repay an $8,000 loan
from Randall State Bank that he secured with the property in 1984 to
buy a car for his wife. Had the land been sold, the only way Steiner
could have gotten it back would have been to match the winning bid
within a year.
   With only half an hour before the aucition was to begin
Wednesday, Steiner, along with Thompson, the beer distributor and
two other VVA officials from Ohio, brought the money to a Little
Falls law office to pay the debt.
   Coors, based in Golden, Colo., has a longstanding interest in
helping veterans and their families, said Gary Fruth, co-owner of
Fruth Companies.
   ``They kind of entered this as a white knight,'' Fruth said. ``We
just didn't like the idea of them taking it away from that guy after
all of his work.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890105-0059 </DOCNO>
