<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     01-05 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain in West, Cold in the East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers lingered over the Southwest today after a storm that left
Phoenix cleaning up from a tornado that briefly touched down, while
subzero temperatures prevailed in New England and parts of the
Midwest.
   The tornado touched down briefly Wednesday and did minor damage
to some buildings. No injuries were reported.
   In the Pacific Northwest, a cold front produced rain and snow in
the mountains. A low-pressure system over the Southwest left snow
over parts of the Rocky Mountains.
   In Utah, 12 inches of snow fell in Richfield, 10 inches in Kanosh
and 5 in Price. Snow tapered off in Colorado, where 7 inches were
reported in Silverton. Flagstaff, Ariz., got 9 inches. Hail was
reported in Albuquerque, N.M.
   Snow advisories were posted for the southern Cascade and Siskiyou
mountains of Oregon, California's Sierra Nevada, parts of Nevada and
New Mexico.
   The subzero temperatures in New England combined with strong
winds to produce bone-chilling wind chill factors of minus 30
degrees in much of the region. The wind chill index in Limestone,
Maine, was 50 below.
   The nation's high Wednesday was 86 degrees at Harlingen, Texas.
   Today's forecast called for rain in Iowa, Illinois, Wisconsin,
Indiana, Ohio and Tennessee; rain showers and occasional
thunderstorms in Kansas, Oklahoma, Texas, the lower Mississippi
Valley and Missouri. Rain showers with snow was predicted at higher
elevations. Snow was also forecast in sections of the upper Missouri
Valley, the Rockies, Wyoming and the Pacific Northwest.
   High temperatures were predicted in the single digits and teens
in northern New England; the 20s and 30s in central New England, the
Virginias, the Great Lakes, the upper Mississippi Valley, the
northern Plains, the upper Missouri Valley, the Rockies and Wyoming;
60s and 70s in Florida, the Gulf Coast, the lower Mississippi
Valley, Texas, Arizona and California; and 40s and 50s in the rest
of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 12
degrees below zero at Rome, N.Y., to 72 degrees at McAllen, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 33 fair; Boston 6 windy; Buffalo 8 snow;
Charleston, S.C. 36 fair; Cincinnati 24 fair; Cleveland 17 cloudy;
Detroit 20 cloudy; Miami 57 fair; New York 12 fair; Philadelphia 13
fair; Pittsburgh 14 snow; Portland, Maine 0 windy; Washington 19
fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 17 partly cloudy; Chicago 26 fair; Dallas-Fort
Worth 62 cloudy; Denver 39 rain; Des Moines 34 partly cloudy;
Indianapolis 22 fair; Kansas City 42 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 18
fair; Nashville 30 fair; New Orleans 46 fair; St. Louis 36 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 36 cloudy; Anchorage 11 snow; Las Vegas 41
fair; Los Angeles 53 partly cloudy; Phoenix 53 partly cloudy; Salt
Lake City 26 snow; San Diego 54 fair; San Francisco 50 cloudy;
Seattle 39 rain.
   _Canada: Montreal -7 fair.
</TEXT>
