<FIRST>r a PM-RestaurantHostages     01-05 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Restaurant Hostages,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunman Remembered As Troubled, `Stressed'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOVELAND, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A parolee whose violent outburst ended in
the deaths of two hostages and himself was anxious about the
possible breakup of his marriage and haunted by his Vietnam War
experiences, say those who knew him. But Wayne Strozzi, 35, also was
remembered as a good father, neighbor and friend in the aftermath of
Tuesday night's bloody drama.
   ``There was something wrong with Wayne last night. Wayne wasn't
Wayne last night,'' said Maryanne Urista, a neighbor who called
Strozzi a good father ``who cared so much about his girls'' and a
horseman who loved his animals and went on family rides.
   Authorities investigating the standoff at the Riverhouse
Restaurant here said they are mainly concerned now with the
accidental killing of a hostage by police.
   ``We are focusing on one question, and that is that matter of the
justification of the police shooting,'' said Larimer County District
Attorney Stu VanMeveren.
   Fenton Crookshank, 45, of Loveland was shot and killed by a
Loveland police officer as he tried to escape through a bathroom
window of the restaurant. Police said Crookshank failed to heed
warnings to stop.
   Strozzi had broken into the restaurant and taken about 20 people
hostage. During the standoff, he threatened he was ``going to waste
everybody'' and intended to burn down the restaurant, and demanded a
getaway car and a plane to Libya.
   At one point, waitress Ann Knight said, Strozzi ordered her to
fetch his boots and a shirt from his pickup truck, saying, ``A good
cowboy dies with his boots on.'' He wounded two officers before he
was gunned down by a sharpshooter.
   After Strozzi was shot, he apparently shot another hostage,
waitress Sally Mills, 40, in a dying reflex, police said. Strozzi
and Mills died later at McKee Medical Center.
   VanMeveren said he was trying to determine whether the officers
were covered by Colorado law when they opened fire. The law mandates
that when police fire at someone they have reasonable fear that they
or a hostage will be hurt or that the person has committed a felony
with a dangerous weapon.
   VanMeveren declined to name the officers who shot Strozzi and the
hostage. He said they were suffering from ``post-traumatic stress''
and were placed on leave with pay until the case is resolved.
   Most people who knew Strozzi were shocked by the news of the
standoff, though some said he had serious emotional problems.
   Strozzi's estranged wife, Bobbi, called him ``a real sweetheart.''
   ``I think he had a lot of emotional problems because of
Vietnam,'' she said. ``It was real hard to feel good about himself
again. He was trying real, real hard to work his problems out. Heck,
he hadn't touched a drink in over a year, or any other kind of
drug.''
   The couple had graduated from a domestic violence class together.
The events Tuesday night began when Bobbi Strozzi told police her
husband had choked and threatened her.
   Strozzi, a Las Vegas native, served one year in Vietnam with the
101st Infantry in the early 1970s and received a general discharge.
He openly discussed his combat experiences, which a halfway house
counselor described as ``pretty heavy.''
   His father, Harry Strozzi of Las Vegas, said his son was ``pretty
stressed out.''
   After moving to Loveland in 1975 with their two daughters, the
couple was separated late last year. Last month, Bobbi and the two
daughters moved out of the trailer where the family had lived.
   Strozzi, a construction worker, was arrested in 1984 and
convicted 1{ years later on charges of possessing and selling
cocaine. He was sentenced to three years in prison. Strozzi was
paroled in 1987 after time in a minimum-security prison and a
halfway house.
   William Fitzgerald, a parole officer in Boulder County, said
parole officers didn't consider Strozzi a threat.
   ``In our records, there is absolutely no indication of him being
violent,'' Fitzgerald said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890105-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 0700EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Judges'Feud     01-05 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Judges' Feud,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>County Commissioners Solve Judges' Office Feud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state judge who wanted a rival's
courtroom so badly he broke into his office and removed his papers
and books was awarded the chambers when El Paso County Commissioners
decided seniority should prevail.
   The commissioners' decision Wednesday in favor of district Judge
Peter Peca Jr. means Judge Jose Troche is a man without a chambers:
El Paso has 11 district judges but only 10 courtrooms.
   The office and courtroom in dispute had been vacated last week by
Ward Koehler, the former 168th district judge who defeated Peca last
November for a spot in the state's 8th Court of Appeals.
   In one of his last acts as district judge, Koehler decreed that
Troche, his appointed successor, should get the sixth-floor office
rather than Peca.
   Peca, who was elected to the 171st district two years ago, had
been the odd judge out in the game of musical benches. He had to
hold court wherever he could find an available courtroom.
   On Sunday, Peca broke into the office and removed papers, books
and other items belonging to Troche, who had moved in Friday and
posted Koehler's decree on the door.
   When Troche went to the office Monday to tidy up, he found Peca's
nameplate in place of Koehler's order. The locks had been changed,
and Troche's property had been moved to a table in a jury room down
the hall.
   Despite Peca's unilateral action, commissioners bought his
argument that he should get a permanent office because he has
seniority over Troche.
   Peca was not present at the commissioners' meeting, but Troche
commented, ``I'd like the court to establish some procedure (for
allocating court space).''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
