<FIRST>r i PM-Panama     01-05 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delvalle Writes Noriega Offering To Negotiate Political Solution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle
has written to the nation's leader, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
offering to negotiate a solution to Panama's political crisis.
   Delvalle asked Noriega in a letter to accept ``this ...
invitation to reach an understanding which will benefit our country
and all Panamanians.''
   A copy of the letter, dated Dec. 27 and written on stationery of
the Panamanian Embassy in Washington, was obtained by The Associated
Press from Noriega opponents who refused to be identified further.
   In February 1988, Delvalle attempted to fire Noriega as commander
of Panama's Defense Forces after two federal grand juries in Florida
indicted the general on drug trafficking and money laundering
charges.
   Noriega orchestrated Delvalle's ouster by the National Assembly
and replaced him with Education Minister Manuel Solis Palma.
   The United States, which continues to recognize Delvalle as
Panama's president, imposed economic sanctions on Panama and brought
diplomatic pressure to bear in an unsuccessful effort to force
Noriega to resign.
   Delvalle signed the letter ``President of the Republic of
Panama.'' The Panamanian Embassy in Washington is in the hands of
Noriega opponents.
   A Defense Forces official in Panama City, who spoke condition of
anonymity, said: ``We have no knowledge'' of Delvalle's letter.
   Delvalle said the nation's political and economic crisis has
created hardships for Panamanians and ``caused the government to be
incapable of providing basic public services due to a drop in
government revenue.''
   He wrote the letter six days after meeting in Washington with
President-elect Bush, who told reporters later his policy will
continue to be ``that Noriega must go.''
   Raul Saint Malo, a counselor at the Panamanian Embassy in
Washington, said in a telephone interview Delvalle's letter was sent
by way of the Vatican Embassy in Washington to the Vatican Embassy
in Panama City.
   Diplomatic sources said Delvalle had returned to Panama and was
in hiding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
