<FIRST>r i PM-Laos-MIAs     01-05 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Laos-MIAs,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Laos, U.S. Agree To Year-Round Cooperation On MIAs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Laos have agreed
to conduct year-round joint activities to resolve the fate of
missing American servicemen, according to a U.S. statement.
   In the talks, the Laotians also agreed in principle to cooperate
in anti-narcotics programs, said the statement, dated Wednesday.
   The talks were held Monday and Tuesday in the capital of Laos,
Vientiane, by teams led by Laotian Vice Foreign Minister Soubanh
Srithirath and Richard Childress, director of Asian affairs at the
U.S. National Security Council.
   The U.S. team issued its statement through the U.S. Embassy in
Bangkok.
   The statement said the two sides reviewed the issue of missing
Americans, and ``agreed to establish a year-round schedule of joint
activities, including research, further surveys and excavations.''
It said specifics of the plan will be discussed during a meeting of
technical experts later this month.
   The United States wants to account for 547 Americans listed as
missing in action in Laos as a result of the Indochina war, which
ended in 1975. The two sides have conducted four joint excavations
of U.S. warplane crash sites to search for remains.
   The United States also acknowledged Laos' domestic problems,
recently complicated by a poor rice harvest because of drought, and
``renewed its pledge to respond to the extent possible,'' the
statement said.
   It said: ``Following a U.S. expression of concern over narcotics
production and trafficking, the Laos government informed the U.S.
side of its agreement in principle to bilateral cooperation with the
United States on narcotics program activities, a development we
strongly welcome.''
   U.S. officials have accused Laotian government and military
authorities of involvement in the production and trafficking of
large quantities of opium and marijuana. The Laotians deny this and
have protested the charge.
   The two sides also expressed interest in increased commercial
contacts, the statement said. It said representatives of the U.S.
State and Commerce departments also met with Laotian officials to
discuss trade and investment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
