<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-CarolinaProkofiev 1stLd-Writethru a0522 01-05 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Carolina Prokofiev, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0522,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prokofiev's Widow Dead At 90</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4-5 grafs pvs, ``Mrs...1918.'' with 2 grafs to ADD details
on Mrs. Prokofiev's name. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``They were...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carolina Prokofiev, widow of the celebrated Russian
composer Serge Prokofiev, has died of cancer in London, her son said
today. She was 91.
   Mrs. Prokofiev, who survived a Soviet prison camp, two years ago
narrated her husband's classic children's work ``Peter and the
Wolf'' at Lincoln Center in New York to celebrate the 50th
anniversary of the work.
   She died Tuesday about three months after falling ill and will be
cremated in London on Jan. 11, said her son, Oleg Prokofiev.
   Mrs. Prokofiev was born Carolina Codina in Madrid in 1897 to a
Catalonian father and a Polish-French mother. Later she became
universally known Lina, and unlike the rest of the family, insisted
on transliterating her married name from the Russian as Prokofieff,
her son said.
   Her parents were professional singers, and she trained as a
classical recitalist. The Codinas traveled extensively and settled
in New York, where Carolina met Prokofiev in 1918.
   They were married in Germany in 1923, lived in Paris, then moved
to the Soviet Union in 1934. But they drifted apart in the 1940s.
   In 1948, Prokofiev was one of the composers denounced by the
Stalin government for writing ``bourgeois'' music. Mrs. Prokofiev
was accused of having contact with anti-Soviet elements and was sent
to Ubez prison camp in the northern Urals.
   Prokofiev died in 1953, and his widow was freed three years
later. Her son Oleg, a sculptor, emigrated to England and in 1974
she was allowed to join him.
   She settled in London and traveled extensively.
   Later this month, in accordance with her wishes, her ashes will
placed at her mother-in-law's burialplace in Paris, her son said.
   An older son, architect Sviatoslav Prokofiev, lives in Moscow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890105-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 0921EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-GandhiAssassins     01-05 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gandhi Assassins,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Dismisses Appeals for Gandhi Assassins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today dismissed two
appeals that a defense lawyer called ``the last legal battle'' to
save two Sikhs condemned to hang for the 1984 assassination of Prime
Minister Indira Gandhi.
   A panel of five justices quickly turned down a plea by Satwant
Singh, the lone surviving assassin. Another five-judge panel, acting
almost as swiftly, rejected a petition by Kehar Singh, who allegedly
helped plot the murder.
   ``This is the last legal battle. We can't go anywhere now,'' said
Kehar Singh's attorney, Ram Jethmalani.
   Kehar Singh, 54, and Satwant Singh, 30, are to hang at 8 a.m.
Friday in the refurbished gallows of New Delhi's maximum-security
Tihar Central Jail.
   The two men are not related, but like all members of the Sikh
faith use the name Singh, which means lion.
   Heavily-armed security forces were placed on maximum alert and
checkpoints set up in the capital and in the northern states of
Haryana, Himachal Pradesh and Punjab, where militant Sikhs have been
waging a 6-year-old war for independence. Authorities fear the
executions could trigger a new outbreak of communal violence.
   Jethmalani, one of the country's leading criminal attorneys,
asked the Supreme Court to block the scheduled executions,
challenging President Ramaswamy Venkataraman's refusal of clemency
for Kehar Singh.
   The attorney said the president considered only the government's
case and ignored new evidence, including the arrest of a Sikh
terrorist who allegedly confessed he was the mastermind of Mrs.
Gandhi's murder.
   ``I am arguing in the shadow of the death of Kehar Singh, with
two ready hangmen and a prepared pyre,'' an emotional Jethmalani
told the justices.
   Venkataraman twice rejected the mercy plea, saying he was bound
by the recommendations of the government, headed by the slain prime
minister's son and successor, Rajiv Gandhi.
   The government's chief attorney, G. Ramaswamy, said Kehar Singh's
guilt had been proved beyond reasonable doubt by the trial court and
an appeals court as well as the Supreme Court.
   Down the corridor, another court panel rejected an appeal by
Satwant Singh, seeking prosecution of two of Mrs. Gandhi's security
guards. The inmate claimed the two guards shot him after he had been
disarmed and that their actions were tantamount to attempted murder.
   The justices ruled the appeal had no merit.
   Satwant Singh did not file a mercy petition with the president.
But under Indian laws, his death sentence was automatically delayed
when Kehar Singh sought clemency.
   In London, the Amnesty International human rights group and a
leading British jurist, Lord Gifford, appealed today for clemency
for the two Sikhs, and said the evidence against Kehar Singh was too
weak to justify his conviction.
   Two Sikh bodyguards, Satwant Singh and Beant Singh, shot Mrs.
Gandhi in the garden of her New Delhi residence on Oct. 31, 1984.
   Mrs. Gandhi apparently was killed in retaliation for an army raid
she ordered four months earlier to rout Sikh militants from the
Golden Temple, the Sikhs' holiest shrine. More than 1,200 people
died, most of them Sikhs.
   Beant Singh was killed in a shootout with other security guards
and is revered as a martyr by many militant Sikhs. Satwant Singh was
injured.
   Kehar Singh, Beant's uncle, was arrested a month later and
charged with helping to plot Mrs. Gandhi's assassination, which
triggered anti-Sikh riots across northern India by members of the
majority Hindu religion. More than 2,700 people were killed, nearly
all of them Sikhs.
   Sikh violence since then has escalated. At least 2,440 people
died last year in northern Punjab state alone.
   The eight-month trial, which culminiated in convictions and death
sentences on Jan. 22, 1986, was held in a make-shift courtroom at
the prison.
   A third Sikh, Balbir Singh, also was arrested, tried and
convicted on conspiracy charges and sentenced to death in Mrs.
Gandhi's assassination. The Supreme Court, however, overturned his
conviction and sentence in August for lack of evidence.
   Capital punishment is rare in India. Of 85,000 murder cases
between 1974 and 1984 only 288 death sentences were passed,
government statistics say.
   The last hanging in New Delhi's Tihar prison was in February 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
