<DOCNO> AP890105-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 0945EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-CustomsWar     01-05 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Customs War,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Export Limits Won't Apply to Hard Currency Purchases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western travelers, already a privileged class in
the Soviet Union, will gain further favors Feb. 1 because their hard
currency can exempt them from the fallout of a ``customs war'' among
socialist countries.
   The Soviet Union is slapping a 100-ruble, or $165, limit on the
value of consumer goods that travelers may carry out of the country
and a complete ban on exports of caviar and children's shoes from
Feb. 1 until the end of 1990, in attempt to shore up extreme short
supplies at home.
   But the deputy customs chief, Vitaly Boyarov, told a news
briefing today that purchases made with hard currency will be
exempted.
   That will allow the Soviet Union to continue earning scarce hard
currency by selling the best caviar, fur hats and coats, vodka and
souvenirs to foreigners in stores that require dollars, pounds, or
other freely convertible currency.
   The restrictions on export of consumer goods, particularly home
appliances, are directed primarily at citizens of other socialist
countries.
   Since November, Czechoslovakia, East Germany and Poland have
enacted similar laws to stop hordes of shoppers from neighboring
nations from stripping their shelves of items impossible to find at
home.
   None of the socialist countries of Eastern Europe has fully
convertible currencies, and they trade with each other based on
exchange rates that often do not cover the exporting country's cost
of production, much less bring a profit.
   Still, Boyarov denied descriptions in both the Soviet and Western
press that the reciprocal restrictions amount to a trade war. ``This
is not so,'' he said, ``because the restrictions do not cover
foreign trade.''
   He indicated the restrictions are aimed at halting the sale in
rubles of Soviet goods that purchasers can then sell for hard
currency.
   ``We are encouraging exports, but not exports at any price and
not those damaging Soviet citizens,'' he said.
   ``Our stores are empty and we have to take steps,'' he said.
   Customs analysis has shown that in the past 10 months, travelers
have left the Soviet Union hauling 200,000 washing machines and half
a million television sets, Boyarov said.
   This despite the fact that Soviet televisions earned a reputation
a few years ago for blowing up and setting apartments on fire.
   The Soviet Union manufactures just 7 million televisions a year
for its 284 million people.
   Boyarov also said foreign embassy workers have been abusing their
diplomatic privileges, with one such person taking ``1,400 irons,
several hundred freezers, 3.5 million bars of soap and an impressive
amount of detergent'' out of the country in nine months.
   Television sets have joined windshield wipers in the last few
months on the long list of ``deficit'' goods in the Soviet Union,
but consumers have been particularly irate over the complete absence
of soap and detergent. One furious consumer signed a letter to a
newspaper, ``the mother of two dirty children.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890105-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 0947EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceMisconduct     01-05 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Misconduct,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eighteen Los Angeles Police Officers Face Charges Of Misconduct</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen police officers have been accused of
misconduct for their part in an anti-gang raid in police allegedly
ransacked four apartments, roughed up residents and painted
anti-gang slogans, it was reported today.
   Investigators are also looking into allegations that the officers
were acting under what they assumed were orders from station Capt.
Thomas D. Elfmont to ``render the residences uninhabitable,'' the
Los Angeles Times reported.
   A quarter-gram of crack was seized in the Aug. 1 raid, which also
resulted in one drug charge and 33 people being taken into custody.
   Elfmont and Cmdr. William Booth, a police spokesman, declined to
comment on the case. Booth said the case had not been formally
reviewed by the department administration.
   The newspaper, citing unidentified sources, said seven officers
were ordered to appear before department tribunals. They could be
fired or suspended without pay.
   The 11 other officers are subject to lesser suspensions of up to
10 days or letters of reprimand, the newspaper reported.
   All are accused of violating departmental regulations ranging
from lying to investigators to excessive property damage, the Times
said.
   The district attorney's office is also investigating to determine
whether any officers should be prosecuted, the Times reported.
   The raid was carried out by more than 70 officers at four
tenement apartments, which had been targeted by the police anti-gang
task force following a series of gang-related, drive-by shootings.
   Officers obtained a warrant to search for drugs. But during the
raid they ripped plaster off walls, slashed furniture with knives,
destroyed toilets and sinks with sledgehammers and hacked apart
stereos, according to a lawsuit filed in federal court by about 40
people claiming their civil rights were violated.
   The lawsuit alleged that some of the officers spray-painted
anti-gang slogans and ``LAPD Rules'' on walls, and that some
residents taken to the station after the raid were ordered to
whistle the theme from the ``Andy Griffith Show'' and run a gauntlet
of officers beating them with fists.
   Those who didn't whistle were beaten with fists and steel
flashlights, the lawsuit charged.
   Damage to the apartments was so severe that the Red Cross offered
emergency housing to several residents.
   The police Internal Affairs Division, in a 668-page report, said
much of the damage attributed to the officers existed before the
raid or occurred afterward, but it determined that officers had
caused excessive damage.
</TEXT>
