<HEAD>Ms. Honors 6 As 1989's ``Women of the Year''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Ann Archer and talk show host Oprah
Winfrey were among six people honored today as Ms. magazine's Women
of the Year.
   The winners' ``determination, grit and guts inspire others and
have helped change our world,'' the magazine said.
   Archer was named for ``courageous pro-choice advocacy,'' and
Winfrey for ``her mission to expose black talent.''
   Sarah Brady, wife of former Reagan press secretary James Brady,
was honored for her stand against the powerful gun lobby. Her
husband was critically wounded in the 1981 assassination attempt on
President Reagan.
   The others honored were Marjory Stoneman Douglas, for a 60-year
battle to protect the Florida Everglades; ``Sweet Alice'' Harris,
for helping poverty-stricken children in Los Angeles' Watts section,
and Yolanda Serrano, for fighting AIDS among New York's drug addicts
and prostitutes.
   ``The six women Ms. salutes this year share one overwhelming
characteristic: they all are fighters, women determined to make a
difference,'' the magazine said.
