<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Afghans     01-05 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Afghans,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Cadets Go on New Year's Rampage; At Least Three Die, Paper
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan military cadets went on a New Year's Day
rampage in Tashkent, burning cars and smashing furniture in a
drunken and drug-fueled brawl that left an infant and two other
people dead, a newspaper said today.
   Komsomolskaya Pravda said 30 drunken Afghan cadets went to a
market in Tashkent to sell sunglasses, lighters and other items that
are hard to find in the Soviet Union.
   Soviets objected to Afghans becoming black marketeers and
fighting broke out when the Afghans began insulting the Soviets, the
paper said.
   Police rapidly intervened and sent the Afghans back to
dormitories around Tashkent where they live, it said.
   The Afghans gave their version of events to other Afghans living
in the dormitories, and they began smashing furniture and windows,
according to the newspaper account. Another group of Afghans, many
of whom had been taking drugs, smashed a traffic police post, the
paper said.
   The Afghans jumped on the hoods of passing cars and lay down on
the street, Komsomolskaya Pravda said. Twenty cars were vandalized
and four burned, according to preliminary information, the paper
said.
   Komsomolskaya Pravda, quoting a report printed in Uzbekistan
newspapers, said a 6-month-old child was killed ``as a result of the
rampages.'' It did not give details. Two people hurt in the rioting
died later of ``heavy trauma'' in the hospital, Komsomolskaya Pravda
said.
   Sixteen people, including seven Afghans, were reported
hospitalized, including one in critical condition.
   Friction has been reported before between Afghans and residents
of Tashkent, a city of 1.8 million that is the capital of the Uzbek
republic.
   Tashkent residents last year told visiting Western journalists
that some goods, such as tea kettles, had been taken off the market
because Afghans were buying them up and selling them for big profits
in their homeland.
   The paper expressed the hope that Soviet-Afghan relationship
would not be damaged by the incident. The Uzbek press report quoted
by Komsomolskaya Pravda said violators ``of Soviet laws and ethical
norms'' would be punished.
</TEXT>
