<FIRST>r a PM-SearsTower     01-05 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sears Tower,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sears Says Sale Of Tower Not In Sight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. has denied that a Japanese
real estate firm is close to buying the Sears Tower, the world's
tallest building.
   ``We are compiling a financial analysis, which is the first step
in the offering process. We are not involved in any negotiations at
this time,'' Sears said in a statement Wednesday.
   But Jack Barthell, managing partner of Kenneth Leventhal &amp; Co. of
Los Angeles, said his client, a Japanese real estate firm he would
not identify, was nearing a deal to buy the 110-story skyscraper for
about $1.2 billion.
   ``Because of the closeness of the deal, it's very sensitive,''
Barthell said.
   He said only that his owned high-profile buildings in other
cities and already has ``a presence in Chicago.''
   Sears announced Oct. 31 that it would sell the tower as part of a
restructuring plan. The giant retailing-and-financial-services
company has said it intends to keep its corporate headquarters in
the 15-year-old building.
   The tower, which rises 1,450 feet above downtown Chicago, is
expected to fetch a record price for a U.S. building, surpassing the
$660 million paid by Walter Shorenstein in 1985 for the Bank of
America Building in San Francisco.
   The building's value on the open market has been estimated at
$1.2 billion to $2 billion.
   Barthell's description prompted speculation that his client was
Shuwa Corp., a Japanese developer with more than $2 billion in U.S.
holdings, including ABC's New York headquarters, Arco Plaza in Los
Angeles and the Quaker Oats Tower in Chicago.
   But Scott Tagliarino, a spokesman in Los Angeles for Shuwa
Investment Corp., a Shuwa affiliate, said the company was not
negotiating to buy the Sears Tower.
