<FIRST>r w PM-CountdowntoCrisis 1stLd-Writethru a0444 01-05 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Countdown to Crisis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0444,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dogfight Is Escalation Of Drama Rooted In Chemical Arms Charge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Restores dropped matter in 2nd graf changing ``diplomat'' to
``diplomatic;'' Subs pvs 7th graf, ``On the,'' with 3 grafs to update with
report on Reagan against strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five-minute dogfight between U.S. and
Libyan fighters over the Mediterranean Sea climaxed a public drama
that began last October with charges by the CIA that Libya was
building a chemical weapons plant.
   Tension over the facility marks the latest chapter in a long
confrontation between America and Libya, a conflict U.S. officials
are trying to channel into a diplomatic campaign to close the plant,
which Libya denies makes chemical arms.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said Wednesday the U.S. F-14
Tomcat fighters shot at the Soviet-made Libyan MiG-23s in ``self
defense,'' and denied that the warplanes or their host aircraft
carrier, the USS John F. Kennedy, intended to attack the suspected
chemical plant.
   Nevertheless, statements by U.S. officials and the history of
U.S.-Libyan conflict triggered concern in Libya. Pentagon sources
said Libyan airplanes have been extremely active in recent days,
flying close to American reconnaissance and patrol planes.
   In the three months since CIA Deputy Director Robert Gates warned
of the Libyan plant, other U.S. officials have made progressively
more ominous noises. President Reagan said in an interview broadcast
last month that he could not rule out a military strike.
   ``That is a decision that has not been made yet,'' Reagan said on
Dec. 22. The next day President-elect Bush said he shared Reagan's
determination to prevent the reported Libyan plant from being used
``to spread further destruction.''
   After the incident, Reagan privately decided against a military
strike on the plant, according to unnamed administration officials
quoted in today's editions of The Washington Post.
   Reagan thought an attack could ``cause an international uproar''
and damage U.S. diplomatic efforts, including the campaign to curb
the proliferation of chemical weapons, according to the newspaper's
sources.
   But on the day before the dogfight over the Mediterranean, U.S.
officials speaking on condition of anonymity said they believed the
factory had already started production.
   Statements like those, and the announcement that the carrier USS
Teddy Roosevelt was leaving Norfolk, Va., on Dec. 30 on a routine
mission to the Mediterranean, fueled speculation of a possible
strike against the plant similar to the April 1986 bombing raid
against alleged terrorist training centers in Libya.
   Against that tense backdrop, the aircraft carrier Kennedy was
steaming east off the southern coast of Crete, 127 miles north of
Tobruk, Libya, at noon local time Wednesday (about 5 a.m. EST), with
two F-14s flying a routine combat patrol. The planes were
supplemented by an E-2C Hawkeye electronic warfare aircraft,
according to Pentagon officials.
   Carlucci said U.S. forces had conducted 12 similar maneuvers in
that area this year without incident.
   ``The MiG aircraft were detected shortly after they left Al
Bumbah (an airfield in northeast Libya) at 4:50 EST and were tracked
as they closed on the two F-14 aircraft,'' said Carlucci.
   The U.S. pilots, he added, ``maneuvered to avoid the closing
aircraft. They changed speed, altitude and direction.
   ``The Libyan aircraft continued to close in a hostile manner. At
about 14 miles, the U.S. section leader decided his aircraft was in
jeopardy and they could wait no longer. One MiG-23 was shot down
with a Sparrow missile. The second MiG was shot down by a Sidewinder
missile at six miles,'' he said.
   ``Each time, the Libyan aircraft sought to put their nose on our
aircraft. They also accelerated. So the hostile intent seems to be
fairly clear,'' he said.
   Carlucci said there was ``some preliminary information that
radars were turned on,'' indicating the Libyans were preparing to
fire. There was no evidence that the MiG-23s fired their AA-2 Atoll
air-to-air missiles, Pentagon sources said.
   Navy pilots spotted two parachutes in an area, well into
international waters 70 miles north of the Libya coast, and Libyan
ships and helicopters were seen conducting search and rescue
operations, officials said, although they did not know whether the
pilots survived.
   ``The 6th Fleet operation had no connection whatsoever with
Libya's newly constructed chemical facility. These operations were
conducted over 600 miles northeast'' of the facility, Carlucci said
at a Pentagon news briefing.
   ``We now consider this matter closed,'' he said.
</TEXT>
