<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Trotsky     01-05 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Trotsky,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Stalin Ordered Trotsky Assassination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet newspaper has publicly agreed with Western
historians' longstanding assertion that former Soviet leader Josef
Stalin ordered the assassination of fellow revolutionary and rival
Leon Trotsky.
   Literaturnaya Gazeta on Wednesday published a full-page article
on Trotsky, a leader of the Russian revolution in 1917 who came to
oppose Stalin and Vladimir Lenin.
   Historian N. Vasertzky got to the point five paragraphs from the
end:
   ``Stalin couldn't forget past offenses and outrages. Being
convinced that Trotsky was no longer needed, he apparently either
took the decision himself or let the decision be known to the people
around him: With Trotsky, `it's time to finish him,''' the paper
said.
   Many Soviets are aware of the Western belief that Stalin ordered
his rival's assassination, and a Soviet play and the official
newspaper Pravda have hinted at the same conclusion.
   An article last summer in Pravda titled, ``Demon of the
Revolution'' came closest, saying Stalin's aide Lavrenty Beria
carried out Stalin's wish to kill Trotsky and that he was promoted
to deputy prime minister for security shortly thereafter in 1941.
   The Literaturnaya Gazeta article quoted the original Pravda
account of Trotsky's death from 1940, which called him ``an
imperialist spy'' who was ``killed by his own allies.'' The original
account also named the assassin as Jack Morten Vandendreich, when it
was actually Ramon del Rio Merkader, Literaturnaya Gazeta charged.
   But the newspaper did not say that Merkader, a Spaniard, spent
his old age in Moscow, drawing a Soviet pension. He died in Havana
of cancer in 1978.
   Trotsky started his opposition to Lenin in the early 1900s,
saying Lenin's ideas would result in a one-party dictatorship. But
following the February revolution in 1917, he joined up with Lenin
to take power from the Provisional Government in the October
Revolution. He served as a member of the ruling Politburo from 1919
to 1927, but lost a power struggle with Stalin and was exiled.
   Stalin reviled Trotsky as a traitor and used his alleged
anti-Soviet plot as an excuse for bloody purges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
