<FIRST>u i PM-Flight103 2ndLd-Writethru a0531 01-05 0737</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0531,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lockerbie Buries One of its Own</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with emergency air security meeting,
second funeral. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``In these...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than two weeks after the crash of
Pan Am Flight 103, Lockerbie today buried two of its own, a
10-year-old girl whose parents are still among the missing and an
81-year-old widow.
   Air security chiefs, meanwhile, held an emergency meeting to
discuss the bombing of the jumbo jet.
   The National Aviation Security Committee, which was to have met
in February, changed schedule and gathered at a secret venue ``to
discuss the implications'' of the Dec. 21 crash, the Transport
Department said.
   The committee is headed by a department official and includes
police, airline and airport representatives. It was expected to
explore ways of tightening security at British airports following
the conclusion that a bomb blew up aboard the Boeing 747, killing
all 259 people aboard.
   Another 11 died on the ground, only three of whom have been
located.
   The first to be buried Thursday was 10-year-old Joanne Flannigan,
whose parents are missing and presumed dead. Her funeral was
followed by that of Mary Lancaster, an 81-year-old widow, at All
Saints Anglican Church.
   Joanne's funeral service at the Holy Trinity Roman Catholic
Church was even simpler than a memorial service held Wednesday for
all the victims.
   Rev. Patrick Keegans told a congregation of several hundred
mourners that death is harsh and bitter ``even in normal
circumstances.''
   ``In these circumstances it is almost unbearable and
unbelievable,'' he said.
   There was no music, except for the unaccompanied singing of two
hymns, ``Abide With Me'' and ``The Lord is My Shepherd.'' Only two
sprays of white flowers adorned the church, although the hearse
carrying the girl's coffin was covered with bright floral bouquets
and wreaths.
   Keegans prayed not only for Joanne, but also for her parents Tom
and Kathleen who are missing and presumed dead.
   Her 14-year-old brother Stephen survived the disaster because he
was at a neighbor's garage repairing his sister's bicycle. An older
brother, David, 20, who was living away from home, returned for the
funeral.
   The Flannigans and all the others who died in Lockerbie lived on
Sherwood Crescent, where the jet's fuel-filled wings landed.
   Officials have said they believe some of the missing passengers
and townspeople might have been cremated in the fiery crash which
left a 30-foot-deep crater in the town.
   On Wednesday, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, U.S. Ambassador
Charles Price and Pan Am executives joined relatives of the dead and
other townspeople in the Dryfesdale Parish Church of the Church of
Scotland.
   No members of Britain's royal family attended the service,
prompting headlines of ``Where Were the Royals?'' in both The Sun
and the Daily Mirror, Britain's two largest circulation newspapers.
   ``Fury as Family Snubs Lockerbie Memorial,'' added The Sun.
   A Daily Express columnist, Jean Rook, wrote: ``At a time of
national mourning, we rightly and naturally turn to our queen for
the lead ... Broken-hearted Britain watching TV needed to see their
equally grieving monarch.''
   Buckingham Palace said Queen Elizabeth II does not attend
memorial services or funerals and that it was a personal decision
for other members of the royal family whether to attend. The queen
and others did send representatives to the service.
   After the Dryfesdale church's 700 seats were filled, others stood
outside in the rain-soaked graveyard listening to the prayers on
loudspeakers, and more than 1,000 watched the service on
closed-circuit television in other halls.
   The Right Rev. James Whyte, the moderator or leader of the Church
of Scotland, warned in his sermon against seeking revenge for the
bombing.
   ``Justice yes. Retaliation no,'' Whyte said. ``We may be tempted,
indeed urged by some, to flex our muscles in response, to show that
we are men.''
   ``To show that we are what? To show that we are prepared to let
more young and more innocent die, to let more rescue workers labor
in more wreckage to find the grisly proof, not of our virility, but
of our inhumanity. That is what retaliation means.''
   ``I, for one, will have none of it, and I hope you will not
either,'' Whyte said.
   Searchers have recovered 242 of the dead. As of Wednesday, 149
bodies had been identified _ three of Lockerbie residents _ and
released to relatives for burial.
</TEXT>
