<FIRST>r a PM-ImmigrantDrowning     01-05 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Immigrant Drowning,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials: Illegal Aliens Drowned In Attempt To Cross Niagara River</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Asian women and their two children
apparently drowned in the fast-moving Niagara River while trying to
enter the United States illegally in a rubber raft, federal
authorities said today.
   The four may have been provided with the boat by smugglers, said
Benedict Ferro, district director of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service in Buffalo.
   ``These people didn't have a chance in the world,'' said Ronald
McNamee of the New York State parks police.
   The body of one of the women, an Asian in her 30s, was recovered
Tuesday afternoon in Youngstown, about 10 miles north of Niagara
Falls.
   The victim was believed to have been accompanied by another woman
and two children, ages 13 and 7, who were missing and presumed
drowned, officials said. Authorities searched the river and Lake
Ontario for the three today.
   McNamee said officials learned of the accident after a tipster
called and said four people he was supposed to meet in the United
States didn't show up.
   ``It's hazardous enough to try to cross the river then (in
summer),'' Ferro said. ``The water out there is cold and the strong
currents are unpredictable.''
   The temperature early Tuesday when the four are believed to have
started their trek was near zero.
   Ferro said all four were believed to be from Malaysia.
   ``We think this may be part of a major alien smuggling ring,'' he
said. Ferro said 11 people were caught trying to use rubber rafts to
cross the Niagara from Ontario to New York state last summer.
   The ring is believed to smuggle illegal aliens from Hong Kong to
Vancouver, and then through Toronto and St. Catharines into the
United States for $2,000 each, McNamee said.
   A purse, two suitcases and the raft were found by the Coast Guard
on Tuesday, McNamee said. The purse contained a Malaysian passport,
he said.
</TEXT>
