<HEAD>Man Allegedly Shot Man So Passenger Could Go To Bathroom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who witnesses said wanted to make
freeway traffic move faster so one of his passengers could get to a
bathroom has been charged in the shooting death Dec. 3 of another
motorist.
   Darryl Ray Poole, 19, was held without bail today on charges of
murder and firing into an occupied vehicle in the slaying of
Lawrence Ellingsen, 53.
   An anonymous tip led to Poole's arrest Dec. 30, police said.
Police initially thought it was a random bullet that pierced the
rear window of Ellingsen's car and hit him in the head.
   Poole had four passengers in his car and was driving behind the
Ellingsen and his wife, Sherri, according to police.
   The passengers said he told them he was ``going to make traffic
speed up'' because one of them had to go to the bathroom, said Sgt.
Dan Voznik.
   Poole fired a single shot from a rifle but did nothing beforehand
to indicate to the Ellingsens that he wanted them to go faster,
Voznik said.
   Mrs. Ellingsen took control of the car and steered it to the side
of the road as her husband slumped over the wheel.
   ``To shoot at someone going 60 to 65 miles an hour because
someone had to go to the bathroom? I just can't imagine what kind of
people we're dealing with,'' she said Tuesday.
