<FIRST>r a PM-MinersKilled 1stLd-Writethru a0471 01-05 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miners Killed, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0471,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Miners Killed In Roof Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XLDN1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with government saying it is worst
such collapse in 2{ years, ADD identity of fourth miner. PICKS UP 8th graf
pvs, `A dozen ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLESBORO, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cave-in nearly a half mile inside a
coal mine killed three miners in the nation's worst such accident in
2{ years, authorities said. A fourth miner escaped unharmed.
   The cave-in occurred as the men were removing coal about 2,400
feet into the mine near this southwest Kentucky city Wednesday
afternoon, said Willard Stanley, commissioner of the state
Department of Mines and Minerals.
   Rescue teams began digging toward the men within 20 minutes of
the collapse, said Ronnie McDowell, an instructor with the
department in Harlan.
   By midday today, the last of the bodies had been pulled from the
Cumberland Valley Contractors No. 2 mine. Killed were Steve
Bradburn, 36, of Harrogate, Tenn., Joe Ditty, 32, of Harlan, and
Tony Osborne, 31, of Tazwell, Tenn.
   Ditty was the brother of mine co-owner Stanley Ditty, Stanley
said.
   A fourth miner, Roger Wilder, 36, of Cubbage, escaped unharmed
after the collapse, Stanley said.
   ``The last time there was an accident in which more than one coal
miner was killed occurred'' July 9, 1986, near Waltonville, Ill.,
said Kathy Snyder, a spokeswoman for U.S. Mine Safety and Health
Administration in Arlington, Va.
   ``That was also a roof-fall accident in which three people were
killed.''
   Stanley said his department would begin an investigation Friday
on why the roof collapsed. The Mine Safety and Health Administration
also will send investigators, agency spokesman Sam Stafford said in
Washington.
   A dozen people work per shift, mining a 48-inch seam at the mine,
the agency said.
   The mine had no fatalities or serious injuries in 1988 and no
violations involving roof regulations, officials said.
   Kentucky reported only one roof-fall death last year, down from
15 in 1987. The number nationally declined to eight, down from 19
the year before.
   Officials attributed the improved safety record to greater
awareness by miners of the dangers of roof falls and to the
increased use of automated roof-support systems.
</TEXT>
