<HEAD>Subsidized Route Averages One Passenger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government spent $379,000 last year to
subsidize flights between Atlanta and Moultrie that averaged one
passenger.
   The Department of Transportation is trying to stop the subsidy to
Eastern Atlantis Express' service connecting the southern Georgia
city with Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport.
   The flight, with two pilots, makes two trips each way, six days a
week, but sold just 1,301 tickets, at $79 one way, last year.
   David Howard, a vice president of the commuter airline, which is
affiliated with Eastern Airlines, said the route will be eliminated
if the subsidy ends.
   The airline is required by law to maintain the route in exchange
for the subsidy, a carryover from the days when the government
regulated domestic routes.
