<FIRST>u i PM-Gulf-Ship 1stLd-Writethru a0567 01-05 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gulf-Ship, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0567,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saudi Tanker Ablaze, Eight Crew Members Missing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with background, details, second incident. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Saudi Arabian tanker caught in a storm
in the southern Persian Gulf was ablaze in the Strait of Hormuz
today with eight of its crewmen missing, shipping executives
reported.
   The executives identified the vessel as the 36,904-ton Saghera,
manned by a 34-member crew of Greek officers and Sri Lankan seamen.
   The Omani navy rescued 26 crew members in lifeboats but eight
remained unaccounted for, the executives said. They spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The London-based Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit, which
monitors maritime traffic around the world, said the vessel caught
fire just outside Omani territorial waters before the bend of the
Hormuz, gateway to the gulf.
   Lloyd's said the vessel was reported to be abandoned and no
further details were available.
   The shipping executives said winds gusting to 35 mph caused waves
as high as 30 feet in the southern gulf and the Strait of Hormuz.
   It was not immediately known what started the fire aboard the
Sagheera or where the ship was headed.
   Lloyds said a two-mile oil slick had formed, indicating the
vessel may have been carrying a cargo of fuel.
   The shipping executives ruled out the possibility of an attack by
an Iranian speedboat, saying the weather was too bad for speedboats
to operate in the gulf.
   They said high seas had prevented patrol boats and salvage
vessels from approaching the Sagheera to put out the fire.
   The Sagheera is managed by Avin International Bunkers Supply SA,
based in Piraeus, Greece, LLoyd's said.
   On April 4, when the Iran-Iraq war was still raging, Iranian
gunboats attacked the Sagheera, setting it afire near the Strait of
Hormuz.
   On that occasion, the fire was put out and none of the crew was
injured. It was not known whether the same crew was still aboard the
tanker.
   The Strait of Hormuz was a major area for the so-called ``tanker
war,'' an offshoot of the Iran-Iraq war during which 546 commercial
vessels of different nationalities were attacked by either side.
   Iran and Iraq accepted a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire in August.
   Earlier today, bad weather forced the Moajil-5, a small
Honduran-flagged freighter, to run aground after it broke anchor in
the rough seas, sources in the gulf and in London said. No
casualties were reported.
   A salvage tug, the Smit Sumatera, answered a distress call from
the 9,724-ton freighter as it drifted off Sharjah during the night.
But the tug could not get close enough to help and the Moajil-5
grounded on the jetty of Sharjah harbor, Lloyds said.
   The Moajil-5, one of several ships trapped in Iraq's gulf port of
Umm Qasr during the war, was formerly managed by the Kuwait-based
United Arab Shipping Co.
</TEXT>
