<HEAD>Soviet General Acknowledges Libya May Have Chemical Weapons Capability</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Foreign Ministry comment on shootdown,
CORRECT official's name to Nikita Smidovich sted Nikolai Smedovich. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet general today gave his country's first
acknowledgement that Libya may be able to manufacture chemical
weapons, but said they would be in quantities too small for waging
war.
   As recently as Wednesday night, state-run Radio Moscow rejected
as ``groundless'' U.S. charges that Libya has built a chemical
weapons plant south of Tripoli.
   A spokesman for the Soviet Foreign Ministry, meanwhile, said news
of the confrontation Wednesday in which U.S. Navy jets shot down two
Libyan fighters above the Mediterranean was received with
``indignation'' in Moscow.
   Libya's ambassador to Rome linked the incident to U.S. charges
that his country had built a chemical weapons plant about 60 miles
southwest of Tripoli.
   In an interview last month, President Reagan said he could not
rule out a military strike on the plant, which Libya says makes
pharmaceuticals.
   U.S. officials in Washington, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Tuesday they believe the Libyan plant has already begun
production.
   Lt. Gen. Anatoly Kuntsevich, deputy chief of Soviet chemical
weapons troops, told reporters in Moscow today that ``Libya doesn't
have the industrial capacity to make toxic agents in sufficient
quantities to conduct warfare.
   ``But as far as a few kilograms of toxic agents goes, any serious
chemical laboratory in the world can make several kilos, say one to
five kilos (2.2 to 11 pounds), of toxic agents.''
   Kuntsevich spoke at a news briefing called to discuss a five-day
international conference on chemical weapons that begins Saturday in
Paris. Secretary of State George P. Shultz plans to use the meeting
to try to persuade more that 100 nations to impose sanctions on
countries that use poison gas.
   Asked if an attack on the Libyan plant at Rabta could pose a
danger to the more than 820,000 residents of Tripoli by releasing
toxic agents, Kuntsevich said, ``As far as I know, this is a
pharmaceutical plant. If there is an attack, there would be much
physical destruction.''
   ``If they use chemical substances, there would be some harm to
the local population,'' the two-star general added. ``But as far as
I know, this is not a large plant, and so there would be no danger
for residents of the capital.''
   The Tass news agency quoted Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman
Gennady I. Gerasimov as saying: ``News that Washington's anti-Libyan
campaign had produced an armed clash over the Mediterranean, as a
result of which two Libyan planes were brought down, has been
received with indignation in Moscow.''
   It said Gerasimov called U.S. actions ``a show of political
adventurism and state terrorism.''
   Gerasimov said the Soviet Union was not asked to help Libya and
did not increase its state of military readiness.
   Kuntsevich said Soviet Chemical Weapons Forces, which the
Pentagon says number between 45,000 and 60,000 troops, do not send
advisers to other countries, and thus have none in Libya.
   In 1987, the Soviet Union acknowledged for the first time that it
possesses chemical weapons, and said its stocks of toxic agents do
not exceed 50,000 tons. Western military specialists estimate Soviet
chemical weapons stocks at between 300,000 and 700,000 tons, figures
Kuntsevich called ``a myth.''
   Nikita Smidovich, a Foreign Ministry official, told the briefing
his country will propose in Paris that U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar be empowered to conduct an investigation as soon as
information about the use of chemical weapons is received.
   The 1925 Geneva Protocol under review in Paris bans the use of
chemical weapons, but does not outlaw their production, and has no
enforcement mechanism.
   Smidovich indicated the Kremlin will resist any attempt to
transform the Paris meeting into a forum to condemn Libya or any
other single nation.
   The Soviets are seeking an agreement that calls for all nations,
including the superpowers, to liquidate chemical weapons stocks over
a 10-year period.
   The United States ceased manufacture of such weapons in 1969, but
resumed 17 years later on the grounds the Soviets and other
potential adversaries have chemical weapons stocks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
