<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1211EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-PSACrash     01-05 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PSA Crash,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>NTSB Blames Shooting for Airliner Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Transportation Safety Board ruled
officially today that the 1987 crash of a Pacific Southwest Airlines
jet was caused by an attack by a gun-wielding passenger.
   PSA Flight 1771 crashed Dec. 7, l987 about l75 miles northwest of
Los Angeles, killing all 43 people aboard, including a former USAir
employee who had opened fire with a revolver in a revenge attack
aimed at a former supervisor who also was on board.
   Authorities within weeks of the crash disclosed that the former
airline employee, David Burke, had smuggled a .44-caliber Magnum
revolver through a security checkpoint at Los Angeles International
Airport when boarding the flight to San Francisco.
   A cockpit recorder tape from the plane included gunshots in or
near the cockpit, according to the NTSB. The board said in a brief
summary of findings that the tape revealed ``the sounds of a scuffle
and several shots which were apparently fired in or near the
cockpit.''
   It has been presumed that both the pilot and co-pilot likely were
shot.
   According to the NTSB findings, the official probable cause for
the accident were ``interference'' and ``intentional sabotage'' by
an emotionally distraught passenger.
   The safety board cited as contributing factors inadequate
security and inadequate operatoring procedures by the airline that
permitted Burke to bypass security at the Los Angeles airport
because of his previous employment.
   The accident prompted the Federal Aviation Administration to
order a tightening of security measures taken at passenger
checkpoints so that there is a closer scrutiny of airline and
airport employees.
   In an action that grew out of the PSA accident, the FAA on
Wednesday announced a final regulation aimed at tightening access to
restricted areas of an airport by the use of computerized
identification badges. Such badges would make an ID card ineffective
if it is reported stolen or if a person leaves employment without
returning the badge.
   Investigators have said Burke was believed to have still had his
USAir identification badge at the time he boarded Flight 1771.
   According to the PSA investigation, it is believed Burke was able
to avoid detection of his revolver because he bypassed normal
passenger security checks after being recognized as a former airline
employee. PSA was a subsidiary of USAir Corp. at the time of the
accident and since has merged completely into USAir.
   The NTSB confirmed previous reports that Burke had left a
``goodbye'' message with friends and boarded Flight 1771 with the
intention of killing his former supervisor at USAir. The board said
a note written by Burke and found in the wreckage threatened the
supervisor.
   The revolver and six expended rounds were also found in the
wreckage, the board said.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890105-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1213EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Libya-USPilots 3rdLd-Writethru a0575-a0580-a0582 01-05
0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya-US Pilots, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0575-a0580-a0582,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>United States Accuses Libya of Lying, Cites Photographic Evidence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States today accused Libya of lying
to the world community and said it had photographic evidence that
the two MiG jet fighters shot down Wednesday were armed and
approaching Navy jets with hostile intent.
   A Navy intelligence review of videotape shot by one of the F-14
Tomcat jets ``tells me that the Libyan ambassador to the U.N. is a
liar. That's the first thing it tells me,'' said Dan Howard, the
Pentagon's chief spokesman.
   ``They've gone out yesterday and said repeatedly that those were
unarmed reconnaissance aircraft. Well, we have the pictures now that
they were not unarmed aircraft,'' Howard told a news briefing.
   ``They were obviously armed aircraft with obvious hostile intent.
We believe that our aircraft commanders behaved in a prudent manner
in defending themselves, in defending their aircraft and in
defending their ship,'' he said.
   Howard said one of the Navy jets' two-man air crews had been
flown to Washington overnight and brought the video footage shot by
the jet's target camera.
   Debriefing of the two officers and a review of the video footage
shows the MiG-23 Flogger aircraft ignored evasive maneuvers by the
Navy jets five times and kept turning toward the Americans, Howard
said.
   Even after the lead F-14 had fired two Sparrow missiles, the two
MiGs did not break off their approach, he said, but turned and tried
to jump on the second F-14, the spokesman said.
   The first two Sparrows apparently did not strike their target.
But a third Sparrow fired by the second F-14 claimed one of the
MiGs, and the lead F-14 pounced on the rear of the other MiG and
downed it with a heat-seeking Sidewinder missile, Howard said.
   By the time the confrontation was over, the planes had come as
close as 1.5 miles of each other, he said.
   The American pilots did not have any indication that the Libyans
had turned on their attack radars, he said. But intercepted radio
communications show the Libyans had some type of radar on their
planes operating and searching for the F-14s, Howard said.
   Given the manner in which the Libyans were flying, the American
pilots did not need evidence of a radar ``lock-on'' to know that
they were in danger, Howard added.
   In offering other details on the confrontation, Howard said:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Wednesday's confrontation was ``peculiar'' in several respects,
not the least being that the two Libyan fighters did not report back
to their ground controllers that the American jets had ``locked on''
them with their own radars at a range of 72 miles.
   That is a normal procedure used by Navy pilots to warn away other
planes. Always in the past, Howard said, when a Libyan pilot knew he
was locked on, he would report that and then be directed to return
home. The closest previous approach by a Libyan fighter was 30 miles.
   _No effort was made by the Americans to communicate by radio with
the Libyans. The F-14s did not have compatible radio equipment, and
the E-2C radar sentry plane that was also airborne did not try.
There was not enough time to make such an attempt, and such tries at
radio communication are not standard procedure when dealing with
Libya.
   From takeoff to shoot down, the entire incident lasted only eight
minutes, Howard said.
   ``Frankly, we're still scratching our heads as to why Libya did
this,'' he said.
   _The Pentagon has not ordered any special alert status for its
forces around the world. The aircraft carrier Kennedy, from which
the F-14s flew, is now long out of range of Libya and proceeding
toward a port call.
   _The Pentagon still has no information on the fate of the two
Libyan pilots. Two parachutes were spotted, as was a Libyan
search-and-rescue helicopter, but there is no confirmation as yet
that the two Libyans were fished from the water.
</TEXT>
