<FIRST>r a PM-BlindAssault     01-05 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blind Assault,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charges Dropped Against Blind Man Who Assaulted Police Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORANGE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charges have been dismissed against a blind
man accused of assaulting two police officers during a late-night
walk.
   Municipal Judge Gary P. Ryan on Wednesday granted the
prosecutor's request to dismiss the charges against 27-year-old
Daniel Serrano, saying, ``How can Mr. Serrano assault someone if he
is blind?''
   Serrano spent 16 days in jail before being released last month.
He was charged with assaulting an officer and resisting arrest, both
misdemeanors, after he and a friend were confronted by four officers
on a street Nov. 23.
   The friend, Roy DeHerrera, 26, was wanted on a traffic warrant.
   Serrano, a student the Braille Institute in Anaheim, contended
that police attacked him and DeHerrera without warning. He said he
was knocked to the ground and bitten by a police dog.
   Police said DeHerrera attacked one of the uniformed officers and
Serrano joined in, jumping on one officer's back and throwing
punches at another.
   Deputy District Attorney Sandy Mitchell said the last-minute
request to dismiss charges was based on an ophthalmologist's
verifying that Serrano lost his vision two years ago when he
suffered a gunshot wound.
   Prosecutors also discovered police didn't identify themselves to
the blind man.
   DeHerrera still faces assault charges. His trial began Wednesday.
</TEXT>
