<FIRST>r a PM-Killer'sChildren     01-05 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Killer's Children,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Ruling Granting Custody of Children To Man Who Killed
Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELGIN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Illinois Appellate Court has allowed a man
who strangled his wife in front of their two daughters to retain
custody of the children.
   No law or prior case supported overruling a lower-court decision
granting custody to James Lutgen, 34, of East Dubuque, the
three-judge panel said in a decision issued last week.
   ``I'm glad to have my children home for good now,'' Lutgen said
of his daughters, Tracy, 12, and Dana, 10. ``I know that I'm a good
parent.''
   ``Just because somebody does something wrong'' doesn't mean he
should lose custody of his children permanently, he said.
   Lutgen pleaded guilty to manslaughter in the 1984 death of his
26-year-old wife, Carol, and was released in 1986 after serving 13
months of a four-year sentence.
   The sisters witnessed the fight between their parents that
resulted in Mrs. Lutgen's death.
   The appeals court ruled that except for his wife's death, Lutgen
had ``an unblemished record.''
   The victim's brother, Gene Tranel of Eldridge, Iowa, had sought
to prevent the girls from being turned over to their father. Tranel
took them in when Lutgen was arrested.
   Tranel said he is not sure if can afford to appeal the case to
the Illinois Supreme Court.
   ``The court system and now even the appellate system has failed
to protect battered women and innocent victims,'' Tranel said. ``It
appears the courts are not willing to deal with domestic violence.''
</TEXT>
