<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Girl     01-05 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Girl,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>3-Year-Old Evades Airport Security, Boards Plane to See Grandmother</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 3-year-old girl who wanted to see her
grandmother in London got on an airport bus, toddled through Israeli
security and passport checks, and boarded a Europe-bound flight
before being discovered, her father said.
   Graham Hodson confirmed newspaper accounts published Thursday
about the adventure by his daughter, Candy, 10 days ago at the Uvda
Air Force base, which is used for tourist flights between Europe and
the Red Sea resort of Eilat.
   ``We were quite surprised, but not that surprised, because she's
done these kind of things before. She's really quite independent,''
said Hodson, a guitarist from Liverpool, England.
   Candy slipped away from her father in the lobby of a large hotel
where Hodson's rock group ``Shazam'' has been playing.
   She boarded a charter bus with a group of departing tourists, and
the English-language Jerusalem Post said she did not attract
attention because she was one of many blond children.
   ``Apparently she was befriended by a woman on the bus who gave
her some chewing gum. Everybody stuffed her with sweets,'' Hodson
said.
   At the airport, ``she got by all the security checks, because we
travel a lot and she's familiar with airports, and she finds it a
lot of fun,'' he said.
   Candy wound up on a charter flight bound for Copenhagen, Denmark.
Her presence was discovered only after the plane was readying for
takeoff.
   ``There was a passenger screaming to get on the plane, and they
started checking whether there was someone aboard without a
ticket,'' Hodson said.
   Candy said nothing. She was seated between two strangers and each
thought she belonged to the other. The Jerusalem Post said she was
picked up and taken from passenger to passenger. No one claimed her.
   ``They took her off the plane crying,'' Hodson said.
   Candy was asleep by the time a taxi brought her back to the hotel
five hours after she disappeared.
   The next morning ``she mumbled to us that she (had) wanted to
visit her grandmother. We told her off, but we couldn't really
discipline her,'' Hodson said, adding he and his wife searched the
resort grounds and a nearby beach for three hours before airport
security officials called the hotel.
   After initially being upset by lax security, Hodson decided to
take the incident with a sense of humor.
   It wasn't her first sign of wanderlust. When she was two, Candy,
wandered without clothes about a mile away from her home in Tenerife
in the Canary Islands.
   ``She reached the supermarket. She took a baby bottle with
chocolate and a bag of crisps (potato chips). She's getting to be
famous for her independence,'' said Hodson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
