<HEAD>British Rail to Pay 10,000 Pounds Compensation for Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Rail will pay about $18,000 in immediate
compensation to relatives of the 34 people killed in last month's
Clapham rail crash, officials said Thursday.
   The sum would be given in advance of consideration for other
possible compensation awards following the Dec. 12 disaster, said a
spokesman for the state-run rail service.
   ``In many cases, this payment for bereavement will be only part
of the overall compensation paid,'' said the spokesman.
   British Rail also offered families $3,600 in hardship
compensation immediately following the triple-train crash in south
London.
   The morning rush-hour crash injured more than 100 people and
killed 33 others outright. Another victim died later of injuries.
   British Rail said that improperly installed signal equipment
during a modernization of signals probably caused the accident, but
is still investigating.
