<FIRST>r a AM-SkaterConvicted     01-05 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skater Convicted,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Convicts First Person Of Violating Anti-Skating Ordinance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Skating on Houston streets can be expensive: It
cost one Urban Animals club member $50 in fines, and officials said
more busts of skateboarders and roller skaters are planned.
   ``It's a dumb law,'' said Alex Siegel, foreman of the Municipal
Court jury that on Wednesday convicted Kenneth William Hessler for
illegal skating. ``We found him guilty because that's what the law
says.''
   The maximum fine for skating on city streets is $200 under a
20-year-old ordinance.
   ``I think our police officers have more important things to do
than enforce this law,'' said Councilman Dale Gorczynski. ``I'd
rather see them busting crack houses.''
   But city officials say this was the first in what is expected to
be a flurry of such trials, including another one for Hessler for
allegedly skating in the street on Halloween.
   Most defendants are part of a loose-knit group called the Urban
Animals, who have skated on downtown streets since 1978.
   John McKay, owner of the Montrose Skate Shop and a member of the
Urban Animals, said the group will continue skating downtown and
hopes any future confrontations will help result in a change in the
ordinance. The group skates mostly downtown, but it is illegal to
skate on streets any place in the city.
   Hundreds of the skaters petitioned City Council in 1987 to let
them ride on streets similar to bicyclists. Council, however, said
skaters pose a threat to themselves on the streets.
</TEXT>
