<FIRST>r a AM-BombHoax     01-05 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bomb Hoax,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Hoax Keeps Police Up All Night</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DELPHI, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a traveling salesman parked his camper
at a restaurant overnight, he had no idea it would keep police up
all night worrying it was filled with explosives.
   Police got a call Tuesday night from someone who said the camper
``had enough explosives to blow away a whole city block,'' Police
Chief Dick Roe said. ``This is small-town America. We don't get
calls like that here.''
   The parking lot was emptied and blocked off. Two airmen from
Grissom Air Force Base arrived with a dog trained to sniff for
explosives. State police, Carroll County sheriff's deputies and the
Porter County Sheriff's Department bomb squad also arrived to help.
   Donald Wright of Traverse City, Mich., had gotten approval from
an assistant manager at the Hardee's restaurant to leave the
Airstream camper overnight and then drove his truck into Lafayette
to visit friends.
   As the dog tried to get a scent for explosives, police finally
tracked Wright through his home to his friends in Lafayette. He
returned to Hardee's about 9:30 a.m. Wednesday.
   ``I couldn't believe it. The only thing I could think of was that
it must be some misidentification. I fully expected to see my
trailer blown apart, the way the Traverse police described it to
me,'' he said.
   ``When I got here, someone told me the police had thought about
drilling a hole to unlock it. I started to give my keys to the
police, but they said, `No, you do it.'''
   The bomb hoax canceled breakfast at Hardee's. Usually open at
5:30 a.m., the restaurant didn't serve its first customer until 10
a.m. Wednesday.
   ``We don't have any suspects,'' Roe said.
</TEXT>
