<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Belgium-Guns     01-05 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Belgium-Guns,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Belgium Restricts Arms Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced Thursday it
will restrict the sales of riot guns, sawed-off shotguns and other
modified guns it said are ``too dangerous, too widely sold and cause
too many deaths.''
   A decree to be published Friday will submit the sales of these
weapons to a police authorization.
   Another decree, also to be published Friday, will make it
compulsory for people who already own these weapons to register them
with police before May 1.
   Penalties for ignoring the restrictions will range from one month
to one year jail or a fine from about $162 to $8,100.
   Justice Minister Melchior Wathelet, while announcing the new
regulations, said they would not solve all problems, but he said he
would propose to the government very soon an additional restriction
in the arms trade.
   A spokeswoman for Wathelet said this would apply to .22-caliber
rifles, sports guns held responsible for many deadly accidents.
   So far, only the sales and possession of war guns and handguns
were restricted in Belgium. When all regulations will have been
changed, only the sales of shotguns will be left unrestricted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
