<DOCNO> AP890105-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Libya-Journalists     01-05 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya-Journalists,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libya Turns Back Nearly 30 Journalists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 30 journalists who flew to Libya
after U.S. warplanes shot down two Libyan fighter jets over the
Mediterranean Sea were detained at Tripoli airport today, then sent
back to Rome.
   Earlier today, residents fleeing Tripoli reportedly jammed gas
stations and troops fortified the home of Col. Moammar Gadhafi after
his government claimed the downing of the Libyan jets on Wednesday
was a prelude to a major attack.
   U.S. officials said two armed Libyan jets were downed after they
approached two Navy fighters with hostile intent. The Libyans said
its planes were unarmed and on a reconnaissance flight when they
were fired upon for no reason.
   At least one of reporters turned back at Tripoli airport today
had been invited to Libya by a government official.
   The journalists, who arrived from Rome, spent about 1{ hours
inside the airport terminal before being put back on the flight.
   The regularly scheduled Alitalia flight carried about 30
journalists, mostly Europeans, and other passengers, including
businessmen and Libyan citizens. The flight left Rome at 12:05 p.m.,
two hours behind schedule, and landed in Tripoli at 1:45 p.m.
   Libyan officials gathered the passports of all the journalists
and led them into a room in the arrival area.
   About 15 or 20 minutes later, the journalists were told they were
being sent back to Rome and they were asked to present their baggage
checks so their luggage could be identified and put back on the
flight.
   One Libyan in civilian clothes who wouldn't identify himself said
repeatedly in Italian, ``If you don't have a visa, you can't stay.
You must go back to Rome.''
   The only reporter allowed in was a correspondent for the Italian
news agency ANSA. The agency has an arrangement with Libya which
allows its correspondent to enter the country whenever he wants, and
the reporter visits Libya several times a year.
   Libya officially requires a visa from Americans and Western
Europeans, but sometimes journalists have been allowed in without
visas, including an Associated Press reporter in April 1988.
   On Wednesday, the Associated Press office in Rome received a
telex from Ali Maria, the head of the Information Ministry division
which deals with foreign press, telling the news agency its reporter
was welcome to come to Libya.
   The AP reporter showed the telex, written in English, to at least
half a dozen Libyans in civilian clothes at the airport but to no
avail.
   One official agreed to telephone Ali Maria, but the man came back
a short time later and said, ``There's nothing to be done.''
   Alitalia officials and Libyans ordered the journalists to get
back on the plane, but the reporters protested for about 45 minutes.
   Finally, with the help of two unarmed Libyans in army fatigues,
the journalists were led back onto the plane. An Italian newspaper
reporter, who has been to Libya before and was particularly
insistent about entering the country, was pushed by Libyan airport
officials.
   The plane returned to Rome and landed at about 5 p.m.
   An aide to Ali Maria, contacted by phone from Rome at the
ministry office, said, ``We have stopped letting in journalists. We
have 200 journalists now.''
   He indicated that they, too, would be sent back soon.
   A spokesman for the Libyan Embassy in Rome, asked about the
journalists being turned back, said the embassy received a telex
today from Ali Maria saying not to issue any more visas. The telex,
according to the spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity, also
said that Libya would not let in any more journalists because ``all
the hotels are full.''
</TEXT>
