<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1356EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Church     01-05 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Church,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Raises Issue of Rehabilitating Believers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Russian Orthodox Church, for decades
subservient to a hostile Soviet government, said on the eve of its
Christmas celebration Thursday it is seeking rehabilitation of
priests and lay believers persecuted since the Bolshevik Revolution.
   Church officials told the official news agency Tass that they had
decided to form a commission to gather material on persecuted
believers.
   The action signaled another cautious move by church leaders to
take advantage of the freer atmosphere presented by the reforms of
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who met in April 1988 with Patriarch
Pimen to ask the church's support for his reforms and promise legal
changes reflecting a new attitude toward religion.
   Orthodox Christians mark Christmas on Jan. 7, but religious
celebrations begin on Christmas Eve and last through the night.
   A commission of the Communist Party Politburo is reviewing cases
of Soviet citizens who were killed or imprisoned under Josef Stalin,
and secular scholars and artists are leading an effort to build a
monument to Stalin's millions of victims.
   But the Tass announcement said the church's Holy Synod, or ruling
council ``has raised the issue of rehabilitating clergy and laymen
repressed after the 1917 revolution, and decided to form a special
commission to study related material.''
   That takes the church's review back to the rule of Soviet founder
Vladimir I. Lenin, who unlike Stalin still is regarded in the Soviet
Union with near-religious reverence.
   It was in the first years of the revolution, prior to the advent
of Stalin's rule in 1924 that some of the most severe repression
against the church took place.
   Writer Vladimir Soloukhin, in a letter published in the December
issue of the monthly Nash Sovremenik said the number of priests
dropped from 360,000 before the revolution to 40,000 at the end of
1919, two years later.
   Most of the 54,000 churches that existed before the revolution
were torn down or coverted into warehouses, factories or turned to
other uses.
   Tass said the question of rehabilitation had been discussed by
the Holy Synod on Nov. 30 and Dec. 27. It said the commission would
begin its work immediately after being formally approved at the next
Synod meeting. It did not say when that would be.
   It said the Russian Orthodox Church was inviting anyone with
material that should be considered to send it to church headquarters
in Moscow.
   Stalin had thousands of the remaining priests shot or sent to
labor camps or exile and in 1929 imposed strict laws that requires
all religious groups be registered by the government, and prohibits
religious organizations from educating the young or conducting
charitable activities.
   Religious dissidents have demanded the Russian Orthodox Church
recognize the injustice of the purges and canonize some of those
killed in purges after the revolution. But a list of new saints
approved by the church for festivities marking its 1,000th
anniversary, which was celebrated in June, refrained from that.
   Neither the church nor the government releases figures on the
number of Russian Orthdox believers among the more than 280 million
people in the Soviet Union, but the figure is believed to be in the
tens of millions.
   For more than a year Gorbachev, whose mother is reported to be a
regular church-goer, and Soviet officials have been promising a new
law on ``freedom of conscience'' that they say will ease many of the
restrictions on religious activity. Russian Orthodox Church
officials say they are helping prepare the law, tacitly
acknowledging they consider many of the restrictions unfair.
   In recent months, officials have been allowing religious
organizations to conduct some minor charity work. Sisters of Nobel
Peace Prize winner Mother Teresa's Missionaries of Charity were
permitted to come to the Soviet Union to care for those injured in
the Dec. 7 Armenian earthquake.
   The weekly Moscow News reported in its latest edition released
Thursday that Seventh Day Adventists were helping repair a school in
the village of Zaoksky, south of Moscow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890105-0118 </DOCNO>
