<FIRST>u i PM-UN-Libya 4thLd-Writethru a0599 01-05 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Libya, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0599,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Say They Warned U.S. Before Libyan Incident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs with Soviets saying they warned U.S. about
raising tensions. Pickup 11th graf pvs, ``U.S. forces...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet ambassador said today that
Moscow had warned the United States to show restraint and ``not to
raise the tension'' with Libya before U.S. jet fighters shot down
two Libyan aircraft.
   The United States told the Security Council its planes opened
fire on the Libyan jets in reaction to hostile actions that
``constituted an armed attack'' on American forces.
   U.S. Ambassador Herbert S. Okun made the statement in a letter to
the 15-member council, which held private consultations on Libya's
protest of the U.S. downing of the jets over the Mediterranean Sea
on Wednesday.
   Libyan Ambassador Ali Sunni Muntasser requested the meeting,
saying: ``Without a doubt, we will ask for condemnation of this
premeditated act of aggression.'' The two Libyan Mig-23s, he said,
were ``unarmed, on routine reconnaissance, ordinary flying. It was
an innocent flight.''
   In Washington, U.S. officials accused Libya of lying and said it
had photographic evidence the jet fighters were armed and
approaching Navy jets with hostile intent.
   A Navy intelligence review of videotape shot by one of the F-14
Tomcat jets ``tells me that the Libyan ambassador to the U.N. is a
liar. That's the first thing it tells me,'' Dan Howard, the
Pentagon's chief spokesman, told a news briefing.
   The United Nations' Soviet ambassador, Alexander M. Belonogov,
told reporters after the Security Council consultations that the
Soviet Union was worried about tension in the region over U.S.
allegations that Libya is building a chemical weapons plant.
   ``But before that (Wednesday's) incident, we gave a warning
signal to Washington to show restraint in that area, not to raise
the tension in the area,'' Belonogov said, refusing to elaborate.
   ``We deplore this accident,'' Belonogov added. ``It shows the
seriousness of the situation and that all military personnel should
be under strong instructions not to be too quick to pull the
trigger.''
   When asked about his use of the word accident, he said, ``Well,
everything that has a tragic ending is an accident.''
   Earlier, he told reporters the U.S. attack ``could provoke very
grave consequences.''
   But Okun, speaking as he entered the consultations, said the
event is ``a closed incident.''
   The session considered Libya's request for a condemnation of the
U.S. action. A formal session of the council, the most powerful U.N.
body, was scheduled later.
   ``U.S. forces have exercised their inherent right of self-defense
under international law by taking defensive action in response to
hostile actions constituting an armed attack by the military forces
(of Libya) against U.S. forces,'' said the letter from Okun.
   It said the U.S. aircraft were engaged in a routine training
operation when two Libyan aircraft ``without provocation approached
them in a hostile manner.
   ``After repeatedly attempting to disengage by taking evasive
measures,'' the letter said, ``the American aircraft, acting in
self-defense, fired upon and shot down the two Libyan aircraft.''
   It said the council should be aware of ``the gravity of Libya's
action.''
   Belonogov said the incident was the result of ``the
overconcentration of American forces in the Mediterranean on one
hand and the enemy image of Libya that exists in this country on the
other.''
   He also said there was no proof a Libyan chemical plant was being
built to manufacture chemical weapons and that a Libyan invitation
to the United States to inspect the plant ``should be taken
seriously.'' The United States rejected the Libyan offer.
   In Moscow today, a Soviet general, Anatoly Kuntsevich, said Libya
may be able to manufacture chemical weapons, but they would be in
quantities too small for waging war.
   Any Security Council resolution critical of the United States was
expected to be vetoed by the U.S. delegation and possibly by its
allies Britain and France _ all permanent members with veto power on
the council.
   The Soviet Union and China also can kill resolutions.
   In 1986, when the United States attacked Libya with air strikes
to punish it for allegedly providing logistical support for
terrorist attacks, many U.N. members protested and Libya went to the
Security Council.
   But a resolution of condemnation was blocked then by vetos from
the United States, Britain and France.
</TEXT>
