<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   01-05 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0560,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Threats Painted Over, Mayor Denies He's Hiding</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to ADD details of Arafat's statement. Pickup 3rd
graf pvs, ``I cannot...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers today forced
residents to paint over graffiti threatening the life of Mayor Elias
Freij, whose proposal for a U.N.-sponsored truce in the Palestinian
uprising was rejected by the PLO.
   Freij denied reports he was in hiding following PLO chairman
Yasser Arafat's statement that anyone trying to stop the uprising
``exposes himself to the bullets of our people.'' Arafat made the
comment at a rally Jan. 1 in Saudi Arabia marking the anniversary of
his Fatah movement.
   ``I cannot believe he (Arafat) said that,'' Freij said in a
telephone interview from his office.
   Also today, 15 Palestinians, ranging in age from 15 to 37, were
wounded in clashes with troops in the Gaza Strip refugee camp of
Shati, Arab hospital officials said.
   Palestinians in the West Bank town of Jericho said a 25-year-old
resident gunned down near his house Wednesday was suspected of
collaborating with Israeli authorities.
   Army officials confirmed the death of Bassam Barahmeh, who died
in a hospital, but said they had no information on his activities.
The officials said they were checking reports that 15 Palestinians
were wounded.
   Leaders of the uprising have repeatedly threatened Palestinians
who cooperate with Israel, and more than a dozen alleged
collaborators have been killed since the unrest began in December
1987.
   Barahmeh's death brought to 347 the number of Palestinians killed
in the uprising. Fourteen Israelis have died.
   Near Bethlehem's Manger Square, dozens of armed Israeli soldiers
took identity cards from shopkeepers and Palestinian youths and
ordered them to paint over anti-Freij slogans.
   The threats were signed by the Popular Front for the Liberation
of Palestine, a Marxist faction of the PLO, and included, ``Shame on
all traitors'' and ``Death to all those who forsake the cause.''
   Freij today denied as ``absolutely groundless'' reports that he
went into hiding or hired bodyguards after the threats appeared
early in the week.
   ``I have been in my office working normally yesterday (Wednesday)
and today and will be tomorrow, too,'' he said.
   Efforts to reach Freij on Tuesday night and Wednesday were not
successful. His aides said he was not in his office Wednesday
afternoon, and Freij changed his home telephone number. An
Associated Press reporter was turned away from the Freij home
Wednesday evening.
   Freij, who returned an AP call today, said the death threats
against him are ``absolutely meaningless.''
   He claimed they were signed by Hamas, an anti-PLO Moslem
fundamentalist group, but an Arabic-speaking reporter clearly saw
the signature of the front, a PLO faction.
   Freij said he accepted the PLO's rejection of his truce proposal,
which he linked to Israel releasing 5,000 Arab prisoners and
reopening universities, but said he was not withdrawing the idea.
   ``I have the right to make suggestions, and the PLO has the right
as our representatives to make decisions. They made such a decision
(and) I fully respect that,'' he said.
   Freij said he never supported a unilateral cease-fire and
supports continued anti-Israeli protests until occupation ends or
peace talks start.
   Also today, Finance Minister Shimon Peres presented an economic
austerity plan to the Cabinet to cut $611 million from the nation's
$52 billion budget, including $67 million from the defense budget.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said the army will have to shift
about $83 million from existing military programs to cover expenses
stemming from the uprising. He said he was agreeing to the plan
because he couldn't ignore Israel's economic problems.
   The Arabic-language newspaper Al Shaab said a joint PLO-Jordanian
committee would meet in Amman on Saturday to discuss emergency
payments to thousands of former Palestinian employees of Jordan in
the West Bank.
   The three-day meeting was to be attended by Arafat and Jordanian
Prime Minister Zaid Rifai, said the newspaper, published in Arab
east Jerusalem.
   The employees, including teachers and civil servants, lost their
salaries after Jordan's King Hussein announced July 31 that he would
sever all administrative ties with the West Bank.
   Mohammed Milhem, a PLO member of the committee, told the AP in
Amman that funds for the project had not yet been secured, and that
no firm date for the meeting had been set.
</TEXT>
