<FIRST>r a PM-ReaganDinner 2ndLd-Writethru a0549 01-05 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reagan Dinner, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0549,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hollywood Crowd Wants Reagan Back</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to CORRECT quote; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs,
`Merv Griffin ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A legion of Hollywood glitterati
feted President Reagan at a $1 million homecoming gala, singing
``Camp David is rare, but it ain't Bel-Air'' and tantalizing the
former actor with a TV offer.
   Reagan, for his part, said he was eager to return to the state
where he began his dual careers in film and politics.
   ``Every time I come home, I say to myself, `Why did I ever
leave?'' Reagan remarked at Wednesday night's dinner. ``I'm not
saying I can hardly wait, but in 15 days, 15 hours, 55 minutes and
14 seconds, I will be on my way.''
   Merv Griffin, who escorted Eva Gabor to the gala to raise money
for Nancy Reagan's anti-drug program, replied ``Isn't it
wonderful?'' when asked about the Reagans' imminent return to
California.
   ``Maybe we'll all make a movie together. I'm sure they'll be the
leaders of everything that happens here,'' he said.
   Dinner guests included Griffin and Marvin Davis, the Reagans' new
neighbors in posh Bel-Air, along with Charlton Heston, Lucille Ball,
Aaron Spelling, Angie Dickinson and Burt Bacharach. The menu
featured caviar, truffles and lobster.
   As the president and his party arrived, limousines at the Beverly
Hilton unloaded such passengers as Phyllis Diller, Armand Hammer,
Shelley Duvall, Charles Bronson and his wife, actress Jill Ireland,
the first lady's friend Betsy Bloomingdale and Mr. T.
   Dynasty star Joan Collins invited the president to play a role on
her nighttime soap. ``He could be my ex-husband or something,'' she
quipped.
   ``I'm delighted to have him back,'' said Heston. ``We'll miss him
in Washington, but I'm glad he's back here.''
   To attend the dinner and a reception, the only welcome home party
for the Reagans before they leave Washington on inauguration day
Jan. 20, about 65 people paid $25,000 each for a table of 10. About
950 people paid $1,000 each for single seats.
   Reagan used the gala as a forum to praise the first lady's
anti-drug crusade, saying his wife used the White House ``bully
pulpit'' for the good of America.
   Presentation of a $1 million check by Barron Hilton, whose hotel
chain paid the cost of the ceremony, highlighted the fund-raiser for
the planned Los Angeles home of the Nancy Reagan Center for drug
rehabilitation.
   The center, for those ages 12 to 18, is to be established in a
former hospital in the San Fernando Valley. Organizers say they need
$10 million to buy and renovate the structure.
   At the dinner, Don Rickles delivered his rapid-fire brand of
caustic comedy. In a five-minute routine, he opened saying, ``Mr.
President and Mrs. Reagan, for $25,000, this meal was lousy.''
   In an evening that also featured a Nancy Reagan singing duet with
Mary Martin, Griffin filled in for Frank Sinatra, who was ill with a
cold. Griffin sang a personalized version of Sinatra's signature
song, ``My Way.''
   ``Camp David is rare, but it ain't Bel-Air. Bel-Air is my way,''
Griffin crooned.
   The usually staid and stoic Gov. George Deukmejian told Reagan,
``I hope it won't bother you to be the second-most charismatic
person in California.''
   Reagan's eyes stayed on his wife.
   Nodding at the first lady, Reagan said, ``Nancy, I knew from the
first moment I laid eyes on you, that you were the greatest. Now,
the whole world knows.''
   Reagan said he took pride in the achievements of his eight years
as president, but at the top of the list was Mrs. Reagan's battle
``long before it was fashionable to get America's young people to
just say no to drugs.''
   Some Southern Californians, however, are less than enthusiastic
about the prospect of having the drug rehabilitation center in their
neighborhood.
   A dozen homeowners from the Lake View Terrace area, where the
Nancy Reagan center is slated to be located, demonstrated outside
the hotel, chanting, ``If you really care, put it in Bel-Air.''
   The Reagans spent the Christmas holidays at their $2.5 million
Bel-Air home for the first time.
</TEXT>
