<FIRST>u i PM-Libya-US 3rdLd-Writethru a0537 01-05 0839</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya-US, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0537,0862</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libyans Brace For Attack; Gadhafi's Home Fortified</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 6th, `Gadhafi's home...' to add journalists
turned away. Pickup 7th pvs, Gadhafi's compound...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents fleeing Tripoli jammed gas
stations and troops fortified the home of Col. Moammar Gadhafi,
whose government claimed the U.S. downing of two Libyan jet fighters
was a prelude to a major attack, news reports said.
   The Foreign Ministry summoned heads of West European diplomatic
missions after Wednesday's incident over the Mediterranean, asking
them to condemn the U.S. ``aggression'' and prevent an escalation in
tensions, the official news agency JANA reported.
   Gadhafi branded the U.S. action an example of increased
``official American terrorism, which is backed by brute force,'' the
agency said.
   The Libyan leader, whom Washington accuses of sponsoring
international terrorism, was quoted as declaring the
``revolutionaries of great Libya'' would ``meet challenge with
challenge.''
   The Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported from Tripoli that
residents were packing filling stations as they fled the capital
after learning two Libyan fighters had been shot down by U.S.
warplanes.
   Gadhafi's home was turned into a ``fortress,'' with anti-aircraft
missiles mounted on its roof, Tanjug said.
   Nearly 30 journalists flying from Italy to Libya were turned back
at the Tripoli airport today and sent back to Rome.
   A spokesman for the Libyan Embassy in Rome, asked about the
journalists being turned back, said the embassy received
instructions not to issue any more visas. The telex said Libya would
not let in any more journalists because ``all the hotels are full,''
said the spokesman, who demanded anonymity.
   Gadhafi's compound was a target of the last U.S. military strike
on Libya when aircraft bombed Tripoli and Benghazi in April 1986,
killing more than 100 people. President Reagan described the raids
as retaliation for the bombing of a West Berlin disco frequented by
American servicemen, which the United States blamed on terrorists
sponsored by Libya.
   Two U.S. servicemen and a Turkish woman died in the disco bombing.
   Libya claimed the downing of its fighters Wednesday was a
premeditated attack and a potential precursor to a major assault.
   The Foreign Ministry summoned Arab ambassadors in Tripoli to ask
for a ``unified Arab stance'' against the United States, JANA said.
   The ministry called for an emergency meeting of Arab League
foreign ministers to adopt ``collective measures for defense and to
participate with the Libyan Arab people in the defense of its land
and existence,'' the agency said.
   Gadhafi also sent a message to the head of the non-aligned
movement, Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe, asking the group to help stop
the U.S. ``aggression'' and warning of the ``threat'' to world
security posed by American military moves in the Mediterranean, it
said.
   The Reagan administration said the two U.S. fighters acted in
self-defense while on routine patrol over international waters, but
the Libyan ambassador to Rome linked the event to U.S. allegations
Libya has built a chemical weapons factory in Rabta, 60 miles
outside Tripoli.
   The State Department denied there was a connection.
   Gadhafi has said the plant's function is to produce medicine, and
JANA reported in recent days that Libyan doctors and nurses were
conducting a sit-in at the factory in hopes of deterring a U.S.
attack.
   Most West European governments have responded with some
skepticism to allegations the plant is to manufacture chemical
weapons. West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher said
Wednesday his government had no evidence proving a West German
pharmaceutical firm had helped build it.
   Britain's Foreign Office said it had independent information
confirming the Rabta plant was constructed to produce chemical
weapons.
   President Reagan said last month his advisers were considering
attacking the plant. But The Washington Post today quoted
unidentified senior officials in the Reagan administration as saying
the president now opposes a strike because Washington's European
allies are against the idea.
   After the Libyan jets were destroyed Wednesday, Gadhafi asked the
Soviet Union to move some of its warships in the Mediterranean to
the area in which U.S. vessels are operating near Libya, Tanjug
reported.
   The agency's correspondent, one of the few non-Arab journalists
with an office in Tripoli, has had access to high Libyan sources and
his reports often prove reliable.
   A reporter for Italian TV said Gadhafi's residence-headquarters
in Tripoli, already equipped with watchtowers and tanks parked in
camouflaged garages, had been even more heavily fortified.
   The Italian correspondent said anti-missile batteries had been
placed in key areas. He said the government television station was
one point at which security was notably greater.
   He described the reaction as ``first incredulity, then anger''
when word arrived in Tripoli that fighters from the U.S. 6th Fleet
had shot down two Libyan MiG-23 jets.
   In New York on Wednesday, Libya's U.N. ambassador, Ali Sunni
Muntasser, requested an emergency meeting of the Security Council to
condemn the U.S. action.
   JANA quoted the Foreign Ministry as describing the U.S. naval
presence in the Mediterranean as ``a smokescreen'' for a
``large-scale aggression to be launched'' against Libyan military
and economic installations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
