<DOCNO> AP890105-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1421EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Reagan-House     01-05 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-House,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>The President's New Digs: Four Fireplaces and a Heated Pool</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald Reagan and his wife have two more weeks
of living in government quarters on Pennsylvania Avenue in
Washington before setting up California housekeeping in a $2.5
million ranch-style house _ modest by neighborhood standards _ that
was purchased for them by friends.
   During their two-week Christmas-New Year's vacation which ended
Thursday, the president and Nancy Reagan slept nine nights in the
house. Aides said they unpacked boxes, hung pictures and drank juice
squeezed from oranges off their own trees. It was their first stay.
   The 35-year-old single-story, three-bedroom, six-bathroom,
four-fireplace flagstone house stands behind a wall and security
fence on a hillside dotted with orange, palm and other trees.
   It was purchased by a group of 20 friends from whom the Reagans
will lease it for a reported $15,000 a month, with an option to buy.
   At the Reagans' request, its address, on the mailbox in front,
was changed last summer from 666 Saint Cloud Drive to 668 because of
connotations surrounding the number 666. Some people believe 666 is
the symbol of the devil.
   Despite the seven-figure price of the Reagans' new home, it is
overshadowed by others in the posh Bel Air neighborhood.
   The house is ``the low-man-on-the-totem-pole house'' in a
neighborhood where the neighbors include Elizabeth Taylor and Zsa
Zsa Gabor, said neighbor Jeffrey Hyland, president of the real
estate firm Alvarez, Hyland &amp; Young.
   ``The house to the west sold for $13.5 million and the house to
the east sold for $14.5 million,'' he said.
   He said Reagan ``is following out the real estate rule that you
always want to buy into a neighborhood on the bottom end,'' adding:
``You want to be the cheapest man on the block so every other house
pulls you up.''
   Unlike houses farther up the hill, the new Reagan home doesn't
have much of a view.
   ``All the trees across the way have in the past 25 to 35 years
blocked it,'' Hyland said. ``It's amazing. Every 25 feet you go the
view is bigger and better. There's a house up above them where you
can see the ocean as well as downtown Los Angeles.''
   The Reagans' house has an outdoor heated swimming pool, but the
weather during their vacation was a bit chilly for swimming.
   Elaine Crispen, Mrs. Reagan's press secretary, said the first
lady told her that Reagan thought ``that it was a real treat for him
that he had orange juice from the oranges off their own trees.''
   Mrs. Reagan told Mrs. Crispen that the president ``was pleased to
see that she had been able to get so much done'' in making the house
a home, even though she was 3,000 miles away in Washington most of
the time.
   Mrs. Reagan made several visits to the house before their current
stay.
   ``She would spend an afternoon or so looking at things and
deciding what she needed and what would have to be done and sort of
some mental placement of furniture,'' Mrs. Crispen said.
   Reagan got his first look inside the house on an earlier trip
when, Mrs. Reagan has said, she sneaked him past reporters by having
him crouch in the back seat of a White House car.
   On Dec. 23, when he rode to the house for the first time sitting
straight up, he was quoted by aide Mark Weinberg as saying, ``I'm
awed, and I love it.''
   The Reagans have not allowed reporters into the 6,500-square-foot
house. Hyland said his listings showed it has a drawing room and
library, a dining room, a patio with a heated floor, a kitchen with
a walk-in cooler and a two-bedroom servants' wing above a three-car
garage.
   Security gear has been installed, with television cameras mounted
on the chimneys and the street blocked off and lined with vans,
trucks and trailers.
   ``I live a block up the street and every time I drive up and
down, it's just a mess,'' Hyland said this week.
   Information made available in 1986 to the Office of Government
Ethics showed that among the friends who bought the house for the
Reagans are Holmes Tuttle, a California automobile dealer and
industrialist, and Earle Jorgensen, chairman of a steel and aluminum
distribution company. Both are long-time unofficial advisers of
Reagan. Each paid at least $156,000, the documents showed.
   Hyland also said he believed the buyers got a bargain. He
estimated the land alone was worth $3 million when they bought it
and the property is probably worth $5 million now with the
improvements that have been made. The house stands on a lot of just
over an acre.
</TEXT>
