<FIRST>u w PM-HomeworkSuit     01-05 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Homework Suit,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Garment Workers' Union Challenges Administration Effort To Expand
Homework</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Ladies' Garment Workers'
Union today asked a federal court to prohibit the Labor Department
from implementing regulations that would allow homework in five
apparel-related industries.
   The suit, filed in federal district court here, argues that Labor
Secretary Ann McLaughlin acted arbitrarily in approving the
regulations and that she ignored evidence that there were not
adequate safeguards in the rules to prevent violations of labor and
worker-safety laws.
   The regulations are scheduled to take effect Jan. 9. It was not
immediately clear whether there would be a hearing on the complaint
before then.
   The suit also asked that the Labor Department be ordered to
reconsider its 1984 decision allowing homework in the knitted
outerwear industry. The department said its success in monitoring
that industry led it to draft the new regulations, but the suit
contended there has been inadequate monitoring and enforcement of
homework in the industry.
   The five manufacturing industries covered by the new rules are:
gloves and mittens, buttons and buckles, handkerchiefs, embroideries
and, to a limited extent, jewelry.
   About 167,000 workers are employed by the affected industries,
which generated $10 billion worth of production in 1986, according
to Susan Cowell, vice president of the ILGWU.
   Joining the garment workers' union in filing the suit were two
other national unions, Amalgamated Clothing and Textile Workers
Union and Service Employees International Union, two New-York based
locals, three apparel-industry groups and the states of New York and
Pennsylvania.
   Named as defendants were McLaughlin and Paula V. Smith,
administrator of the department's wage and hour division, which
enforces many of the laws the suit contends would be violated if the
homework regulations are allowed to take effect.
   Bans on homework in the apparel and related industries date back
to the 1940s, when they were adopted to prevent exploitations of
low-wage workers, predominantly immigrants. The Reagan
administration for the past several years has attempted to eliminate
the restrictions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
