<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1430EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-GandhiAssassins     01-05 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gandhi Assassins,0795</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Dismisses Appeals in Gandhi Assassination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court rejected appeals by the
two Sikhs condemned for the 1984 assassination of Prime Minister
Indira Gandhi, and ordered that they be hanged Friday in the central
prison's courtyard.
   Panels of five justices each turned down pleas Thursday by
Satwant Singh, the only assassin who survived, and Kehar Singh,
convicted of helping plot the murder.
   ``This is the last legal battle. We can't go anywhere now,'' said
Kehar Singh's lawyer, Ram Jethmalani.
   The condemned were ordered executed at the maximum-security Tihar
Central Jail, where the last hanging was in 1984. They are not
related; all members of the Sikh faith have Singh, which means lion,
as part of their names.
   A third Sikh, Balbir Singh, also was arrested, tried and
convicted on conspiracy charges and sentenced to death, but the
court overturned the conviction in August for lack of evidence.
   Mrs. Gandhi was shot down by members of her personal guard Oct.
31, 1984, in the garden of her home in New Delhi. Other members of
the guard then fired on the assassins, but Satwant Singh survived.
   Police and soldiers were put on maximum alert Thursday in New
Delhi and in the northern states of Haryana, Himachal Pradesh and
Punjab, where Sikh militants are waging a 6-year-old separatist war,
in case violence accompanied the hangings.
   Security was increased at bus and railway stations, often targets
of Sikh extremists, at government offices and other locations. Many
schools were ordered closed.
   Preparations for the executions were completed last October after
the first death warrants were issued. The manila ropes, an inch
thick and nearly 20 feet long, were stretched, tested and locked in
a vault. The country's only two hangmen have been kept under guard
inside the prison for the past three months.
   Lawyers and relatives went to the prison Thursday for final
visits.
   Attorney R.S. Sodhi emerged after a 45-minute meeting with
Satwant Singh, 54, one of two Sikh bodyguards accused of killing
Mrs. Gandhi. He described his client as calm and composed, then read
handwritten statement by the condemned man.
   ``There is no greater privilege for a Sikh to lay down his life
for the protection'' of his faith, it said. ``I wish I could be born
again and again and each time lay down my life for this.''
   Jasbir Kaur, Kehar Singh's wife, said after visiting him: ``He's
happy and laughing. He told me to take care of the family.''
   Defense lawyers had filed several appeals this week in a third
attempt to block the executions.
   Jethmalani, a leading criminal lawyer, challenged President
Ramaswamy Venkataraman's refusal of clemency for Kehar Singh, 54.
   He said the president considered only the government case and
ignored new evidence that might prove his client's innocence,
including the arrest of a Sikh terrorist who allegedly said he
planned the assassination.
   Venkataraman rejected the mercy plea twice. He said he was bound
by the recommendations of the government, which is led by the
victim's son, Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi.
   Satwant Singh's appeal sought prosecution of two of Mrs. Gandhi's
security guards. He claimed the guards shot him after he was
disarmed and said their actions amounted to attempted murder.
   He did not appeal for clemency, but under Indian law his death
sentence was delayed automatically Kehar Singh did so.
   Mrs. Gandhi was killed in apparent retaliation for an army raid
she ordered four months earlier to rout Sikh militants from the
Golden Temple in Amritsar, the holiest shrine of Sikhism. More than
1,200 people were killed, most of them Sikhs.
   As Mrs. Gandhi lay dying, a guard named Beant Singh threw down
his gun and shouted: ``I have done what I had to do! Now, you do
what you must do!''
   Other guards opened fire, killing Beant Singh and wounding
Satwant Singh. Beant Singh is revered as a matryr by many Sikh
militants.
   Kehar Singh, a government clerk who was Beant's uncle, was
arrested a month later and charged with helping plot the
assassination, whih caused anti-Sikh riots in northern India by
members of the Hindu majority. More than 2,700 people were killed,
nearly all of them Sikhs.
   Sikh violence has increased since, and at least 2,440 people were
killed last year in Punjab, the only Indian state in which Sikhs are
the majority. That was more than double the 1,032 victims in 1987.
   Sikh militants have fought since 1982 for a separate nation in
Punjab. They claim discrimination by Hindus, who make up more than
80 percent of India's 880 million people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
