<FIRST>r w AM-People-Barrymore     01-05 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Barrymore,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drew Barrymore, Star of ``E.T.,'' Talks of Her Alcohol Abuse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``E.T.'' actress Drew Barrymore, who entered an
alcoholism treatment center at age 13, says she got into trouble
with drinking because she wanted to imitate relatives in the
legendary Barrymore theater family, some of whom drank heavily.
   ``I wanted to be just like them so badly for so long,'' she said
in an interview to be shown on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America''
next Monday. A transcript was made available to The Associated Press
on Thursday.
   ``They were all famous people of the theater and they were
respected and they were talented and, you know, they drank,'' she
said. ``Little did I know that it was cool not to do it. ... It
became like a fashion and that's what I wanted to be part of.''
   Miss Barrymore, who was a seasoned actress at age 6 when she
played the impetuous Gertie in the hit movie ``E.T. the
Extra-Terrestrial,'' was released just before Christmas from an
unidentified rehabilitation center in California, where she was
treated for alcohol abuse.
   She said she started drinking at age 8, when she downed a glass
of champagne on a dare. She said she started using drugs at age 11.
   It was easy to sneak out to night clubs and drink with friends,
she said. ``I really was a party girl.''
   Miss Barrymore is the granddaughter of the late movie and theater
actor John Barrymore, himself a notoriously heavy drinker, and is
the daughter of a Hungarian-born actress who is the third wife of
reclusive John Barrymore Jr.
   The girl said her mother didn't notice her alcohol problems
partly because she used her acting talents to hide it, and because
her mother ``didn't want to believe that I was doing it, either.''
   She said she hated her first experience with alcohol, but ``like
if you can't control it, it progressively gets worse, you know, an
unfortunately I was one of those people.''
   Asked what advice she had for other children tempted to
experiment with drugs and alcohol, Miss Barrymore replied:
   ``No matter how many times people would tell me or my friends, no
matter what, I did not want to believe it until I had hit my bottom,
which I did. But I think the best advice I can give anyone is to
just listen to other people because I didn't and those people, a lot
of those people, were right.''
</TEXT>
