<FIRST>r i AM-Music     01-05 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Music,0154</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Firm Buys Major Music Portfolio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American classics like ``Blue Moon'' and ``Singing
in the Rain'' will become British property under a $336 million
purchase announced Thursday by the entertainment conglomerate Thorn
EMI PLC.
   Thorn EMI said it was buying SBK Entertainment World Inc., a
major U.S. music publishing company that owns more than 250,000
individual copyrights, mainly of songs commissioned by big U.S.
movie producers.
   Thorn EMI's chief executive, Colin Southgate, called it ``a
once-in-a-lifetime opportunity for Thorn-EMI'' that would create ``a
worldwide music publishing business of immense potential.''
   Income from the portfolio is expected to be about $37 million for
1988, mainly in the United States and Europe.
   Southgate said the deal included setting up a joint record
production venture with two of the selling shareholders. He gave no
details.
   The purchase takes effect in April, pending shareholder and
regulatory approval.
