<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1442EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PSACrash     01-05 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PSA Crash,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Board Gives Final Ruling: Onboard Shooting Caused PSA Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Transportation Safety Board ruled
in a final report Thursday that the l987 crash of a Pacific
Southwest Airlines jet was caused by a gunman seeking revenge on a
former supervisor.
   PSA Flight 1771 crashed Dec. 7, l987, about l75 miles northwest
of Los Angeles, killing all 43 people aboard including a former
USAir employee who apparently had opened fire with a revolver during
the flight.
   The safety board said a note written by the man, David Burke,
threatened his former supervisor, who also was aboard the flight.
The note was found in the wreckage as were the revolver and six
spent cartridges.
   The final two-page federal report on the accident included no
information that had not previously been disclosed by investigators
in general terms.
   Authorities within weeks of the accident said Burke had taken a
.44-caliber Magnum revolver aboard the San Francisco-bound flight.
According to the PSA investigation, it is believed that Burke was
able to avoid detection of his revolver because he bypassed normal
passenger security checks at the Los Angeles airport after being
recognized as a former airline employee.
   A cockpit recorder tape from the plane included gunshots in or
near the cockpit, according to the federal board. The board said in
a brief summary of findings released Thursday that the tape revealed
``the sounds of a scuffle and several shots which were apparently
fired in or near the cockpit.''
   It has been presumed that both the pilot and co-pilot were shot,
but the federal board's summary does not specifically say the two
pilots had been hit by gunfire.
   According to the findings, the official probable cause for the
accident was ``interference'' and ``intentional sabotage'' by an
emotionally distraught passenger. The safety board cited as
contributing factors inadequate security and inadequate operatoring
procedures by the airline that permitted Burke to bypass security.
   The crash prompted the Federal Aviation Administration to order
tighter security measures at passenger checkpoints, especially in
regard to airline and airport employees.
   In an action that grew out of the PSA crash, the FAA on Wednesday
announced a final regulation aimed at tightening access to
restricted areas of an airport by using computerized identification
badges. Such badges would make an ID card ineffective if it is
reported stolen or if a person leaves his job without returning the
badge.
   Investigators have said that Burke was believed to have still had
his USAir identification badge at the time he boarded Flight 1771.
USAir was a subsidiary of USAir Corp. at the time of the crash and
since has merged completely into USAir.
   The accident report said, as has been disclosed previously, that
Burke had left a ``goodbye'' message with friends and boarded PSA
Flight 1771 with the intention of killing his former supervisor at
USAir.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890105-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1443EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PrisonReleases     01-05 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prison Releases,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>600 Inmates Released In Louisiana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 600 inmates were put on the
streets today under pressure from a federal court to relieve prison
overcrowding.
   The inmates were the first to be released under a 1986 state law,
expanded in 1988, alowing well-behaved prisoners to leave after
serving half their sentences rather than two-thirds. Some 300 more
are to be freed later this month.
   Hilton Butler, warden of the Louisiana State Penitentiary at
Angola, said inmates were taken to the gates if they had family
waiting, while vans took the rest to a bus terminal in Baton Rouge.
   Several of the 30 inmates awaiting buses at the terminal
complained that the Corrections Department could have handled the
release better.
   Robert Dennis Hage complained there was ``no organization in all
of this. You get $20 and they say, `There's the door.' I've already
spent $5 here for a skimpy breakfast.'' Department records showed
that Hage was convicted of rape.
   Between the mid-1970s and 1982, every state, parish and city jail
in Louisiana came under federal court orders to relieve overcrowding.
   The court set a maximum allowable population in the state's nine
prisons of 12,330 inmates, and also set ceilings in local jails.
   Of the inmates released today, about half were from state
prisons; the rest were inmates being held in parish jails until room
could be found for them in the state prisons, which are at the
population limit set by the court.
   Overcrowding has been blamed primarily on the enactment in recent
years of mandatory sentences for various crimes. Lawmakers approved
construction of two prisons, but work has come almost to a
standstill because of financial problems.
   The Legislature rejected most of former Gov. Edwin Edwards'
efforts to lessen penalties for various non-violent crimes and
create programs such as home imprisonment.
   ``I'm not happy with our criminal justice system,'' Gov. Buddy
Roemer said Wednesday, adding that a task force will study the
criminal justice system ``all the way from sentencing to
rehabilitation'' to determine how to ease overcrowding.
   Although the inmates will be under parole supervision, the
releases will cause problems for the officers in charge of watching
them, officials said.
   Over the past three years, the number of field parole agents has
fallen from 365 to 252, said Charles Adams, assistant director of
parole services.
   Adams said statistics show that prisoners with early releases are
more likely to run into trouble than regular probation and parole
cases.
</TEXT>
