<FIRST>r a AM-Mother'sSuicide     01-05 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mother's Suicide,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mom Shoots Self at Slain Daughters' Graves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE WALES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who killed her three young
daughters fatally shot herself at their graves 32 years later,
authorities said.
   Lorene Calbeck, 67, shot herself in the chest Tuesday night at
Lake Wales Cemetery, then drove home and called the 911 emergency
number, Polk County sheriff's Detective Richard Land said. She died
in an ambulance.
   A neighbor said the woman was depressed since the loss in June of
her husband, Mark, of 45 years. She left detailed notes to
authorities telling them to contact a friend and giving instructions
on how to care for her oven.
   Authorities said Mrs. Calbeck had tried to commit suicide shortly
after the deaths in May 1956 of her daughters, ages 1 through 5.
   Then 34, Mrs. Calbeck took her children on a moonlight ride to a
deserted area, stripped them to their panties and shot each in the
heart with a $22-caliber target pistol, police reported.
   Then she drove them back home to the Lake Wales Trailer Park,
placed them on a bed in order of their size and covered them with
cellophane.
   She left three suicide notes then _ one to authorities on how to
reach her husband, who was working in Michigan at the time; one to
her husband; and one to the trailer park's manager on how to care
for her gardenias.
   She then fired a pistol into the left side of her chest, but she
survived. She never told authorities why she shot the girls.
   A grand jury took no action against Mrs. Calbeck. She was sent to
the Florida State Hospital in Chattahoochee and was hospitalized for
12 years, said Hilda Barnhardt, a Lake Wales resident who knew Mrs.
Calbeck since 1982 but had not known about the daughters.
   ``It was such a shock to learn she had children,'' Mrs. Barnhardt
said. ``She had never mentioned the children or why she had been
institutionalized. She just didn't talk about it.''
   She said Mrs. Calbeck had been depressed since the death last
June of her husband.
</TEXT>
