<FIRST>r a PM-TroubledSchools     01-05 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Troubled Schools,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kentucky to Take Over Two Troubled School Districts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state, exercising its powers under a
1984 ``academic bankruptcy'' law for the first time, plans to seize
control of two troubled school districts, a newspaper reported today.
   Superintendent of Public Instruction John Brock will recommend
taking control of the Floyd and Whitley districts to the state
school board next week, The Lexington Herald-Leader said, citing
unidentified sources.
   Brock refused to comment on the report.
   The school districts in rural eastern Kentucky have been the
focus of state investigations and parents' complaints. Both are
receiving state help with management and academic problems.
   Floyd County Superintendent Ron Hager said Brock telephoned him
to say the action was based on low attendance and test scores. The
school system is expecting to complete the fiscal year with a
deficit of more than $300,000.
   Floyd and Whitley have a combined enrollment of about 12,900
students.
   A month ago, Brock issued a study of Floyd County's 22 schools
that turned up reports of rampant patronage and nepotism, wide
disparities in what is taught from school to school and other
academic shortcomings.
   A 1987 consultant's report on the Whitley district said it lacked
sound purchasing procedures, had attendance problems, spent too much
time embroiled in politics and legal action and lacked high-quality
teaching in areas.
</TEXT>
