<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talk show host Oprah Winfrey, actress Ann Archer
and gun control advocate Sarah Brady are among Ms. magazine's Women
of the Year.
   The magazine, citing their ``determination, grit and guts,'' said
Thursday that the winners ``share one overwhelming characteristic:
They are all fighters, women determined to make a difference.''
   Ms. Archer was named for ``courageous pro-choice advocacy,'' and
Ms. Winfrey for ``her mission to expose black talent.''
   Ms. Brady, wife of former Reagan press secretary James Brady, was
honored for her stand against the powerful gun lobby. Her husband
was critically wounded in the 1981 assassination attempt on
President Reagan.
   The other honorees: Marjory Stoneman Douglas, for a 60-year
battle to protect the Florida Everglades; ``Sweet Alice'' Harris,
for helping poverty-stricken children in Los Angeles' Watts section,
and Yolanda Serrano, for fighting AIDS among New York's drug addicts
and prostitutes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Juan Carlos and his family quietly
celebrated the monarch's 51st birthday Thursday in their Zarzuela
Palace residence, a palace official said.
   Celebrating with the king were his wife, Queen Sofia, 50, and
their children, Crown Prince Felipe, Princess Elena and Princess
Cristina.
   Juan Carlos, who received congratulatory telegrams from around
the world, did not plan to attend any public events Thursday,
according to the palace official, who did not identify himself.
   Juan Carlos, born in Italian exile in 1938, assumed the throne
Nov. 22, 1975, two days after the death of Gen. Francisco Franco,
and helped engineer the country's smooth transition to democracy.
