<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it comes to riveting plots, Hollywood should
take a look at teen-age actor River Phoenix's life. It has it all:
religious cults, hard times and his break into movies _ all before
age 12.
   Phoenix, now 18, has appeared in such films as ``Stand By Me,''
``Mosquito Coast,'' and, most recently, ``Running on Empty.''
   The latter earned him a Golden Globe nomination for best
supporting actor, and his backers are hoping an Academy Award
nomination is not out of his reach.
   But glitz and glitter is not what River Phoenix is all about.
   An anti-fur activist, he doesn't wear animal skin and has been a
vegeterian since he was 8.
   ``When I was old enough to realize all meat was killed, I saw it
as an irrational way of using our power, to take a weaker thing and
mutilate it,'' he said in an interview in Thursday's New York Times.
   Phoenix's parents joined the Children of God religious cult when
he was 2; by the time he was 5, he was playing his guitar in the
streets, accompanied by his sister, Rainbow, now 16. The family left
the cult in 1977.
   The other children include Leaf, 14, who is also an actor;
Liberty, 12; and Summer, 11.
