<FIRST>r i AM-Crash-Israel     01-05 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash-Israel,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Terrorism Experts: Many Explosives Not Detectable by X-Ray</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many explosives cannot be detected by
conventional technology and only intensive questioning of passengers
can prevent bombings of commerical airliners, Israeli terrorism
experts said Thursday.
   The experts displayed a replica of an explosive-laden suitcase
believed similar to one suspected in the bombing of Pan Am Flight
103 on Dec. 21 over Lockerbie, Scotland.
   They said the hard-sided bag could hold two to 44 pounds of
plastic explosive concealed in a false bottom.
   ``This kind of device is very hard to detect. By relying on the
traditional kind of X-raying used in Europe and the United States,
it is almost impossible,'' said Menachem Bacharach of International
Consultants on Targeted Security, an Israeli company specializing in
aviation security.
   ``It is better to concentrate on the passenger and whether he
exhibits suspicious behavior during questioning,'' Bacharach said.
   The suitcase and a replica of a radio-cassette tape player fitted
with about one pound of explosives seized from Palestinian
guerrillas in Frankfurt in October are among the devices to be
displayed at an international seminar on aviation security to be
held Feb. 5-9 in Tel Aviv.
   Civil aviation authorities and security heads of airports and
airlines from 25 countries will attend the conference, aimed at
improving air security worldwide.
   The replica of the radio displayed Thursday contained coils of
brown clay instead of plastic explosives.
   Bacharach said his company planted the dummy radio on a woman
employee to try to test security in six European airports in
November and early December.
   He said the radio was discovered by security officials in five of
the airports after the woman was subjected to intensive questioning.
In one airport, the officials identified the woman as suspicious but
did not find the radio hidden in her hand luggage.
   ``In each case, the X-ray monitor ... failed to detect the radio.
Only when the security officials emptied the suitcase and went
through it item by item, did they discover something was wrong,''
Bacharach said.
   He said the task of detecting hidden explosives was made more
difficult by the fact that electrical appliances containing the
devices often operate normally.
   Many devices also are detonated by timers that cannot be detected
by immersion in decompression chambers frequently used by airlines
to test for explosives, Bacharach said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
