<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-France-PLO     01-05 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-PLO,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>France Elevates Status of PLO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand said Thursday that
France plans to elevate the status of the Palestine Liberation
Organization's office in Paris to a ``general delegation.''
   The president, speaking to reporters at the Elysee Palace, said
France recognized only states possessing a territory and thus was
unable to accord the PLO representation diplomatic status and
privileges. But he said Paris had to take into account the recent
decisions of the PLO in Algiers.
   Mitterrand did not indicate when the change would be made.
   There are two ``general delegations'' in Paris, representing
North Korea and Quebec. The PLO currently operates an ``office of
liaison and information,'' directed by Ibrahim Souss.
   A French Foreign Ministry official said a ``general delegation''
was a title that did not carry the same status and privileges as a
diplomatic mission. The official was unable to specify exactly what
the change would mean, but said the move clearly was a ``significant
and symbolic gesture toward the PLO.''
   On Nov. 15, the Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament
in exile, declared an independent Palestine, without specifying its
borders, accepted unequivocally U.N. Resolution 242, implicitly
recognizing Israel, and renounced terrorism.
   Even more explicit statements on recognition of Israel and
denunciation of terrorism were pronounced by PLO Chairman Yasser
Arafat in Geneva last month, prompting the United States to make its
first official contact with the guerrilla organization.
   Dozens of countries have recognized the state of Palestine, as
represented by the PLO.
   Mitterrand said the declarations by the PLO at Algiers
``unquestionably advanced things.''
   ``If there is no Palestinian country today, there is a
renaissance of the Palestinian nation,'' the president said.
   Asked about an eventual meeting with Arafat, Mitterrand said: ``I
certainly would not refuse, under conditions that I would define.''
</TEXT>
