<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     01-05 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every day's a holiday in Yogi Ward's taxi.
   ``It's a happy cab,'' says Ward, who decks out his cab according
to the season of the year. This being the New Year's season, the cab
is decked out with flashing light and tinsel that brushes
passengers' heads as they parade through the city.
   But that's not all. Ward plays cassettes of his own weather
reports, news items, and offers words of wisdom.
   ``If you're out there ... smoking, bebopping or doing something
that you're not supposed to be doing ... the police are out in
droves and they'll be waiting for you,'' says Ward's tape for the
New Year.
   Ward, 44, figures he'll keep the New Year's decorations for a few
weeks, before it's time to bring out the pink paper hearts, arrows
and cupids for Valentine's Day.
   ``Everyone loves it and nobody wants me to take the decorations
down,'' he said. ``People are waving at me down the street. I had a
police paddy wagon wave at me. State troopers wave at me. An
ambulance tipped their lights at me.''
   Beverly Morris, a 36-year-old advertising saleswoman, has been a
Ward customer for about five years.
   ``It's a nice refreshing thing,'' she said. But even Mrs. Morris
admitted that she occasionally gets tired of the hoopla.
   ``Sometimes I have to act like I'm asleep,'' she said. ``He'll
just keep talking.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREENSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Luckily for the Howard family, Christmas
only comes once a year.
   The Howards awoke last weekend to dozens of telephone calls from
people eager to sell their Christmas trees. The Howards were
somewhat surprised, since they had no interest in buying Christmas
trees, even ones that were only used once.
   The family soon tracked down the source of the calls: a
classified ad in the Tribune-Review of Greensburg. It read:
``Wanted: used Christmas trees. Will pay $5-$10 ea.'' The ad
included the Howards' telephone number and Hempfield Township
address.
   Family members said they didn't place the ad.
   ``The first callers were nice when we explained the mistake,''
said Mrs. Howard, who declined to give her first name. ``But others
have called and gotten quite angry when we tell them we ... don't
want their trees.''
   She said one man demanded payment after telling her he had
collected more than 150 trees on a flatbed truck.
   ``He was one of the more angry ones,'' she said Thursday.
   The family has not yet discovered who placed the ad.
</TEXT>
