<FIRST>u a PM-AutoShow 1stLd-Writethru a0579 01-05 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Show, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0579,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Gives Toyota a Break in Lexus-Lexis Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf, `Mead won..' to OCRRECT to Jan. 30, sted 13.
A longer version moving on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court, ruling in a
trademark-infringement case, today spared Toyota Motor Corp. from an
embarrassing scramble to mask the nameplates on its Lexus luxury
cars premiering at a major auto show.
   But the court said the Japanese automaker cannot advertise the
brand nationally until the trademark dispute is settled.
   The ruling by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New York
came as Toyota unveiled its Lexus line at the North American Auto
Show here.
   Mead Data Central Inc., which provides a computerized legal
information service called Lexis, has sued Toyota over its use of
the name Lexus.
   Mead won a lower-court order barring use of the name, but Toyota
received a stay last week. Today's ruling by Circuit Judge Emilia
Kearse extends the stay at least until Jan. 30, when the court will
hear arguments in the case.
   Kearse ruled that Toyota may continue to use the Lexus name at
the auto show and at other expositions but cannot advertise the name
nationally in the meantime.
   Before the ruling, Toyota officials had nervously wondered
whether they would have to cover up the names of the cars at their
swank display booth.
   ``Essentially, they have given each side part of what it
wanted,'' said Charles J. Farouki, a Mead attorney.
   Arthur D. Gray, a Toyota attorney, said, ``We're pleased with the
result.''
   Reporters got a preview of the auto show in Detroit's Cobo Hall.
The opens to the public Saturday and runs through Jan. 15.
   ``Our most immediate job is to earn name recognition for Lexus,''
said Jim Perkins, senior vice president for Toyota Motor Sales USA,
the American subsidiary of the automaker. ``Unfortunately, we're
doing it the hard way.''
   The Lexus booth features two four-door sedans, the LS400 and
ES250, which cost from $20,000 to $40,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
