<DOCNO> AP890105-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1951EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-NATOMeeting     01-05 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NATO Meeting,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jet Training Move Being Explored to Ease Strains over West Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Air Force is considering
moving some jet fighter training missions to Morocco as a way to
ease the burden over densely populated West Germany, the Air Force's
European chief said Thursday.
   Gen. William L. Kirk, in an interview with The Associated Press,
also staunchly defended the need to keep up low-level training
missions to have a ``mission ready'' force in central Europe.
   The training missions have caused controversy in West Germany
because of military jet crashes in the country.
   The Air Force announced Kirk will retire in April. The
56-year-old Louisiana native will be replaced by Lt. Gen. Michael J.
Dugan, now based in Washington.
   ``We're looking at the possibility of moving some training
missions to Morocco,'' Kirk said in his office at the U.S. Air Base
in Ramstein. The base was the site of a fiery crash of an Italian
air force stunt team that killed 70 people at an air show in August.
   Kirk, the Air Force's commander in chief in Europe, said talks
between U.S. and Moroccan officials are at a ``very preliminary
stage.''
   ``We have on previous occasions deployed U.S. aircraft to Morocco
for joint training with the Moroccan air force,'' he said.
   Morocco, an Arab nation in northern Africa, is known for its
generally moderate, pro-Western stance. Kirk would not give any
other information about the possibility of moving training missions
there.
   The general said an ``export'' of low-flying fighter training to
other countries was one way to ease the burden on West Germany, but
he acknowledged that finding countries willing to accept more
training missions would be difficult.
   On Tuesday, NATO pilots resumed tactical flights over West
Germany after a three-week moratorium sparked by the Dec. 8 crash of
a U.S. military jet in the northern city of Remscheid. The crash
killed five West Germans and the U.S. pilot.
   Low-level flights are defined as those involving dives below 250
feet, but in the public debate the term has been blurred to the
extent that it sometimes includes flights below 10,000 feet.
   The U.S. Air Force reduced low-flying missions by about 40
percent from 1981 to 1987 and has reached ``the point beyond which
we can't reduce any further and still maintain mission-ready
status,'' Kirk said.
   He added, ``I can understand the burden on the people.''
   However, Kirk said the recent flying moratorium had seriously
hurt the five fighter wings comprising 350 jets in West Germany.
   ``You can't just not fly for three to four weeks and then all of
a sudden turn it back on,'' Kirk said. ``We are at a point where the
civilian leadership within the NATO alliance needs to say one way or
the other whether or not we're going to maintain mission-ready
status in the Federal Republic (West Germany).''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
