<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1954EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BombHoax     01-05 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bomb Hoax,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Jailed For Making Bomb Hoax So Friend Could Catch Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICHESTER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was sentenced to a year in jail
Thursday for making a bomb threat against an airline so that his
girlfriend could catch her flight.
   Naveed Aslam admitted to giving false information that delayed a
British Airways flight from London to Casablanca for almost four
hours in August.
   Chichester Crown Court judge Peter Crocker said he sentenced
Aslam ``so that people will know if bomb threats are made in respect
of aircraft that (jail) is going to be the result.''
   British Airways asked for $38,000 in compensation.
   The incident occurred after a three-day visit by Aslam's
29-year-old girlfriend from Morocco. She overslept, and they were
hurrying to London's Gatwick Airport, when he pulled over to make
the call.
   Aslam, a 22-year-old store manager from southwest London, said
there was a bomb aboard Boeing 737, which had 89 people aboard.
   The flight was delayed 3 hours, 55 minutes as a result, but Aslam
was arrested at the airport when ticket office staff became
suspicious. It was not known if his girlfriend made her flight.
   Defending attorney Diana Ellis, said: ``If Mr. Aslam had been
aware of matters today back in August, his offense would never have
occurred.''
   She referred to the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 on Dec. 21,
which killed all 259 people on board and 11 people on the ground in
Scotland.
</TEXT>
