<FIRST>d p AM-BRF--Sununu-LastActs     01-05 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Sununu-Last Acts,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pig Manure and Small Claims Among Sununu's Last Worries As Gov.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House Chief of Staff-designate John
Sununu had other matters on his mind Thursday, his last day as
governor, namely a $5 claim against the state and security at a pig
farm.
   During their last meeting under his administration, Sununu and
the Executive Council approved paying Kenneth Kaslow of Jackson
$5.22 for damage to his car from a bottle that fell off a state
garbage truck.
   Though an auto-body shop estimated the repairs at $100, Kaslow
said that a can of touch-up paint would suffice.
   Sununu and the council also approved spending $2,500 for the
state police to protect Department of Environmental Services workers
at a pig farm in Mason. The department ordered tests to determine
the impact of a manure storage lagoon at the farm.
   But the farm's owner ``at times has been unreasonable and
threatening,'' said Alden Howard, environmental services
commissioner.
</TEXT>
