<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle     01-05 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Tours Inaugural Headquarters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President-elect Dan Quayle toured the
Inaugural Committee headquarters Thursday, picked up his
personalized ``QUAYLE'' license plate and deflected queries about
his role in the Bush-Quayle administration.
   ``You're asking the wrong question,'' Quayle said the third time
he was asked by reporters following him on his tour.
   The job, he explained, is ``vice president of the United States
of America. There are a lot of tasks, a lot of responsibilities and
a lot of serious challenges that I'll be working with George Bush
on. You'll see after I become vice president.''
   Taking his cue from a Bush line, Quayle said, ``Tune in and watch
exactly what we do. I am going to work as hard as possible to become
a very effective vice president, and I think that I'll be able to
meet that challenge.''
   Quayle and his wife Marilyn picked up tickets for the Inaugural
galas and thanked hundreds of volunteers during their tour of the
remote federal facility serving as the nerve center for the
inaugural events starting in a fortnight.
   The envelope-stuffers paused to greet the Quayles, but not all
work stopped.
   ``We have not closed down telemarketing,'' John Gartland,
director of tickets, confided to Inaugural co-chairmen Bobby Holt
and Penne Percy Korth as they escorted the Quayles on their rounds.
   Gartland's operation, selling tickets to all inaugural events
including coveted $175 tickets to the official Inaugural balls, will
bring in most of the $20 million needed to pay for all the pomp,
parades and other trappings of inauguration week.
   The red-white-and-blue Inaugural license plates are expected to
raise another $2.5 million. As the Quayles affixed their new plate
to the family van _ supplanting an ordinary Indiana plate with the
numbers ``35 x 60'' _ aides were distributing news releases on how
the public can buy Inaugural plates for $50. They can be used on any
road in America until March 31.
   There are also red Inaugural Christmas tree balls for $7.50,
bronze medallions for $29.95, neck ties for $30, cufflinks for $25,
a $30 frame for the Inaugural Invitation, and umbrellas for $20 _ or
$30 to fit golfers.
   ``It's people like you that make the clock go round,'' Quayle
told a roomful of envelope-stuffers at the start of the 75-minute
tour. ``You will have a small but very important part in that
historic occasion.''
   Elsewhere, he met 75 military volunteers, from major generals to
privates, all part of the 916-strong Armed Forces Inaugural
Committee. ``Am I back in the Senate Armed Services Committee?'' the
former Indiana senator quipped.
   Quayle said he had been briefed by Secretary of Defense Frank
Carlucci about the downing of two Libyan jet fighters in
Mediterranean Sea on Wednesday.
   ``I believe that our pilots took the responsive and defensive
action. It was fully justified. ... They were, in their judgment,
under hostile attack by the Libyan planes. They took appropriate
defensive measures,'' he said.
</TEXT>
