<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1957EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MountWilsonObservatory     01-05 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mount Wilson Observatory,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mount Wilson Telescope Given New Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the nation's oldest astronomical
treasures, the mothballed 100-inch telescope at the Mount Wilson
Observatory in California, will be recommissioned under a new
ownership plan for the facility, the Carnegie Institution announced
Thursday.
   The institution, which built the observatory in 1904 and has
operated it since, retired the big Hooker telescope in 1985 as it
shifted its priorities to development of more powerful instruments
at its new observatory in Las Campanas, Chile.
   For three decades, the Hooker telescope, completed in 1917, was
the world's largest, and the prototype for all modern-day reflecting
telescopes. Its 100-inch mirror, weighing 4{ tons, was cast by a
French bottle-making company.
   Despite mothballing the Hooker, the Carnegie Institution has
continued to operate three other research telescopes at Mount
Wilson. Under the plan announced Thursday, the entire observatory
will be transferred to the new Mount Wilson Institution, headed by
Carnegie veterans, over the next two years and will be independently
financed, largely from government grants.
   The arrangement was worked out primarily by George Preston,
former observatory director and now a chief scientist there. Preston
called the plan ``a rebirth for the observatory, and one that will
make the best use of the facilities.''
   Not only will the Hooker telescope be recommissioned within a
year, he said, but it will be fitted with high-tech computer
controls and instruments over two to three years. He said also that
overall research at the observatory will be expanded under plans to
double the operating budget, to $750,000, and to add several more
scientists to the five teams already at work there.
   During the 1920s, Carnegie astronomers Edwin Hubble and Milton
Humason, using the Hooker telescope, established that the ``spiral
nebulae'' in the night sky were other galaxies, made up of billions
of stars and located far outside the Milky Way, the galaxy that
contains the Earth. Thus, the size of the universe then known by
astronomers expanded almost a thousand-fold overnight.
   But growing light pollution from nearby Los Angeles has in recent
years virtually destroyed Hooker's biggest claim to fame _ that
ability to study faint, distant galaxies _ and was a major factor in
Carnegie's decision to focus its efforts in Chile.
   However, Preston and Arthur Vaughn said the Hooker telescope, at
5,700 feet altitude, remains an ideal tool for studying the sun and
for detecting planets around stars in the Milky Way. It also will be
used to study ``starspots,'' similar to the sunspot activity once
thought to be unique to the sun.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
