<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Plenum     01-05 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Plenum,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Committee to Hold Plenary Meeting Jan. 10</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party's policy-making Central
Committee will hold a plenary meeting Jan. 10 to set the slate of
party candidates for spring elections to a new government body, news
reports said Thursday.
   The ruling 13-member party Politburo set the date for the meeting
of the approximately 300 members of the Central Committee at a
session in Moscow on Thursday. A report on the Politburo meeting was
carried on the nightly TV news program ``Vremya'' and distributed by
the Tass news agency.
   Under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's governmental reform
approved by the Supreme Soviet parliament last month,
multicandidates elections March 26 will choose 2,250 members of the
new Congress of People's Deputies.
   The congress, in turn, will choose the president and a smaller,
more active Supreme Soviet.
   A third of the congress members will be elected from geographical
districts formed on the basis of equal population. Another third
will be chosen from districts based on their ethnic group. The final
third will be chosen from the Communist Party, Young Communist
League, trade unions, and other social and professional
organizations.
   Under the law the Communist Party is entitled to 100 deputies.
   The Politburo said it received recommendations for candidates
from individual party members and local party organizations as well
as the parties of the 15 Soviet republics, and expressed
satisfaction with how the nominations were made.
   ``It is noted that the selection of candidates has a democratic
nature, proceeds from below, that many party organizations have
taken an active party in it,'' the report said.
   ``It has been decided to submit the proposals for the
consideration of the plenum of the Soviet Communist Party Central
Committee to be held on Jan. 10, 1989,'' the report said.
   The report did not say whether any other issues will be discussed
at the plenum. Top-level personnel changes and major party policy
decisions must go to such a meeting of the Central Committee for
approval.
   Soviet officials already have said two other plenary meetings are
likely this year, one on agriculture and one on ethnic relations.
   The campaign for seats in the Congress of People's Deputies began
Dec. 26.
</TEXT>
