<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Derwinski     01-05 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Derwinski,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Chairman Asks FBI Probe into Nominee's Background</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate chairman on Thursday asked
President-elect Bush to direct the FBI to investigate a newspaper's
allegations that a Bush Cabinet nominee served in a GOP unit
``riddled with former Nazi collaborators.''
   A California paper, the Oakland Tribune, raised questions in an
editorial Dec. 28 about Edward Derwinski, Bush's choice to be the
first head of the newly created Department of Veterans Affairs.
   Through a spokesman, Derwinski said the charges amounted to
``guilt by association.''
   The editorial said that in 1972 Derwinski, a former Republican
congressman from Cook County, Ill., headed the executive board of
the Heritage Groups for Re-election of the President, active in
Richard Nixon's re-election campaign, and this year co-chaired
Bush's Coalition of American Nationalities.
   Several members of the coalition resigned last summer after the
Washington Jewish Week said they had pro-fasict or anti-Semitic
records during World War II.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., who will preside over the Senate
Veterans Affairs Committee's confirmation hearings on Derwinski's
nomination, asked Bush in a letter to direct the FBI to look into
the editorial's charges in the course of ``its customary background
investigation.''
   Cranston asked to see the FBI's findings before the Senate
hearings are conducted this month or in February.
   Derwinski has served in the State Department since 1983. He
became undersecretary of state for security assistance, science and
technology last year.
   Derwinski was not available for comment, but a spokesman, Bill
Anderson, said of the editorial: ``It is guilt by association. He
has had nothing to do with the hiring or the service of those
mentioned in this article. Anyone who examines his record in
support, for example, of Jewish organizations, or as a diplomat in
Israel, can categorically rule out any anti-Semitism on his part.''
   Anderson said Derwinski had lent his name to Republican ethnic
committees in every presidential election campaign since 1960.
   Cranston, in his letter, said he had talked about the editorial
with Derwinski on Wednesday during ``a nice meeting with him to
discuss the forthcoming nomination.''
   He sent Bush a copy of the editorial and wrote, ``As you can see
the editorial raises serious charges about his (Derwinski's) `record
of service in an organization riddled with former Nazi
collaborators' and `his alleged role in passing U.S. secrets to the
South Korean CIA in the late 1970s.''
   The editorial said those questions should be answered before
Derwinski is approved by the Senate.
   ``Those questions are apt, given Derwinski's record of service in
an organization riddled with former Nazi collaborators and his
alleged role in passing U.S. secrets to the South Korean CIA in the
late 1970s,'' the editorial said.
   ``The record certainly doesn't prove that Derwinski is a closet
Nazi sympathizer or a foe of democracy,'' the editorial said. ``But
it does call into profound question his judgment, in particular his
willingness to turn a blind eye to the background and beliefs of
notorious colleagues if they share his anti-communism.''
   The paper quoted Russ Bellant, author of a study published by
Political Research Associates in Cambridge, Mass., as saying that
``at least four people charged with war crimes were in leadership
positions'' of the 1972 Republican group Derwinski headed.
   The editorial also said that during a 1977 House investigation of
alleged South Korean influence peddling on Capitol Hill, Derwinski
appeared to be responsible for leaking to the Korean government the
defection of an official of the Korean Central Intelligence Agency.
   But Anderson said the House Ethics Committee investigated and
cleared Derwinski of tipping off the South Korean government.
   ``It's a non-event,'' Anderson said.
</TEXT>
