<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     01-05 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outgoing Government Cancels Rail, Electricity Price Hikes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslavia's outgoing government has
ordered the cancellation of sharp price increases of electricity and
rail transport, newspapers reported Thursday.
   A wave of steep price increases on other essential services and
foodstuffs hit Yugoslavs when shops opened after the New Year's
holiday.
   Yugoslavia's government resigned Dec. 30 following its failure to
curb a 250 percent annual inflation rate and solve the country's
other economic and social problems. It was the first federal cabinet
to step down since the communists took power after World War II.
   Branko Mikulic will stay in office as a caretaker premier until
the nine-member federal presidency names a new premier, expected by
the end of January. Mikulic then will appoint his new Cabinet by the
end of February, the state Tanjug news agency said Thursday.
   Early speculation in the state-run press on who will become
Yugoslavia's new premier centered on Ante Markovic, former head of
the Croatian government and a supporter of radical market-oriented
reforms, and Oskar Kovac, a prominent Belgrade economist and former
Cabinet minister who resigned over disagreements with Mikulic.
   Also mentioned was Slobodan Milosevic, Serbia's ambitious
hardline Communist Party chief, but it is considered highly unlikely
that he would get support from Yugoslavia's other five republics and
two provinces.
   The outgoing government has canceled a 70 percent price increase
of electricity originally due to take effect on Thursday after
widespread protests by consumers all over the country.
   Yugoslavia's state-run railroad companies, however, defied the
government's order to freeze their prices temporarily, charging 34.7
percent higher rates for passengers and 51.6 percent more for cargo
as of Jan. 1.
   ``As soon as they heard that the government had fallen, the
railroad companies decided to ignore the order to cancel the price
hikes,'' the Vecernje Novosti newspaper said.
   The price increases would boost the country's rampant inflation
and lead to further drop in living standards, which have already
fallen to the level of the mid-1960s, according to official
statistics.
   The last time the prices of electricity and rail transport were
considerably increased was in October.
   The new price increases ranged form 30 percent to 500 percent on
food, drinks, cars, newspapers and nearly all services.
   Nearly 1,400 strikes took place last year amid public calls for
the introduction of a multiparty system as a solution to the
protracted Yugoslav crisis.
</TEXT>
