<FIRST>u a AM-FloravsFauna Bjt   01-05 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flora vs Fauna, Bjt,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Framingham Garden Angers Animal Rights Advocates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRAMINGHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In what may be the ultimate no-win
battle among environmentalists, a wildflower preserve has been
killing muskrats that eat its rare flora, drawing the wrath of
animal rights activists.
   ``The muskrat is a very common animal, and some of the plants we
grow are very uncommon,'' David R. Longland, director of the
preserve, said Thursday. ``We have to manage for the best overall
conservation, and sometimes that favors plants over animals.''
   But the Framingham Humane Society contends there ought to be a
little more muskrat love at the 45-acre Garden in the Woods
preserve. It says that trapping muskrats merely encourages the
remaining ones to reproduce faster, providing little more than a
quick fix to the delicate problem of balance between flora and fauna.
   The society also maintains the underwater Conibear traps, which
break the muskrats' necks, pose a danger to humans and pets. It is
lobbying for a ban on the use of those and all steel-jaw, leg-hold
traps in Framingham, a suburb of 45,000 people about 20 miles west
of Boston.
   ``These are dangerous things. They don't belong in a civilized
urban environment,'' said society member Mary Anne Wyatt.
   Garden in the Woods was founded in 1931 and has been owned by the
3,400-member New England Wildflower Society since 1965. An island of
calm in the middle of Framingham, it contains 1,400 plant species in
a natural setting interwoven with three miles of footpaths.
   Longland, 37, said Garden in the Woods has been trapping muskrats
for at least five years, catching an average of one a year in its
lily pond. He said the preserve uses the spring-loaded, underwater
Conibear traps because they snap the animals' necks, killing them
instantly.
   ``The traps kill very humanely. We made sure of that,'' he said.
   Ms. Wyatt argued that the traps work correctly only if the prey
is the right size.
   ``They're totally non-specific _ they will catch anything that
comes to the water line,'' she said. ``Dogs, cats, waterfowl,
children.''
   Longland said Garden in the Woods decided to trap the muskrats
because they are voracious eaters of aquatic vegetation. Left
unchecked, he said, the furry, web-footed rodents threatened to wipe
out some of the colorful and unusual species _ like albino pickerel
weed, blue iris hookeri and pink pygmy water lilies _ that attract
20,000 visitors to the preserve each year.
   Carol A. Marchione, president of the humane society, said Garden
in the Woods should switch to using box traps, which capture
muskrats alive for relocating.
   But Longland said the preserve has already tried that _ as well
as chemical repellants, lining the banks of the lily pond with
stones, and covering rare plants with wire mesh.
   The muskrats spurned the box traps, even though the bait was a
tantalizing combination of apples scented with water lily extract.
Rain washed away the repellant, forcing repeated applications. When
the banks of the pond were packed with stones, the resourceful
creatures merely dug in from higher ground. And when the plants were
covered with mesh, the muskrats found a way to get through it.
   ``Nothing worked,'' Longland said. ``We've found that muskrats
will do whatever they have to do to eat.''
   Marchione said she believes that Garden in the Woods simply
misunderstands the problem with traps and has requested a meeting
next week to try to reach a solution.
   ``We're both conservationist-type societies, and we should be
able to work something out,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890105-0156 </DOCNO>
