<DOCNO> AP890105-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 2038EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-EducationSpending     01-05 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Education Spending,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Challenged to Spend Money for Education</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The education community on Thursday challenged
President-elect Bush to back up his promise to be the education
president by spending $10 billion more, including a down payment of
$2.5 billion.
   ``During the 1980s, education declined as a proportion and hence
as a priority in the federal budget,'' said Gerald Morris, president
of a 100-group coalition called the Committee for Education Funding.
``A four-year, $10 billion effort is needed to make education a
priority.''
   The committee said Bush should start by proposing $2.5 billion in
extra federal education spending for fiscal 1990.
   In the committee blueprint, most of the money _ $1.6 billion _
would go to programs for disadvantaged students of all ages, from
remedial tutoring to college tuition grants. Another $768 million
would cover the cost of inflation for all federal education
programs, while $150 million would be reserved for presidential
initiatives and modest increases in small existing programs.
   In addition, the committee said Bush should earmark an extra $500
million for Head Start, the preschool program for disadvantaged
children that is administered by the Department of Health and Human
Services.
   The committee plan comes amid congressional complaints over the
federal deficit and reports President Reagan will propose $35
billion in cuts in the budget he sends to Congress on Monday.
   The current Education Department budget is $21.9 billion _ $1.6
billion higher than fiscal 1988. The $2.5 billion increase sought by
the committee, to $24.4 billion, would be an 11 percent boost.
   ``We don't see that it's unrealistic or unattainable,'' said
Becky Timmons, vice president of the committee.
   Morris said reaction on Capitol Hill has been mixed. ``The coin's
still up in the air,'' he said. ``We'll see how it lands when it
falls.''
   Morris declined to comment on Bush's vow not to raise taxes or to
suggest where Bush should cut spending to finance the education
hikes. But he and others stressed they are encouraged by Bush's
campaign promises, his ``tone of moderation'' and his appointments
so far.
   ``We haven't had the luxury of working with the administration in
the last seven years because we've been on opposite sides of the
fence,'' Morris said. With Bush, ``we may have a very different and
warmer _ and certainly welcome _ environment.''
   Bush's priorities will become clear as he and his aides rework
Reagan's lame-duck document, and Education Department officials have
indicated changes will be made. Whether they will be substantial
enough to satisfy the education community is an open question.
   ``There's an education deficit analogous to the Grand Canyon,''
Morris said. ``To have someone throw in a shovel of dirt is not
going to solve the problem.''
   According to the committee, education spending accounted for 2.5
percent of the federal budget in fiscal 1979 but only 1.7 percent in
fiscal 1988. In the same time period, Pell grants to needy college
students went from covering 50 percent of all college expenses to 29
percent while the buying power of the maximum award declined 13
percent.
   Citing other aspects of what the ``education deficit,'' officials
said Head Start serves less than 20 percent of the children who
qualify for it; Chapter 1, the major federal program for
disadvantaged elementary and secondary school children, serves less
than half those eligible.
   In addition, they said federal money for educating handicapped
children now covers only 8 percent of per-pupil expenditures as
opposed to 12.5 percent in 1979.
   The committee is a non-profit, non-partisan coalition of groups
that represent more than 50 million students, parents, teachers,
administrators, presidents, librarians, counselors, trustees and
school board members. Virtually every major education group in the
country is a member.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
