<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1638EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Libya-WorldReax     01-05 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya-World Reax,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Gets Support, Condemnation for Chemical Weapons Claims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Libya Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States got support Thursday from an ally and an
adversary for its claim that Libya is capable of producing chemical
weapons.
   The United States has alleged that Libya has a chemical weapons
plant at Rabta, south of the capital, Tripoli. Libya claims the
plant is for manufacturing pharmaceuticals.
   British Foreign Secretary Geoffrey Howe, visiting Abu Dhabi, lent
support to the U.S. claim when he told a news conference: ``We do
have independent information on Libya's chemical weapons program
showing their plant as a very large one and it is no doubt intended
for chemical weapons production.''
   In Washington, the State Department welcomed Britain's
announcement.
   ``We certainly feel gratified that the British have talked about
evidence that supports the allegations that we have made on this
question,'' spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley told reporters. She declined
to say whether British officials had shared their information with
the U.S. government.
   In Moscow, a Soviet general gave his country's first
acknowledgement that Libya may be able to manufacture chemical
weapons, but he said such weapons would be in quantities too small
to wage war.
   As recently as Wednesday night, state-run Radio Moscow was
rejecting as ``groundless'' U.S. charges that Libya had developed a
chemical weapons plant.
   Lt. Gen. Anatoly Kuntsevich, deputy chief of Soviet chemical
weapons troops, told reporters in Moscow that ``Libya doesn't have
the industrial capacity to make toxic agents in sufficient
quantities to conduct warfare. But as far as a few kilograms
(pounds) of toxic agents goes, any serious chemical laboratory in
the world can make several kilos, say one to five kilos (five to 11
pounds) of toxic agents.''
   Kuntsevich spoke at a news briefing the Soviet government news
agency Novosti had called to discuss a five-day international
conference on chemical weapons that begins Saturday in Paris.
   Secretary of State George Shultz plans to use the meeting to
persuade more that 100 nations to impose sanctions on countries that
use poison gas.
   President Reagan has refused to rule out military action against
the plant, and Howe indicated Britain might not support such action.
   Asked if Britain would support a U.S. attack, the foreign
secretary declined to give a direct reply but noted: ``It must be
emphasized that chemical weapons capability is quite different from
the circumstances which we thought justified the action taken some
time ago.''
   He was referring to the April 1986 U.S. air raids on Tripoli and
Benghazi following charges of Libyan involvement in the bombing of a
West Berlin disco. Some of the U.S. bombers flew from bases in
Britain.
   Howe justified the downing of the two Libyan MiG-23 fighters by
U.S. Navy jets Wednesday as self-defense, and said the incident had
nothing to do with the Libyan plant.
   ``We've been given an account by the United States on what has
happened, from which it is clear that they acted in self-defense,''
he said.
   The Soviet Union denounced the action involving the Libyan
fighters. Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov was quoted
by Tass as calling the act ``a show of political adventurism and
state terrorism.''
   In Rome, Italian government leaders appealed for restraint by
both sides.
   In a statement issued at the United Nations, the 101-nation
Non-Aligned Movement condemned the U.S. act as unprovoked aggression
and ``state terrorism'' and called on the United States to withdraw
its naval forces. Libya is a member of the movement.
   Kuwait and North Yemen condemned the U.S. action, and Persian
Gulf newspapers called for action against the United States for
``enforcing the law of the jungle.''
   Iraq, Syria and Iran denounced the action in statements
Wednesday. But moderate Arab governments, which have long kept their
distance from Libya's leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi, avoided outright
attacks on the United States.
   Saudi Arabia, a key U.S. ally in the Arab world, only voiced
``deep concern'' at the U.S. action and urged ``self-control and
wisdom'' to prevent a further crisis.
</TEXT>
