<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 2043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Marcos     01-05 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Released From Hospital; Lawyers Work On Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos was
released from a hospital before dawn Thursday, after a week's stay
for treatment of congestive heart failure.
   Marcos, 71, left by ambulance, accompanied by his wife, Imelda,
and several physicians, said St. Francis Medical Center spokeswoman
Norma Kop.
   In previous hospital stays, newspapers, television and radio
stations were given notice of Marcos' arrivals and departures from
the hospital.
   Apparently stung by criticism that he sought media attention to
help his legal cause, Marcos was whisked from the hospital with no
fanfare Thursday. A Marcos employee contacted three hours after the
release claimed Marcos was still in the hospital.
   However, Marcos spokesman Gemmo Trinidad later confirmed that the
former president was resting at his Makiki Heights home. Trinidad
said he did not know why the move was made in secret.
   Kop said Marcos' doctors would issue no statement. ``He's gone,
that's all I can say and I don't think there will be any updates,''
Kop said.
   Marcos spent a week at St. Francis after suffering his ``second
severe case of congestive heart failure in a month,'' according to
Kop. He was hospitalized for nine days early last month suffering
the same symptoms.
   Congestive heart failure means the heart is too weak to pump the
amount of blood required by the body, causing chest pain, shortness
of breath and fatigue. It can be fatal.
   Tomas Gomez, the Philippine Consul General here, repeated his
assertions Thursday that Marcos exaggerated his medical plight.
   ``There is no doubt the guy is ill, but he already has a
mini-hospital at his home, so his hospitalization, and the media
hoopla that surrounds it, is a little fishy,'' Gomez said.
   Marcos' lawyers worked in Honolulu on Thursday on their strategy
for a Jan. 19 hearing in New York to determine whether Marcos is
healthy enough to be arraigned there.
   U. S. District Judge John Keenan is to base his decision on
medical evidence presented by the U.S. Attorney's Office, which
contends Marcos is healthy enough to travel, and testimony for the
defense, which says he's not.
   Marcos and his wife, Imelda, were indicted Oct. 21 on federal
racketeering charges accusing them of plundering the Philippines'
economy and stashing much of the money in the United States.
   Mrs. Marcos pleaded innocent to the charges and is free on $5
million bail, but Marcos has not been arraigned because of ill
health.
   The Marcoses have lived in exile here since they were ousted in a
February 1986 popular uprising.
</TEXT>
