<FIRST>r a AM-Vasquez     01-05 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vasquez,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pardoned Inmate's Mother Glad Son Is Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Mel in 2nd graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY O'DELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Her joy tempered by bitterness, the mother
of a pardoned prison inmate said Thursday that her son was
``railroaded'' into serving nearly four years for a murder he never
committed.
   ``I think we have every right to be bitter,'' said Mel Shapiro,
the mother of David Vasquez. ``The system is too political. If we
had been wealthy, we could have bought our way out of it like a lot
of other people do.''
   Vasquez, 42, was released Wednesday from the Buckingham
Correctional Center in Dillwyn, where he was serving a 35-year
sentence for second-degree murder, after Gov. Gerald L. Baliles
signed an order granting him executive clemency.
   Baliles granted the full pardon after new evidence surfaced
indicating that Timothy Spencer, convicted of murdering two other
women, also killed the woman Vasquez was accused of murdering _
Carolyn Jean Hamm, a 35-year-old Washington lawyer.
   Ms. Shapiro said both she and her son were too excited to sleep
on his first night at home, and Vasquez ``was too excited to open
his Christmas presents. They're still under the tree.''
   ``Every once in a while, I'd just reach out and touch him and be
glad he's at home where he belongs,'' Ms. Shapiro said in a
telephone interview from her Manassas home.
   Vasquez finally went to sleep about 6 a.m. and was still asleep
at midday.
   Ms. Shapiro said the family may take legal action, either against
the state or against the defense counsel who encouraged Vasquez to
plead guilty to second-degree murder to avoid a possible death
sentence.
   ``But no amount of money can ever erase the bitterness and
heartache we've been put through,'' she said.
   Ms. Shapiro said police and prosecutors ``railroaded and
brainwashed'' Vasquez. ``They told him they had his fingerprints,
and they didn't. They told him he was seen at the scene of the
crime, but he wasn't. He was at home with me.''
   Ms. Hamm was raped and hanged from a pipe in the basement of her
Arlington home in January 1984.
   ``The crime occurred 35 miles from where we live,'' Ms. Shapiro
said. ``David doesn't drive. How was he supposed to get over there?
That's a question they never did answer.''
   Ms. Shapiro said she is thankful that Baliles granted the pardon,
but is upset with him for not acting sooner. She had hoped her son
would be home for Christmas.
   ``He went on vacations and sort of put this under the rug,'' Ms.
Shapiro said. ``I tried to call him a number of times, but he was
never available. I never talked to anyone but his secretaries.''
   The pardon, recommended by Arlington Commonwealth's Attorney
Helen Fahey, was reviewed by the Virginia Parole Board, the
Secretary of the Commonwealth's Office and the governor's executive
staff. It was placed on Baliles' desk in October.
   The new evidence that led to the pardon involved DNA testing,
also known as ``genetic fingerprinting.'' In such tests, the
molecular structure of body fluds and tissues from a crime scene is
matched with that of the suspect.
   DNA tests were used for the first time to convict Spencer of the
murders of Susan Tucker of Arlington and Debbie Davis of Richmond.
Such evidence indicated that Spencer also killed Ms. Hamm.
   Spencer, who faces two death sentences, is scheduled to go to
trial Jan. 17 in Richmond Circuit Court for the murder of Dr. Susan
Elizabeth Hellams, 32.
</TEXT>
