<FIRST>u w AM-ThirdWorldDebt     01-05 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Third World Debt,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Banks Still Troubled By Third World Loans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although loans to Third World countries won't
cause U.S. banks to fail, the banks will still need to absorb
billions of dollars in losses, the House Banking Committee was told
Thursday.
   The major money center banks, responsible for 85 percent of the
outstanding loans to the six biggest Third World borrowers, should
double the reserves they set aside to cover their exposure, said
Kenneth Pinkes, a vice president of Moody's credit rating service.
   ``The debtor countries, which have born a significant share of
adjustment costs, appear less willing to continue the rescheduling
process,'' Pinkes said.
   ``More importantly,'' he said, ``as the possibility of a major
financial crisis appears less likely, the priority of the U.S.
government seems to have shifted from the need to help the major
money center banks to the need to maintain political stability in
Latin America.''
   The major banks, which saw their credit rating plummet after the
Third World debt crisis appeared in 1982, have set aside reserves
equal to about 25 percent of their exposure to cover losses on the
loans in the past two years.
   But they haven't written the loans off and are still trying to
collect interest or swap them for equity shares in companies in the
lesser developed countries.
   ``Prices in the secondary market and the magnitude of the
single-risk exposures suggest a reserve level of at least 50
percent,'' Pinkes said. ``If the loans are only worth 40 cents on
the dollar, ultimately the accounting is going to have to catch up
with that.''
   Federal banking regulators acknowledged the exposure of the nine
money center banks is still too large, but said they no longer face
the danger of failing if the borrowers default.
   L. William Seidman, chairman of the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp., said most of the regional banks have put the LDC (Less
Developed Countries) debt problem behind them.
   Manuel H. Johnson, vice chairman of the Federal Reserve Board,
said U.S. bank exposure to the 15 major Third World debtors declined
by $8.6 billion between July 1987 and the same month last year to
$76 billion.
   ``A disproportionate share of this reduction was accounted for by
large regional banks, as distinct from the largest multinational
banks,'' he said. ``Nonetheless, the top nine banks reduced their
total exposure over the year by $2.6 billion (to $53 billion).''
   Meanwhile, the debt servicing capacity of the six largest
borrowers _ Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Mexico, the Philippines and
Venezuela _ well exceeds the 40 percent value the secondary market
is now putting on the loans, Seidman said.
   Those countries account for $47 billion, or 85 percent, of the
Third World debt exposure of the nine money center banks _ Bank of
America, Manufacturers Hanover, Continental Illinois, Bankers Trust,
J.P. Morgan, First Chicago, Chase Manhattan, Chemical and Citicorp.
   ``Even in what surely could be considered a worst-case scenario,
each of the nine money center banks could write off 100 percent of
their outstanding loans to these six countries and, on an after-tax
basis, each of these banks would remain solvent,'' Seidman said.
</TEXT>
