<FIRST>r a AM-FireAftermath     01-05 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fire Aftermath,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town Prepares for Mass Funeral After House Fire Kills Ten</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REMER, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schools will close Friday as residents of
this tiny northern Minnesota town hold a mass funeral for six
victims of a New Year's Day house fire that also killed four other
people.
   Services will be held in the Northland High School gymnasium for
the four children of John and Nancy Watson and a neighbor's two
children, Robin and Michelle Bastle.
   John and Nancy Watson were away and the victims were asleep when
the fire broke out around 2 a.m. Sunday.
   The service will be televised by closed circuit to the elementary
school gym if there is an overflow crowd at the high school,
according to Mike Doro, principal of Remer Elementary School.
   Services for the other victims, Mrs. Watson's sister and
brother-in-law, Jean and Becky Smischney, and their two children,
Jay and Kimberly, will be held Saturday in Bemidji, where the family
is from.
   Doro said the mood at the elementary school is ``still quiet,
quieter than it has been at some times. Otherwise, things are pretty
much back to normal.''
   But members of the clergy and therapists trying to ease the pain
and bewilderment of the families and the town's 400 residents say
effects probably will linger long after the funerals.
   ``It left a big gap in this community,'' said the Rev. Jon
Erickson, pastor of Bethany Evangelical Lutheran Church. ``For the
first couple of days, people just kind of walked around speechless.''
   Investigators have ruled out a basement wood furnace as the
source of the blaze. Elmer H. Baltes, a deputy state fire marshal,
said faulty wiring still is considered a possibility, but the cause
may never be known conclusively because the intense fire destroyed
clues.
</TEXT>
