<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 2052EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StranglingProbed     01-05 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Strangling Probed,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Investigating Death Of Retarded Woman Who Strangled On Bed
Railing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials and police are investigating the
death of a retarded woman who strangled on a bedrail at a state
school where workers were supposed to check on residents every 15
minutes, authorities said Thursday.
   Esther Franson, 64, who had lived at the Fernald State School for
36 years, died Nov. 21 when her head got caught between one of the
bed's side rails and the mattress, said the state medical examiner,
Dr. Michael Blackbourne.
   Since her death, a direct care worker was fired, a night nurse
was suspended and remodeling was ordered for the bedrails. A state
Department of Mental Retardation report is due Friday or early next
week on the incident, agency spokeswoman Maureen Sullivan said
Thursday.
   The suspended nurse, Esther Olofson, said she complained
repeatedly about workers sleeping on the job in the past and is now
at risk of being fired because she didn't awaken the workers that
night.
   ``We have very stringent rules that residents are checked every
15 minutes by the direct care staff,'' Ms. Sullivan said. Such
checks, she said, include looking in on residents at night to be
sure their breathing is regular and that they are adequately covered
with bedclothes.
   State police also are investigating.
   The death was ruled accidental, Blackbourne said. He said
strangulations from bedrails is ``not an infrequent situation. We do
see it periodically.''
   Ms. Sullivan said the bed was a new model and that since Ms.
Franson's death such beds were ordered modified at state schools for
the retarded. She knew of no similar incidents.
   The spokeswoman said nurses who see direct care workers sleeping
are obligated to inform the workers' supervisors immediately.
   Ms. Olofson had been hired in September and was still on
probation when the death occurred, Ms. Sullivan said.
   Ms. Olofson said she was giving tube feedings to patients Nov. 21
when a worker came to her about Ms. Franson.
   ``I fully expected to find a woman who was having seizures,'' the
nurse said. ``But when I got there, it was the most horrible
nightmare. Her head got caught in the bedrail, and she strangled to
death.''
   Ms. Olofson said that when she walked through the building the
morning of Nov. 21 dispensing medicine and setting up intravenous
feedings, she saw several staff members asleep in chairs and covered
with sheets.
   She said she didn't awaken them because she was not authorized to
do so and in the past had been threatened by some workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
