<DOCNO> AP890105-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1707EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan     01-05 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebel Leaders Agree To Meet Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan-Analysis, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrillas agreed to meet with
a Soviet diplomat after receiving assurances Moscow will not insist
on a postwar role for Afghanistan's Communist Party, a rebel source
said Thursday.
   The source said the meeting Friday with Soviety Deputy Foreign
Minister Yuli Vorontsov is expected to focus on the transfer of
power from the Soviet-backed People's Democratic Party of
Afghanistan to a broad-based government.
   The composition of the government and how and when it will be set
up in Kabul also will be discussed, the source said on condition of
anonymity.
   The sides held their first round of direct talks last month in
Saudi Arabia.
   Before agreeing to the second meeting, the loose and quarrelsome
alliance of seven Pakistan-based Afghan guerrilla parties listed
five conditions that Vorontsov must meet before talks could begin.
   The source said the Soviets have agreed not to insist on a role
for the Communist Party in a broad-based government, but guerrilla
sources would not say whether the other conditions had been met.
   Those conditions are the unconditional withdrawal of Soviet
forces; the right of self-determination; a commitment not to hold
separate meetings with Afghan groups or individuals; and ``honesty,
sincerity and refraining from hypocrisy.''
   The list of conditions was released by the guerrilla-run Afghan
News Agency in Islamabad.
   A Pakistan Foreign Ministry said on condition of anonymity that
Vorontsov was given the list of conditions but refused comment.
   Sibghatullah Mojaddidi, chairman of the Pakistan-based Afghan
rebels, is to head the guerrilla delegation. Mojaddidi belongs to
the moderate National Liberation Front of Afghanistan.
   Mojaddidi took over the chairmanship Jan. 1. The guerrilla
chairmanship rotates among faction leaders every three months.
   Pakistan and the United States have been among the staunchest
allies of Afghanistan's Moslem insurgents, embroiled in a
10-year-old civil war with the communist government.
   In December 1979, the Soviet Union moved more than 100,000
soldiers into Afghanistan to back the Afghan troops. In April, the
Kremlin agreed to withdraw its forces by Feb. 15. Half had left by
August.
   Vorontsov said Wednesday the deadline could be pushed back if the
guerrillas continue to fight.
   He met the guerrillas in Saudi Arabia last month in a first round
of direct talks. The sides agreed to meet again in Islamabad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
