<FIRST>r a AM-TireTrouble     01-05 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tire Trouble,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Orleans Man is Tired of Tires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wheels of a man's misfortune began turning
about a year ago when someone knocked down a fence on a vacant piece
of his property and dumped a truckload of old tires.
   Others _ many others _ must have figured that's what the lot was
for.
   Now there are 5,000 old tires on A.B. Kupperman's lot and the New
Orleans lawyer is faced with more than just an eyesore. The city
landfill can't accommodate the tires and no one has a solution.
   ``I certainly didn't put the tires there,'' said Kupperman. ``And
I feel terrible about the neighborhood. It's an eyesore and a
problem for some of the neighbors.''
   A private company told him that it would take the tires away _
but he would have to pay $2 to $5 a tire. A collector in suburban
New Orleans said he would take them if a court hadn't ruled he can't
add to the 100,000 tires he already has, Kupperman said.
   City Health Director Dr. Brobson Lutz is sympathetic _ he's
agreed to delay any fines until February. But he said Kupperman has
to get rid of the tire pile, which is a haven for rats and
mosquitoes.
   If the tires caught fire, he said, it would cause a pollution
problem.
</TEXT>
