<FIRST>u a AM-US-Libya-Glance     01-05 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Libya-Glance,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summary of US-Libya Developments</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Libya Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of developments Thursday related to the United
States' downing of two Libyan jet fighters Wednesday over the
Mediterranean Sea:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>PILOTS' REPORT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Thr Reagan Administration said photographic evidence shows Libya
lied when it claimed the two planes shot down were unarmed
reconnaissance aircraft.
   Citing video footage from one of two U.S. Navy F-14 jet fighters
involved, Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard said photos showed one of
the Libyan fighters carrying four missiles.
   Debriefing of the Navy officers and a review of the footage shows
the Libyan aircraft five times ignored evasive maneuvers by the Navy
jets and did not break off even after the lead F-14 fired two
missiles, Howard said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>UNITED NATIONS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet ambassador Alexander M. Belonogov said Moscow ``gave a
warning signal to Washington,'' before the shooting incident to show
restraint and ``not to raise the tension in the area.''
   The United States told the U.N. Security Council the U.S. planes
fired in reaction to hostile actions that ``constituted an armed
attack.''
   Libyan Ambassador Ali Sunni Muntasser called the incident a
``premeditated act of aggression'' and said the Libyan fighters were
``unarmed, on routine reconnaissance, ordinary flying.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LIBYA REACTION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Libya put machine gun nests around public buildings and moved
fighter jets to safer desert areas, saying the downing of the two
Libyan planes was a prelude to a U.S. attack.
   Nearly 30 journalists who flew to Libya after the shooting were
detained at Tripoli airport, then sent back to Rome.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WORLD REACTION=
   British Foreign Secretary Geoffrey Howe indicated the account of
the shooting given by the United States showed ``it is clear that
they acted in self-defense.''
   The Soviet Union's Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I.
Gerasimov called the act ``a show of political adventurism and state
terrorism.''
   The 101-nation Non-Aligned Movement condemned the U.S. act as
unprovoked aggression and ``state terrorism'' and called on the
United States to withdraw its naval forces.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LIBYA-CHEMICAL PLANT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   British Foreign Secretary Howe lent support to the U.S. claim
that Libya has a chemical weapons plant saying: ``We do have
independent information on Libya's chemical weapons program showing
their plant as a very large one and it is no doubt intended for
chemical weapons production.''
   In Moscow, the deputy chief of Soviet chemical weapons troops,
Lt. Gen. Anatoly Kuntsevich, acknowledged that Libya may be able to
manufacture chemical weapons, but he said such weapons would be in
quantities too small to wage war.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>GERMANY-CHEMICAL PLANT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   West German financial examiners announced they had found no proof
to support U.S. allegations that a West German firm helped Libya
build the chemical plant near Rabta. The probe of the
Imhausen-Chemie company was ordered by the federal Finance Ministry
in response to the U.S. claims.
</TEXT>
