<FIRST>r p AM-DemocraticChairman     01-05 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democratic Chairman,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candidates For Top DNC Post Seek Labor Backing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five candidates to succeed Paul Kirk as
chairman of the Democratic National Committee met with labor leaders
Thursday in hopes of winning union backing.
   The meetings were at AFL-CIO headquarters in Washington, with a
number of political directors from the organization's member unions
meeting with each of the candidates.
   The political directors each will report back to their union's
president. The presidents in turn plan to meet next week with
AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland to determine whether labor will
issue an endorsement.
   Thursday's meetings were the official forum to seek labor's
backing but the candidates in the past few weeks have met regularly
with union leaders, according to AFL-CIO officials.
   Washington attorney Ron Brown, a veteran party activist who was
Jesse Jackson's 1988 convention manager and has worked for Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy, and Michigan state chairman Richard Weiner are
considered the front-runners to succeed Kirk.
   Three former Democratic representatives are the other candidates.
They are Jim Jones of Oklahoma, Michael Barnes of Maryland and James
Stanton of Ohio.
   Although the AFL-CIO has not decided as yet whether to endorse, a
number its building trades unions have endorsed Stanton.
   Brown, who also worked on Michael Dukakis' unsuccessful 1988
presidential campaign, has won the backing of several prominent
Democrats, including labor favorites Kennedy and New York Gov. Mario
Cuomo.
   The AFL-CIO endorsed Dukakis in the presidential race, although
the Teamsters union, an AFL-CIO affiliate, later backed Republican
George Bush.
   When the union presidents meet with Kirkland, no endorsement is
likely to follow unless they agree to present it as unanimous,
regardless of any debate in their closed session.
   The Democratic National Committee will meet on Feb. 9-10 to
choose Kirk's replacement. Union's delegates hold 46 of the 404
national committee votes but labor's influence is far greater than
those number would suggest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
