<FIRST>r a AM-Clerk-Dog     01-05 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clerk-Dog,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grocery Clerk Fired For Helping Stray Dog Gets Job Offers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENDALE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grocery clerk who was fired for helping a
stray dog when she was supposed to be working got her job back and
several other offers of work.
   Kathryn Westling, 20, of Glendale said newspaper and radio
reports Wednesday generated about 20 offers of possible jobs.
   ``I'm thinking of something like an animal hospital,'' she said.
   And the owners offered her her old job back at Sentry Foods
store, despite the dispute Tuesday with the store manager, whom the
owners said they plan to reprimand.
   ``I called Kathryn on the telephone this morning and told her we
wanted her to come back to work because she's a good cashier,'' said
Doreen Serio, co-owner of the store with her husband, Frank.
   Westling, a sophomore at the University of Wisconsin-Whitewater
who worked part-time at the store, said she was fired for taking too
long a break while she waited for the Humane Society to pick up a
stray, shivering German Shepherd she spotted outside the store.
   ``I told my manager I had a moral problem leaving the dog in the
parking lot,'' she said. ``And my boss said, `I have a moral problem
with you staying out with the dog and not checking.'''
   After a radio program focused on the situation, about 20 job
offers were called in, she said. ``They're sending me the list.''
Also, someone called her about the possible employment at an animal
hospital, she said.
   Westling said she would have liked to adopt the stray dog, but
``with three cats and a bird, there was no way.''
</TEXT>
