<FIRST>u i AM-Armenia-Quake     01-05 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Armenia-Quake,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Aftershock Reported in Quake Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong aftershock struck Spitak, the Armenian
town leveled by a killer earthquake Dec. 7, Tass said Thursday.
There were no immediate reports of further injuries or damage.
   The official Soviet news agency said the quake, registering 7 on
the 12-point Soviet scale, struck the previous day at noon.
   It said the quake's epicenter was 25 miles from Leninakan and 8.5
miles southwest of Kirovakan, between Spitak and the village of
Alavar.
   The Soviet scale registers earthquakes on the basis of observable
effects, and a quake registering 7 is regarded as very strong and
capable of causing cracks in the walls of stone buildings.
   Tass said nothing about injuries or deaths from the new quake,
and calls to government agencies and news organizations in the
Armenian capital Yerevan did not go through.
   However, most buildings in Spitak were destroyed by the Dec. 7
quake. Survivors have been evacuated and rescue workers are the only
ones remaining in the area.
   Officials say they have recovered about 25,000 bodies from the
wreckage of buildings in the earthquake area.
   Tass said four minor tremors were reported on the night of Jan.
3-4 and quoted seismologists as saying the tremors were part of a
normal pattern after the Dec. 7 temblor.
   Officials said the Dec. 7 quake had a force at its epicenter of
more than 10 on the Soviet scale. It registered 6.9 on the Richter
scale, a measure of ground motion on seismographs.
</TEXT>
