<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 2116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Burma     01-05 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Burma,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Gives Credence to Death Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government said sday it was looking
into reports Burmese students have died in custody since the
military seized control in Burma last September.
   ``We have received credible reports that a number of returned
Burmese students, who had fled Rangoon after the Sept. 18th military
takeover, were subsequently arrested and died while in the military
regime's custody,'' State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said.
   ``We do not have hard information on the precise numbers involved
nor actual evidence of deaths, but we're sufficiently concerned
about the reports ... that we will continue efforts to learn the
facts of the matter,'' Mrs. Oakley said.
   She said she thought 50 or fewer students had been killed, but
that she would have to check before she could even give an estimate
of the number.
   Mrs. Oakley didn't disclose when the students to whom she was
referring had returned.
   Thousands of students fled to the Thai-Burma border after the
military suppressed a pro-democracy uprising following the coup.
   Some 80 students returned home Dec. 26 aboard two Burmese air
force planes after receiving government assurances that they would
not be harmed.
   Unconfirmed reports earlier said students who returned on their
own had disappeared and were presumed killed by the authorities.
   About 7,000 students and others remain along the border with
Burmese rebels, spurning the repatriation offer.
</TEXT>
