<DOCNO> AP890105-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 2106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CarbofuranBan     01-05 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carbofuran Ban,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Proposes Ban on Granular Pesticide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency said
Thursday it plans to forbid use of granular carbofuran, a pesticide
used mostly to protect corn and sorghum from worms and insects,
because it is killing too many birds.
   The agency said it knew of more than 40 incidents where birds had
mistaken the pesticide granules on the ground for food, with up to
1,000 bird deaths in a single incident.
   In addition, eagles, hawks, harriers and other birds of prey have
been killed from eating the carcasses of smaller birds that died
after eating carbofuran granules, EPA said.
   At least 20 species of birds legally protected under various
federal laws have been killed by carbofuran, the agency concluded.
   About 6 million to 9 million pounds of granular carbofuran are
sold each year. Another 1 million to 3 million pounds are sold as
liquids or powders used in different applications and are not
involved in Thursday's announcement.
   About two-thirds of the granular form is used on corn, that form
of use less common than it was 10 years ago, EPA said. The main form
of granular carbofuran is sold as Furadan by FMC Corp.
   It is only the second time EPA has acted to ban a pesticide
solely because it was killing birds, though harm to birds was a
major reason for the ban on DDT in 1972. The other banned chemical
was diazinon.
   The agency said it did not appear that carbofuran posed any
chronic threat to humans, though like other pesticides, high
concentrations could make it a short-term poison.
   EPA began a special study of carbofuran in 1985, but that review
was slowed by the agency's conclusion that it needed to study all
granulated pesticides _ more than 100 chemicals _ for their effect
on birds to set priorities for further work.
   Field tests were recently completed and will be reviewed by the
agency's outside science advisers next month.
   ``Carbofuran was orders of magnitude (several factors of 10)
greater in toxicity than any other'' pesticide, said Al Heier, EPA's
pesticide spokesman. ``On a toxicity scale to birds of one to 10, it
was the only one rated a 10, and the next most toxic was a five.''
   The Fish and Wildlife Service advised EPA that carbofuran posed a
threat to three endangered species, the Aplomado falcon, Attwater's
greater prairie chicken and the Aleutian Canada goose, and could
harm the bald eagle, the whooping crane and the Mississippi sandhill
crane. The chemical should be banned in areas used by those species,
the service recommended.
   EPA said it knew of population declines in the red-shouldered
hawk, the loggerhead shrike, the field sparrow, Henslow's sparrow
and other species. ``Given its high toxicity and its widespread use
in agriculture, carbofuran is likely to be responsible for bird
deaths in those species'' and therefore ``can be an important
additive factor in the declines.''
   In Chicago, FMC Corp. spokeswoman Patricia Brozowski said
``natrually we're disappointed,'' but ``at the same time we are
confident ... that comprehensive and well-documented information
from the scientific and agricultural communities will support our
position that Furadan does not present an unreasonable risk to avian
species.''
   The agency said it had considered tightening the current use
restrictions on carbofuran but concluded such actions as additional
label warnings, limits on use to certain months or geographic
restrictions ``would not adequately mitigate the risk.''
   Growers who use carbofuran on their crops should incur higher
annual costs of $23 million to $33 million through increased crop
damage and higher costs for other pesticides, EPA said. But there
are so many choices for corn the carbofuran ban should have no major
effect on corn farmers, EPA said.
   The biggest single loss would be to rice growers, $12 million a
year in losses to the rice water weevil for which no other control
chemicals are available.
   EPA said it would receive public comment on its plans for 60
days. If it orders a ban, the manufacturer and other holders of
federal pesticide licenses may pursue administrative appeals. If
they do so, sales of the pesticide may continue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
