<FIRST>u i AM-Shultz-Arafat     01-05 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shultz-Arafat,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secretary Shultz Raps PLO Chairman for Death Threats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz sharply
criticized on Thursday a reported death threat by Yasser Arafat
against Palestinian Arabs who advocate an end to the uprising on the
Israeli-held West Bank and Gaza.
   ``We will observe behavior as the process proceeds,'' Shultz said.
   Last month, acting on the secretary's recommendation, President
Reagan ended a 13-year ban on U.S. talks with Arafat's Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   The decision was suggested by the State Department and taken on
the basis of statements by the PLO chairman that he had renounced
terrorism and recognized Israel's right to exist.
   Shultz said in a news conference aboard the U.S. Air Force jet
that brought him to Paris for a chemical warfare conference that not
all violence is an act of terrorism.
   But ``threats against people who try to move in a calmer and more
peaceful direction are acts of intimidation and fall much more into
the terrorism category,'' he said.
   Shultz stressed he had not seen the reported statement by Arafat.
But he criticized it, nonetheless.
   Bethlehem Mayor Elias Freij, one of the West Bank's best-known
moderates, proposed just before Christmas a one-year truce in the
Palestian uprising in the occupied territories as a step toward
peace.
   Freij told reporters this week he was withdrawing the proposal
after Arafat said in Saudi Arabia on Sunday that anyone trying to
stop the revolt ``exposes himself to the bullets of our people.''
   Shultz referred to a U.S. session with a PLO delegation in
Carthage, Tunisia, on Dec. 16.
   ``We have emphasized the importance of stopping terrorism. Now we
have to keep working on it to see that their behavior measures up,''
he said.
   Assistant Secretary of State Richard W. Murphy and other senior
U.S. officials have warned that the ``substantive dialogue'' with
the PLO would be cut off if terrorism recurred.
   Meanwhile, the State Department disclosed on Thursday that U.S.
diplomats were given the green light to exchange social pleasantries
with PLO representatives if they should meet them at parties.
   Arafat's comment came at a rally Sunday marking the anniversary
of his Fatah movement.
   Freij said he could not believe Arafat made such a threatening
statement.
   In Bethlehem on Thursday, soldiers ordered residents to paint
over graffiti threatening Freij with death.
   The slogans, signed by the radical PLO faction Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine, included ``Shame on all the traitors''
and ``The fate of Freij will not be better than that of Zafer Al
Masri.''
   Masri, mayor of Nablus, was killed in 1986 after indications he
might play a role in the peace process with Israel. The Popular
Front claimed responsibility for his slaying.
   Freij maintained that city workers and some shopkeepers
voluntarily painted over the graffiti. He denied reports he had been
in hiding.
</TEXT>
