<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1822EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka     01-05 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Troops Begin Withdrawal; Schools Reopen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian peacekeeping troops have begun
leaving this troubled island at the end of an 18-month mission to
disarm Tamil rebels and enforce a cease-fire, officials said
Thursday.
   Also Thursday, officials reopened more than 10,000 schools
nationwide that were closed two months ago after a wave of student
unrest.
   Officials confirmed that India has begun its long-awaited
withdrawal from the country.
   ``Some Indian troops have already left Sri Lanka during the past
two days, and another battalion is scheduled to leave Sunday,'' said
Gurjit Singh, a spokeman for the Indian High Commission, or embassy.
   India, the regional superpower, sent its troops to Sri Lanka in
July 1987, hours after the two countries signed an accord to end the
Tamil separarist war for an independent homeland in the north and
east provinces. More than 8,500 people have died since the fighting
began in 1983.
   But the biggest and most militant Tamil group, the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam, rejected the accord, saying that it failed to
meet their demands for self-rule.
   The presence of about 47,000 Indian troops in Sri Lanka triggered
resentment among Tamils and Sinhalese, the country's ethnic majority.
   The Indian troops soon became caught in the fighting, and more
than 625 soldiers have been killed.
   Shortly after his election last month, President Ranasinghe
Premadasa asked the Indian government to start pulling its troops
out of Sri Lanka.
   India announced on Sunday that between 2,000 and 3,000 troops
would leave the Indian Ocean island this week. It said the remaining
soldiers would be gradually withdrawn, but gave no timetable.
   Premadasa had opposed the accord, which was signed by his
predecessor, Junius R. Jayewardene. Both are Sinhalese.
   An extremist Sinhalese group, the People's Liberation Front, also
objects to the peace accord, saying it grants too many concessions
to the mostly Hindu Tamils, who make up 18 percent of the country's
16 million people.
   The Tamils contend the predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese denies
them jobs, education and money for development. The Sinhalese
account for over 75 percent of the population and control the
government and military.
   Meanwhile, principals reported satisfactory to good attendance at
the country's 10,400 schools, closed by the government on Nov. 10
after widespread student unrest, rioting and police action that left
at least 20 students dead.
   Police and troops were ordered to stay away from schools
Thursday, and there were no indications of trouble, said Elmo
Gooneratne, an Education Ministry official.
   Sri Lanka has a literacy rate of 86 percent, the highest in Asia.
   There was no indication when seven of Sri Lanka's eight
universities would reopen. The colleges closed in mid-1987 because
of student unrest.
   Schools and college campuses have been used by the People's
Liberation Front as recruiting centers for its cause.
</TEXT>
