<FIRST>u w AM-Reagan     01-05 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Backs US Pilots in Libyan Shootdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, back from California for the
final two weeks of his presidency, said Thursday that U.S. pilots
did the right thing in downing two Libyan jets over the
Mediterranean.
   ``Our pilots acted completely in self-defense,'' Reagan said as
he boarded Air Force One in Los Angeles after spending two weeks
trying out his new home there and visiting friends in Palm Springs,
Calif.
   The president's remarks were his first public statements on the
downing of the Libyan planes since he was awakened early Wednesday
morning at his Bel Air home to be told they had been shot down.
   Asked whether the pilots acted correctly, he replied, ``Yes,''
and added that the situation they faced was ``very obviously a
hostile threat.''
   As for Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi's charge that the United
States was engaged in terrorism, he said, ``I haven't believed what
he said for a long time.''
   In the 14 days remaining between now and the inauguration of
President-elect Bush as his successor, Reagan faces minor surgery,
will submit a fiscal 1990 budget and will deliver a farewell address
to the nation.
   The White House said he would enter Walter Reed Army Hospital for
surgery Saturday to correct a condition that causes his left ring
finger to bend inward.
   Dr. John Hutton, the White House physician, said the president
would return to the hospital on Sunday after resting overnight from
the operation, which is usually performed on an outpatient basis.
   Hutton said the operation should not cause any curtailment of the
Reagan's work schedule, although the president will wear a large
bandage on his hand and lower arm.
   Because recovery usually takes no fewer than two to three weeks,
Reagan was expected to be wearing the bandage when he joins Bush at
the West Front of the Capitol for the swearing-in of the new
president.
   The president's final budget, covering the fiscal year beginning
next Oct. 1, is to be submitted to Congress on Monday.
   Reagan has said that his budget will call for no new taxes, meet
the congressional goal of reducing the budget deficit to $100
million and aim for a balanced budget by fiscal year 1993.
   Bush is expected to submit amendments to the budget, embodying
his own deficit reduction plan, after he takes office. He also has
said he will not propose tax increases.
   Reagan will deliver his televised farewell address at 9 p.m. EST
Wednesday from the Oval Office.
   The president has spent at least part of 458 days in California,
including 345 at his ranch north of Santa Barbara, during his eight
years in office.
</TEXT>
