<FIRST>u i AM-Libya-UN 1stLd-Writethru   01-05 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya-UN, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0736,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Council Meets on Libyan Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `No resolution...' with two grafs to UPDATE with
meeting adjourning, possible resolution. Pick up 8th graf, `At the...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Libya Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council convened in an
emergency session Thursday and heard Libya and the United States
trade blame for the downing of two Libyan jets by U.S. warplanes.
   Libya's Ambassador Ali Suni Muntasser told the council that the
United States is pursuing a policy of ``blatant aggression'' against
his country.
   Libya repeated Thursday that the jets were unarmed reconnaissance
planes. Washington disputed that, contending two U.S. Navy fighter
jets acted in self-defense when they shot down the Libyan MiG jets
on Wednesday.
   ``Our actions were fully consistent with accepted international
norms of self-defense and my government considers this matter
closed,'' U.S. Ambassador Herbert S. Okun told the council.
   U.S. planes were ``faced by growing and imminent threat of being
shot down by intercepting Libyan aircraft,'' he said. ``We have
photographic evidence that clearly shows the Libyan aircraft were
carrying air-to-air missiles.''
   Libya sought the urgent council session and urged the 15-member
body to condemn the U.S. action as premeditated aggression. But the
United States, one of five permanent members with veto power, would
kill any resolution of condemnation.
   The session was adjourned after remarks by eight speakers made
comments, most of them Arab represenatives who condemned the U.S.
military action. Speakers included the Arab League, Bahrain, Burkina
Faso, Tunisia, Syria and Cuba.
   The session will reconvene Friday at 10:30 a.m. EST for further
debate, including comments from Britain and the Soviet Union. The
council is expected to consider a resolution of condemnaion being
drafted by Libya and the Non-Aligned Movement.
   At the meeting, Muntasser accused the United States of
``premeditated, deliberate aggression, a prelude to large-scale act
of aggression aimed at sriking the economic and military
installations in my country.''
   He protested the ``shooting down of two unarmed, reconaissance
planes on routine patrol near the Libyan coast. They were
intercepted by U.S. military aircraft which shot them down without
any justification.''
   Muntasser, responding to U.S. charges that Libya is about to
produce chemical weapons, said: ``Libya has no intention of
producing chemical weapons.'' He said Libya scrupulously abides by
all international bans and conventions against the use of outlawed
poison gasses.
   Before the meeting, Muntasser called the chief Pentagon spokesman
``a liar'' and rejected U.S. claims that videotapes show two Libyan
jets were armed and hostile before they were shot down over the
Mediterranean.
   ``I would say that he is a liar, not me. The man who said I am a
liar, he is a liar, because we are sure that our planes were not
armed,'' he told reporters.
   Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard had said Thursday that the Libyan
envoy was ``a liar'' by asserting that the MiG-23s were unarmed and
on reconnaissance.
   Muntasser suggested the United States had doctored the videotapes
or had fraudulently used film of other, armed Libyan fighters.
   ``We can as well bring pictures that our plane has no missiles,''
he said. Also Thursday, Soviet U.N. Ambassador Alexander M.
Belonogov suggested to reporters the two U.S. F-14 pilots were
trigger-happy and said the Kremlin warned the United States before
the event to exercise restraint with Libya.
   ``We deplore this accident,'' Belonogov said. ``Everything that
has a tragic ending is an accident.''
   He said it demonstrated that ``all military personnel should be
under strong instructions not to be too quick to pull the trigger.''
   ``Before that incident, we gave a warning signal to Washington to
show restraint in that area ... not to raise tension in the area,''
he said. ``We were concerned by this (U.S. anti-Libyan) campaign in
connection with the so-called chemical (weapons) plant.''
   The ambassador urged the United States to consider Libya's offer
of inspection of a plant 60 miles southwest of Tripoli, the Libyan
capital, that Washington says produces chemical weapons. Libya says
it manufactures medicines.
   U.S. officials have denied any connection between the air action
and allegations about the chemical plant.
   Meanwhile, Arab League sources in Tunis, Tunisia, said Libya also
made a formal request Thursday for a meeting of the league's Council
of Ministers.
</TEXT>
