<FIRST>r w AM-Kirkland-Bush     01-05 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kirkland-Bush,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>AFL-CIO President Urges Tough Bush Trade Stance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland urged
President-elect Bush on Thursday to use a new U.S. trade law
aggressively to punish nations considered to be violating workers'
rights.
   ``As good as it looks on paper, the reality remains elusive,''
Kirkland said in a speech to an international labor conference. He
was referring to provisions of the law that allow the United States
to close its markets to nations engaging in unfair trade practices,
including denial of workers' rights.
   ``The translation of principle into fact will require on our part
relentless work for a long time yet,'' Kirkland said. ``What we have
gained amounts to little more than words if not aggressively pursued
by an administration whose appointees really believe in these
things. Words, gestures, promises and formal procedures in and of
themselves do not bring relief to exploited workers nor freedom to
anyone.''
   Kirkland reiterated labor's request that the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade be amended to include ``a social clause'' defining
denial of workers' rights as an unfair trade practice. He said he
hoped that could be accomplished during the current ``Uruguay
round'' of trade talks but conceded past efforts have fallen far
short of success.
   In broader terms, he said, ``As we embark upon a new presidential
administration in Washington, a new opportunity emerges to frame a
foreign policy worthy of the purposes for which democratic
government was brought forth on this continent.
   ``There can be no bigger test of that policy than the extent of
its commitment to the advancement of human rights, beginning with
the basic rights of working people,'' Kirkland said. ``The
enforcement of the workers' rights provision of our trade laws will
and ought to be the crucible of that test.''
</TEXT>
