<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Volcano     01-05 0116</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Italy-Volcano,0119</SECOND>
<UNK>Mount Etna Shaken By Quakes</UNK>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mount Etna, an active volcano in eastern
Sicily, was shaken by two light earthquakes on Thursday, the Italian
news agency ANSA reported.
   It said a seismographic center in Erice, in northwestern Sicily,
recorded two quakes in the afternoon but that the tremors were so
light people in villages on the mountains slopes did not feel them.
   No immediate sign of eruption was reported.
   In 1986, Etna spewed ash, clouds of flaming material and lava
after a small eruption. It is considered Europe's most active
volcano.
   Another active volcano forms the basis of Stromboli, a tiny
island in the Aeolian chain off Sicily's northern coast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
