<FIRST>u i AM-Crash 2ndLd-Writethru a0747 01-05 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0747,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lockerbie Buries Its Own; Experts Review Air Security</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 20th graf, `Searchers so...' to UPDATE number released
for burial.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this close-knit town on
Thursday buried two of their own _ a 10-year-old girl and an
81-year-old widow killed when the flaming wreckage of sabotaged Pan
Am Flight 103 came crashing down.
   Transport Secretary Paul Channon, meanwhile, announced tighter
security measures for cargo and baggage mainly for U.S. airlines at
airports in Britain.
   Investigators were reportedly focusing on a dozen passengers from
airports in the Middle East believed to have boarded the New
York-bound Boeing 747 on Dec. 21, when a bomb killed all 259 people
aboard and 11 on the ground in the village of Lockerbie.
   On Thursday, several hundred mourners attended a Requiem Mass for
10-year-old Joanne Flannigan, whose parents are still missing and
presumed dead. The girl was the first of Lockerbie's victims to be
buried.
   Death, always harsh, is ``almost unbearable and unbelievable'' in
these circumstances, Rev. Patrick Keegans told the mourners at the
Holy Trinity Roman Catholic Church.
   The service was simple. Only two sprays of white flowers adorned
the church, and the only music was the unaccompanied singing of
``Abide With Me'' and ``The Lord is My Shepherd.''
   But the hearse that carried the girl's small coffin to the
graveyard was covered with wreaths and bouquets of bright flowers.
As it slowly pulled away from the church, three women comforted a
sobbing young girl about Joanne's age.
   A few hours later, mourners gathered again at the All Saints
Episcopal Church for the funeral of 81-year-old Mary Lancaster, a
widow for 26 years.
   On Wednesday, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, U.S. Ambassador
Charles Price and Pan Am executives were among 700 people who packed
into the Dryfesdale Parish Church of the Church of Scotland to mourn
all the crash victims.
   Channon announced the tighter security measures after a
closed-door meeting of the National Aviation Security Committee.
   ``As a result of the meeting this afternoon I have decided
immediately to take further steps to increase safety of the security
of cargo, also mislaid luggage and also to take further steps to
tighten up the existing regulations on cabin bags,'' he said.
   ``There will be more rigorous searching on American airlines, and
on any airline where we think the threat is commensurate but at the
moment it will be American airlines,'' he said.
   He gave no other details about the measures or the committee
meeting, but said he would soon take further measures which he would
not specify.
   London's Evening Standard newspaper reported experts probing the
disaster were concentrating on the 12 passengers of the plane who
began their trips from airports in the Middle East.
   ``The fear is that their baggage, checked in as destined for New
York at airports with much less stringent checks than London, may
have been put on to the doomed jet without further security tests,''
the report said.
   It said one may have been a suicide bomber or someone duped to
carry a bomb, the report said.
   Press Association, the British domestic news agency, said it was
told by an unidentified FBI spokesman in Washington: ``We are aware
of this report but we are not in a position to discuss our
investigation publicly.''
   Pan Am had no comment on the report.
   The government also announced Thursday a $1.8 million rebuilding
program in the Scottish town, where buildings were destroyed by
falling wreckage.
   Searchers so far have recovered 242 bodies from the crash and
have released 164 of them for burial.
   Officials say they believe some of the 28 still missing may have
been cremated in the crash that left a 30-foot-deep crater in the
town.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
