<FIRST>u w AM-US-LibyaRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0738 01-05 1246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Libya Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0738,1,000</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Citing Photographic Evidence, Accuses Libya Of Lying About
Planes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update with tape released, subs 24th graf ``At the Pentagon''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Photographic evidence shows Libya lied when it
claimed the two planes that the United States shot down over the
Mediterranean Sea were unarmed reconnaissance aircraft, the Reagan
administration said Thursday.
   Citing video footage from one of two U.S. Navy F-14 jet fighters
involved in the confrontation Wednesday, Pentagon spokesman Dan
Howard said photos of one of the Libyan fighters showed it carrying
four missiles on its fuselage and wings.
   ``It tells me that the Libyan ambassador to the U.N. is a liar.
That's the first thing it tells me,'' Howard told a packed Pentagon
news briefing.
   ``They've gone out yesterday and said repeatedly that those were
unarmed reconnaissance aircraft. Well, we have the pictures now that
they were not unarmed aircraft.
   ``They were obviously armed aircraft with obvious hostile intent.
We believe that our aircraft commanders behaved in a prudent manner
in defending themselves, in defending their aircraft and in
defending their ship,'' he said.
   The United States sent a ``straightforward message'' to Libya
``through diplomatic channels to let them know our point of view''
on the events over the Mediterranean Sea, a State Department
official said Thursday, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   No response from the Libyans has been received, the official
added. The official said the substance of the message, sent
Wednesday, paralleled information in Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci's public briefing on the incident and included the
asserting that the U.S. action was taken in self-defense.
   The official said the message was sent through the normal
chennels used by the United States to contact the Libyans _ the
Belgian Embassy, which represents U.S. interests in Tripoli, and the
United Arab Emirates Embassy in Washington, which represents Libyan
interests in the United States.
   At the United Nations, the Soviet ambassador, Alexander M.
Belonogov, told reporters Thursday that Moscow ``gave a warning
signal to Washington,'' before the American jet fighters shot down
the Libyan planes, to show restraint and ``not to raise the tension
in the area.'' He refused to elaborate.
   ``We deplore this accident,'' Belonogov said. ``It shows the
seriousness of the situation and that all military personnel should
be under strong instructions not to be too quick to pull the
trigger.''
   The United States told the U.N. Security Council that the U.S.
planes fired on the Libyan aircraft in reaction to hostile actions
that ``constituted an armed attack'' on American forces.
   U.S. Ambassador Herbert S. Okun made the statement in a letter to
the 15-member council, which held private consultations on Libya's
protest of the incident. But Libyan Ambassador Ali Sunni Muntasser
called the incident a ``premeditated act of aggression'' and said
the Libyan fighters were ``unarmed, on routine reconnaissance,
ordinary flying.''
   President Reagan, boarding his plane in Los Angeles to return to
Washington following a vacation, told reporters, ``Our pilots acted
completely in self-defense.''
   Asked about Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi's statement accusing
the United States of terrorist actions, Reagan sad: ``I haven't
believed what he said for a long time.''
   Meantime, the State Department on Thursday welcomed Britain's
announcement that it had independent confirmation that Libya is
building a plant to produce chemical weapons, as the United States
has alleged. Libya contends the factory will produce pharmaceuticals.
   Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley also confirmed that Libya
has attempted some back-channel contacts with the United States
recently, but she refused to define the substance of the messages or
how they were transmitted.
   ``The problem is not one of communication, the problem is the
policy and the conduct of the government of Libya, their policy
particularly in support of terrorism,'' she said.
   Speaking to reporters on a flight Thursday from Washington to
Paris for an international conference, Secretary of State George P.
Shultz hinted the United States may be willing to work out a deal
with Libya that would not require the plant to be destroyed.
   ``Obviously, if the facility were destroyed that would take care
of the problem, so that's our posture,'' Shultz said. But, he added,
``whether there is something else that can be done, we'll see.''
   He said the United States was not talking directly to the Libyans
about the plant but that the two sides were able to communicate
through intermediaries.
   Shultz also reiterated that the air incident was unrelated to the
plant dispute. He said the Libyan planes engaged in ``aggressive
behavior'' toward the American planes. But, he said, the incident
``must show Libya's uneasiness about the fact that they have
constructed this chemical weapons complex.''
   The Los Angeles Times reported Thursday that Libya had initiated
secret overtures to the United States in recent months in hopes of
avoiding an armed confrontation, with the most recent contact coming
less than 24 hours before the U.S. Navy planes downed the Libyan
aircraft.
   The Times, quoting unidentified officials, said the overtures
were rejected because they failed to address U.S. complaints that
Gadhafi's regime supports terrorism.
   At the Pentagon, Howard declined to make the Navy aviators
available, but the video footage was released, along with a longer
audio tape. Howard also released a blown-up still photo taken from
the videotape which shows missiles hanging from one of the MiGs.
   He said the crew of one of the Navy jets involved was flown to
Washington Wednesday night and had briefed both himself and top
military leaders Thursday.
   Carlucci said on Wednesday, just hours after the incident, that
two F-14 Tomcats had been flying a routine protective patrol for the
U.S. aircraft carrier John F. Kennedy well off the Libyan coast when
they were approached ``in a hostile manner'' by two MiG-23 fighters.
   The two American planes ultimately fired four missiles and shot
down both of the Soviet-made aircraft, Carlucci said, dismissing
suggestions the F-14s might have been preparing for an attack on a
chemical weapons plant now nearing completion inside Libya.
   On Thursday, Howard offered new details to bolster the American
account of the event. He said the F-14s picked up the Libyan planes
on their radar at a range of 72 nautical miles at 11:57 a.m. local
time.
   The incident was over by 12:03 p.m. local time, with the two MiGs
shot down and two parachutes sighted floating to the water, Howard
said.
   The Pentagon still has no information on the fate of the two
Libyan pilots, Howard said.
   Extensive debriefing of the Navy officers and a review of the
video footage shows the MiG-23 Flogger aircraft five times ignored
evasive maneuvers by the Navy jets and kept turning toward the
Americans ``on a collision course,'' Howard said.
   Even after the lead F-14 fired two Sparrow missiles, the two MiGs
did not break off their approach and instead turned and tried to
jump on the second F-14, the spokesman said.
   Those first two Sparrows apparently did not strike their target.
But a third Sparrow fired by the second F-14 claimed one of the
MiGs, and the lead F-14 was able to pounce on the rear of the other
MiG and down it with a heat-seeking Sidewinder missile, Howard said.
   Howard said the American pilots did not have any indication the
Libyans had turned on their attack radars, as had earlier been
supposed. But intercepted radio communications show the Libyans had
some type of radar on their planes operating and searching for the
F-14s, Howard said.
</TEXT>
