<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-AfghanRiot     01-05 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Afghan Riot,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Cadets Rampage; At Least Three Die</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan military cadets burned cars and smashed
furniture during a drunken New Year's Day rampage that left three
people dead, including an infant, in the city of Tashkent, a Soviet
newspaper said Thursday.
   Komsomolskaya Pravda said the violence began in Tashkent when 30
drunken Afghan cadets went to a market in the capital of Soviet
Uzbekistan to sell sunglasses, lighters and other hard-to-find items
on the black market.
   Soviets objected to Afghans becoming black marketeers during
these ``difficult days,'' the paper said.
   Fighting broke out at the Tashkent market when the Afghans began
insulting Soviets, the paper said. Police intervened and sent the
Afghans back to their dormitories around Tashkent, it said.
   The Afghans gave their version of events to other Afghans living
in the dormitories, and they began smashing furniture and windows,
the paper said. Another group of students, many of whom had smoked
``anasha,'' a narcotic, smashed a traffic police post, the paper
said.
   The Afghans jumped on the hoods of passing cars and lay down on
the street, Komsomolskaya Pravda said. Twenty cars were vandalized
and four burned, the paper said.
   Komsomolskaya Pravda, quoting a report on the ``debauchery''
printed in Uzbekistan newspapers, said a 6-month-old child was
killed ``as a result of the rampages.'' Two adults died of ``heavy
trauma,'' it said.
   Sixteen people, including seven Afghans, were hospitalized,
including one in critical condition, the paper said.
   The Soviets have been helping the communist Afghan government
battle U.S.-backed guerrillas for nearly a decade. Under a
U.N.-brokered deadline, the Soviets are to withdraw their troops
from Afghanistan by Feb. 15.
   Frictions have been reported before between Afghans and residents
of the Central Asian city of 1.8 million. Tashkent residents last
year told visiting Western journalists that some goods, such as tea
kettles, were taken off the market because Afghans were buying them
up and selling them for big profits in their homeland.
</TEXT>
