<FIRST>r a AM-ToyScam     01-05 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toy Scam,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Program For Needy Goes Awry As County Workers Receive Gifts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A justice of the peace, a deputy
constable and five Tarrant County workers said they thought they
were winners in a drawing when they received toys and clothing at
Christmas.
   But officials in charge of a giveaway program for the needy had
the employees investigated for fraud after their names showed up on
a list of recipients.
   District Attorney Tim Curry ultimately concluded that no crimes
were committed, the Fort Worth Star-Telegram reported Thursday. But
the district attorney said he was outraged by the bizarre events
that unfolded at the Polytechnic Subcourthouse and an adjacent
welfare agency.
   ``It looks like a comedy of errors and a case of really bad
judgment by a number of people,'' Curry said.
   The Christmas giveaway program, sponsored by Overton Park
National Bank, was administered by the Tarrant County Department of
Human Services.
   The problems apparently began when a receptionist at the
Department of Human Services, asked to find families to submit
applications for the toys, distributed request forms to workers at
the subcourthouse.
   The receptionist said she was never told only needy families
qualified.
   Applicants were asked the ages and clothing sizes of their
children and were asked to list their gift requests on a form
titled, ``Overton Park National Bank Christmas Wish List.''
   One worker said she asked for two pairs of snakeskin boots,
Barbie Dolls, a Lazer Tag game and a Big Wheel. She got the Big
Wheel.
   ``Our fear at this point is that it will leave a bad taste in
people's mouths about helping other people at Christmas,'' Human
Services Director Ann Hamilton said.
</TEXT>
