<FIRST>r w AM-NavyContract     01-05 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy Contract,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lockheed Awarded Contract To Build Prototypes Of New Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy on Thursday awarded the Lockheed Corp.
a $52 million contract to build two prototypes of a new
submarine-hunting patrol plane, indicating the project cleared an
internal Pentagon review.
   Last October, after a spirited competition, the Navy selected
Lockheed to develop a modernized version of its P-3C Orion
sub-hunter.
   At the time, however, the Navy said it would not award a contract
for full-scale engineering development until ``after formal review
of the program by the Department of Defense.''
   That review by the Defense Acquisition Board occurred last month.
Thursday's award of the contract means the board, comprised of the
Pentagon's highest ranking acquisition executives, approved the
project as ready to proceed despite a grim financial outlook on
Capitol Hill.
   The Navy said the $52 million was being awarded under a
``fixed-price, incentive contract'' and covered ``the design,
development, fabrication, assembly and testing of two prototype''
planes.
   ``Work will be performed in Palmdale, Calif., and is expected to
be completed in March 1993,'' the Navy added.
   The Navy expects the first prototype to fly in September 1991
with production deliveries beginning in 1994. The ``fly-away cost
estimate'' for each plane is $39.1 million.
