<FIRST>u a AM-CanyonMurders     01-05 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canyon Murders,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>7-Year-Old Murder Case Linked to Porn Star Reopens in Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A story of robbery and bad blood between drug
dealers was recounted Thursday in a preliminary hearing in a
7-year-old murder case in which the late sex-film star John Holmes
once was prosecuted.
   David Lind, a convicted drug dealer, told how he and Holmes and
two subsequent murder victims planned and carried out a robbery at
the home of Adel Nasrallah two days before a quadruple murder in
Laurel Canyon.
   Nasrallah, 59, a convicted drug dealer who goes by the name Eddie
Nash, is charged along with his bodyguard Gregory Diles, 40, in the
July 1981 slayings. The prosecution claims the bludgeon murders were
carried out in retaliation for the robbery.
   The case had been dormant since Holmes was acquitted of murder
charges in 1982. It was resurrected this year when Scott Thorson, a
former companion of Liberace, was said to have given authorities
information linking Nasrallah to the killings.
   Nasrallah's attorneys said Thursday they have been told that
Thorson will testify as the last witness in the preliminary hearing
which is expected to last seven to 10 days.
   Lind testified that Holmes, who was involved in drug activities
with Nasrallah, suggested the robbery, left a door open for the
robbers to enter and called to alert them when the time was right.
   ``We had been told by Holmes there would be a large amount of
cash and narcotics and jewelry,'' said Lind. Lind said he was the
first to enter the home, confronting Diles, who was serving
breakfast to Nasrallah.
   ``I believe I yelled, `Freeze! Police! You're under arrest!'''
said Lind who recalled carrying a San Francisco policeman's badge.
   ``I take it you were not a police officer at that time,'' asked
Deputy District Attorney Dale Davidson.
   ``Nor have I ever been,'' said Lind, who acknowledged numerous
arrests for robbery as well as drugs.
   Lind said he was handcuffing Diles when, accidentally, Lind's gun
discharged, wounding Diles. He said Nasrallah panicked.
   ``He asked permission to say a prayer for him or his children,''
he recalled. ``He was on his knees.''
   Lind said he and his accomplices, Ronald Launius and Roy
DeVerell, then forced Nasrallah to lead them to a floor safe in a
closet where they found heroin, cocaine, jewelry and ``tens of
thousands'' of dollars in cash which they stole.
   ``How did Mr. Nash appear?'' asked Davidson.
   ``A little upset,'' said the witness.
   Lind said he and the others returned to the Laurel Canyon house
and gave Holmes a share of their proceeds.
   Lind said he left town the next day and never again saw Launius,
37, or DeVerell, 42, alive. They were bludgeoned to death the night
of July 1, 1981, along with Lind's girlfriend, Barbara Richardson,
22, and another resident of the house, Joy Audrey Miller, 46.
   Launius' wife, Susan, survived the attack but was never able to
identify her attacker.
   Holmes, a top pornographic film star of the 1970s, died of AIDS
last March. He reportedly gave death-bed interviews to police who
were investigating the killings. However, Davidson said his
statements were not the basis of the new charges.
   Thorson, who was Liberace's companion from 1977 to 1982, made
headlines when he sued the entertainer for $12 million, claiming he
had reneged on a promise to support Thorson for the rest of his life.
   Liberace died of AIDs in 1987.
</TEXT>
