<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1940EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Chemical-Germans 1stLd-Writethru a0672 01-05 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical-Germans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0672,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Firms Accused of Helping Iraq, Another Cleared in Libyan Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUB grafs 4-5, `U.S. officials...' with 4 grafs UPDATING with
senior official's remarks. Pick up 6th pvs, `The Imhausen...' with minor
editing to conform and trim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Thursday accused five
firms of helping Iraq produce chemical weapons, but in a separate
inquiry cleared another firm of alleged involvement with a suspected
chemical weapons plant in Libya.
   Officials in Bonn, including Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher, had stated throughout a weeklong investigation of
Imhausen-Chemie that no evidence had been found to back up U.S.
claims the firm helped Libya build or outfit the Libyan plant.
   But the government's announcement of its findings involving five
other firms dealing with Iraq may have been intended to show
Washington that Bonn takes the issue of chemical weapons seriously.
   U.S. officials say the plant at Rabta, south of the Libyan
capital of Tripoli, is intended to produce chemical weapons. Recent
publicity surrounding Washington's allegations of West German
involvement have strained relations between the two NATO allies.
   A senior official of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian
Democratic Party, Volker Ruehe, appeared on a nationally televised
news show late Thursday to reject U.S. allegations that Bonn ignored
claims of West German shipments of dangerous chemicals.
   ``We have nothing to hide and we are ready to clear up
everything,'' Ruehe, deputy chief of the party's parliamentary
delegation, said on ZDF network. ``But what is especially bad is
that our political will is being doubted.''
   Government spokesman Norbert Schaefer told a news conference on
Wednesday that Bonn officials were not upset by the U.S. charges and
had investigated them with all seriousness.
   The Imhausen inquiry has been top news in West Germany this week,
even more so following Wednesday's U.S. downing of two Libyan jets
over the Mediterranean. Libya and other Arab nations have accused
the United States of provoking the dogfight in anger over the plant.
   West German officials have refrained from commenting on the U.S.
action as well as on the subject of the Libyan plant and its
purposes.
   On Monday, Schaefer confirmed that Kohl had been informed of
Washington's suspicion of West German involvement during his visit
there in November.
   Official inquiries were made, Schaefer said, although Bonn had no
concrete information to work with at the time, such as the names of
the firms alleged to have been involved.
   The Finance Ministry began its investigation of Imhausen's export
records Dec. 30, when the government first learned the company was
implicated by U.S. officials, Schaefer said.
   ``There is no evidence of illegal exports,'' the official in
charge of the Finance Ministry investigation, Freiburg district
director Willi Voegele, told reporters at the Imhausen firm on
Thursday.
   Juergen Hippenstiel-Imhausen, managing director of the company,
repeated his denials of the U.S. allegations, saying the firm had
``nothing, absolutely nothing to do with this `Libyan tale.'''
   The government made public Thursday the text of a Dec. 20 report
to Parliament on the investigation of similar allegations of illegal
exports against five West German firms accused of aiding Iraq in
chemical weapons production.
   From analysis of the materials shipped to Iraq, the report
concluded ``that in all probability, there is evidence that the
equipment in question can be used in production of materials for
chemical weapons.''
   The government said the companies under investigation are Water,
Engineer, Trading of Hamburg; the Karl Kolb company of Dreieich;
Pilot Plant of Dreieich; Preussag of Hanover and Heberger Bau of
Schifferstadt.
   No one answered the telephone at Heberger Bau on Thursday, and
lines to WET of Hamburg were constantly busy. Spokesmen for the
other three firms denied any wrongdoing.
   A spokesman for Preussag, Frederick Meyer, restated his firm's
position that no wrongdoing had been committed. He also questioned
the government's motives in making public the report amid the furor
over U.S. allegations that West German firms were involved in the
construction of a suspected chemical weapons plant in Libya.
</TEXT>
