<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     01-05 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Israeli Militia Expels Lebanese From Security Zone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Israeli-backed Christian militia on
Thursday expelled 31 Lebanese from the strip of land used by Israel
as a buffer zone with Lebanon, police said.
   The South Lebanon Army expelled the Lebanese for ``disrupting
security'' and for being members of the pro-Soviet Lebanese
Communist Party, a police spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   Israel has reported a rash of attempted infiltrations into Israel
from Lebanon by Palestinian terrorists. Israel and the South Lebanon
Army patrol the Israeli-designated ``security zone'' in south
Lebanon at the Israeli border.
   Police said those expelled included Najat Bishara, the mother of
a woman who allegedly shot and wounded Gen. Antoine Lahd, commander
of the South Lebanon Army, at his residence in the southern town of
Marjayoun on Nov.8.
   Lahd's reputed assailant, Souha Bishara, 21, is a member of the
Lebanese Communist Party.
   The police spokesman said the expulsions included seven families
from the villages of Kfar Hamam, Ibl el-Saki and Deir Mimas in the
six-to-10-mile-wide zone.
   Israel set up the security zone when it withdrew the bulk of its
occupation army from south Lebanon in the summer of 1985 to curb
cross-border guerrilla raids.
   Mrs. Bishara, talking to reporters in the southern port of Sidon,
said Christian militiamen ``came to my house in Deir Mimas at 5 a.m.
and told me that I'll have to leave the village.''
   She said she was driven in a jeep to the village of Kfar Tibnit
on the northern edge of the security zone, where she joined the
other deportees.
   The group walked to the nearby market town of Nabatiyeh, where
Moslem militiamen provided them with transport, she said.
   In another development, the Syrian-backed Shiite Moslem Amal
militia said Thursday it has banned using its Soviet-made Katyusha
rockets against Israel or in the security zone.
   ``Such action is incompatible with Amal's strategy in its
struggle with the occupier (Israel),'' said an Amal statement issued
in this southern Lebanon port city.
   The mainstream Amal, Arabic for ``hope'', which is at loggerheads
with the fundamentalist pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, has
long tried to shield the predominantly Shiite population of south
Lebanon from Israeli reprisals for Katyusha attacks.
   ``Firing Katyushas from liberated areas into occupied land is
totally forbidden,'' the Amal statement said.
   The ban followed an Israeli air raid earlier Thursday on an Amal
command post in south Lebanon in which eight Amal militiamen were
wounded.
   The Israeli army command said the post was used the day before
the attack by Syrian-backed Palestinian guerrillas in an abortive
raid on northern Israel. It said all three guerrillas were killed by
Israeli troops.
</TEXT>
