<FIRST>r a AM-TopMovies     01-05 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Top Movies,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>1988's Top Movies: `Roger Rabbit,' `Coming to America' and `Big'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedy was the big box office draw in 1988, with
a cartoon rabbit, an African prince and a kid trapped in a man's
body leading the ticket sales.
   ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' grossed $150 million to finish at No.
1, according to year-end figures released Wednesday by Exhibitor
Relations Co., which tracks movie successes and failures.
   The movie, co-produced by Walt Disney and Steven Spielberg's
Amblin Productions, mixed live action and animation.
   ``Roger Rabbit'' was followed by Eddie Murphy's ``Coming to
America,'' the tale of an African prince who goes to New York in
search of a bride, which netted $128.1 million. The No. 3 movie,
with revenues of $112 million, was ``Big,'' Tom Hanks' depiction of
a young boy trapped in a man's body.
   ``Nothing was actually predominant except comedy,'' Exhibitor
Relations chief John Krier said Thursday. There were six comedies in
the Top 10 list.
   ``There was some thought the (interest) for action-adventure
films had fallen off, but there were just less of them this year,''
he added.
   Two such films, ``Rambo III'' and ``Die Hard,'' were among the
top movies, although the high cost of producing ``Rambo'' meant
domestic distribution was unprofitable.
   Box-office receipts for 1988's top three titles were down from
1987, as no film surpassed the $150 million mark this year. A year
ago, three films _ ``Three Men and a Baby,'' ``Fatal Attraction''
and ``Beverly Hills Cop II'' _ all collected more than $150 million.
   Krier warned moviemakers could face problems in 1989 from
``overscreening'' _ too many theaters built too close together
during a recent boom in movie house construction.
   ``That can result in shorter play times for movies in invividual
theaters, meaning more product is needed,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, the holiday film season was down more than $5 million
from a year ago. Grosses from Nov. 29 to this Wednesday were $564
million, off from $569.8 million during the corresponding weeks in
1987. The last two weeks of 1988, with revenues of $221.6 million,
were off from the same period in 1987, with revenues of $257.8
million.
   Here is a list of the top films released in the 1988 calendar
year, followed by the amount they grossed. Hits released in late
1987 were not eligible. Box-office receipts for 1988 ended on Dec.
29, the last full week of the year.
   A complete comparison of 1988 box-office grosses compared with a
year ago would be released in mid-January, officials said.
   1. ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' a Disney film directed by Robert
Zemeckis and starring Bob Hoskins and a host of animated characters.
$150 million.
   2. ``Coming to America,'' a Paramount film directed by John
Landis and starring Eddie Murphy and Arsenio Hall. $128.1 million.
   3. ``Big,'' a 20th Century Fox film directed by Penny Marshall
and starring Tom Hanks and Elizabeth Perkins. $112 million.
   4. ```Crocodile' Dundee II,'' a Paramount picture directed by
John Cornell and starring Paul Hogan and Linda Kozlowski. $109.2
million.
   5. ``Die Hard,'' a 20th Century Fox film directed by John
McTiernan and starring Bruce Willis and Alan Rickman. $79.7 million.
   6. ``Cocktail,'' a Disney film directed by Roger Donaldson and
starring Tom Cruise and Bryan Brown. $76.8 million.
   7. ``Beetlejuice,'' a Warner Bros. release directed by Tim Burton
and starring Michael Keaton and Geena Davis. $73.3 million.
   8. ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' an MGM-UA film directed by Charles
Crichton and starring John Cleese, Jamie Lee Curtis and Kevin Kline.
$60 million.
   9. ``Willow,'' an MGM-UA film directed by Ron Howard and starring
Val Kilmer and Joanne Whalley. $55.8 million.
   10. ``Rambo III,'' a Tri-Star release directed by Peter Macdonald
and starring Sylvester Stallone and Richard Crenna. $53.7 million.
</TEXT>
