<FIRST>u a AM-Bozo'sBirthday     01-05 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bozo's Birthday,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bozo the Clown Celebrates 30 Years On TV</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUINN LOTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ambassador of Laughter, Bozo the Clown,
celebrated on Thursday his 30th year on television.
   The anniversary makes Bozo's show the longest-running live, daily
children's television program. A party to mark the occassion was
held at the Century Plaza Hotel.
   ``Everybody still loves me and still cares about me,'' said the
original Bozo, Larry Harmon, in a telephone interview. ``When you do
something good for the world, you do something good for yourself and
it all turns out wowee, oh wow, wow _ so good!''
   The Ambassador of Laughter, as Harmon likes to call Bozo, is
known around the world. In France, he's called ``Bozo Le Clown'' and
in Brazil he's known as ``Bozo El Payaso.''
   The daily, half-hour ``Bozos Show'' made its debut on Jan. 5,
1959. The show is televised to an estimated 28 million homes in 183
cities nationwide where kids can see Bozo, or a locally-franchised
version of the show.
   Harmon, who celebrated his own 64th birthday on Monday, came up
with the idea of having local actors portray Bozo in live shows
around the country. Harmon himself does not appear on television but
said he trains most of the actors on Bozo nuances.
   The show has produced 50,000 episodes; Bozo has appeared in more
than 10,000 parades; and so far, 200 people have portrayed the
snickering clown, including Willard Scott, the weather man for NBC's
``The Today Show,'' who started out as a Bozo in August 1959.
   Although the trend lately seems to be in maligning the clown,
such as the ``No Bozos Allowed'' bumper stickers and the derogatory
use of the word Bozo as an adjective for dumb or stupid, Harmon
believes there is a place in every person's heart for a Bozo.
   ``Bozo transcends time,'' Harmon said. ``Whatever the time Bozo
is with it. I've gone underwater, I've fought fire and flown way
above the Earth with NASA astronauts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
