<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0764 01-05 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0764,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Raid Thwarted After Israeli Man Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with attempted storming of villages,
details. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli man was killed in the West Bank, and
Jewish settlers tried to raid nearby Arab villages in revenge about
midnight Thursday, but troops ejected them and blocked roads into
Arab areas, Israel radio said.
   Earlier Thursday, 17 Palestinians were reported wounded by army
gunfire in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, and West Bank
residents said an Arab slain by gunmen was suspected of
collaborating with Israel.
   In Bethlehem, soldiers ordered residents to paint over graffiti
threatening death to Elias Freij, mayor of the West Bank city. The
slogans appeared after Freij proposed a truce in the Palestinian
uprising.
   The Israeli civilian's body was found Thursday night by the road
leading into the Jewish settlement of Yakir, and it appeared he had
been shot, a military spokeswoman said.
   The spokeswoman, who under regulations was not identified, said
the army and police were investigating all possibilities and had not
ruled out a guerrilla attack. Israel radio said the man had ``a
criminal past.''
   The man was a resident of the Tel Aviv suburb of Petah Tikva. He
was apparently shot as he waited for a ride at an isolated
crossroads leading from a main road into Yakir, 24 miles north of
Jerusalem. The time of the shooting was not known.
   The army closed off surrounding areas and searched for suspects,
the spokeswoman said. Army radio said troops imposed curfews on two
nearby Arab villages, Kifl Harith and Dir Istiya.
   If the man were killed as part of the 13-month Palestinian
uprising, he would be the 15th Israeli fatality. At least 347
Palestinians have been killed.
   Residents of Ariel, a neighboring Jewish settlement, took to the
streets at around midnight, Army radio said. They tried to block a
main road and threw rocks at Arab cars in anger over the killing,
the radio said.
   Israel's state radio said troops ousted settlers who entered an
Arab village and smashed windshields of cars.
   Thursday's shooting injuries occurred during two clashes in the
West Bank and during rioting in the Shati refugee camp in Gaza City,
according to Arab reports and hospital officials.
   In Shati, soldiers fired when they were stoned while trying to
drive through streets youths had blocked with rocks and burning
tires, Arab reporters said. Officials at the Shifa and Ahli Arab
hospitals said 15 Palestinians aged 15 to 37 were shot.
   An army official said on condition of anonymity that soldiers
fired in self-defense. ``They were in danger,'' he said.
   He said he had reports of 11 Palestinians wounded and did not
know of any soldiers being hurt.
   Two more Palestinians were shot in clashes between youths and
soldiers near the West Bank cities of Nablus and Tulkarem, hospital
officials said.
   Palestinian residents of Jericho in the West Bank said
25-year-old Bassam Barahmeh, who was shot to death Wednesday, was
suspected of collaborating with Israeli authorities.
   Army officials confirmed the death but said they knew nothing of
Barahmeh's activities.
   In Bethlehem, soldiers rounded up youths and some shopkeepers and
ordered them to paint over slogans threatening Freij, one of the
West Bank's best-known moderates.
   Just before Christmas, Freij proposed a one-year truce in the
uprising.
   He told reporters this week he was withdrawing the offer after
PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat said in Saudi Arabia that anyone trying
to stop the revolt ``exposes himself to the bullets of our people.''
   Arafat made the comment during a rally Jan. 1 marking the
anniversary of his Fatah movement, part of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   Freij said he could not believe Arafat had made such a
threatening statement. He denied reports he had been in hiding.
   The slogans, signed by the radical PLO faction Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine, included ``Shame on all the traitors''
and ``The fate of Freij will not be better than that of Zafer Al
Masri.''
   Masri, the pro-Jordanian mayor of Nablus, was slain in 1986 after
indications he might play a role in the peace process with Israel.
   In a telephone call to The Associated Press, Freij called the
threats ``absolutely meaningless.''
   Freij's offer was linked to Israel releasing 5,000 prisoners and
opening universities it closed nearly a year ago. The PLO rejected
the idea, and Israel made no formal response.
</TEXT>
