<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Saudi     01-05 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Saudi,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Groups Claim Killing Of Saudi Diplomat in Thailand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two extremist groups Thursday claimed
responsibility for the assassination of a Saudi Arabian diplomat in
Thailand on Wednesday.
   The two Arabic-language statements came from the Soldiers of
Justice and the Islamic Jihad in Hijaz and were delivered to the
offices of a Western news agency in west Beirut.
   Both groups in the past have claimed killings of Saudi diplomats.
   Saleh Abdullah Maliki, 35, was gunned down as he walked down a
side street near the Saudi Embassy in Bangkok on the way home to
host a party.
   ``The Soldiers of Justice declares responsibility for the
assassination of Satan Saleh Maliki in a commercial neighborhood in
Bangkok on Wednesday,'' said one statement.
   Police in Bangkok have said they were seeking a young
``Arab-looking'' gunman. They said no arrests have been made and no
motive firmly established.
   The statement said the Saudi third secretary was killed ``on his
way back after arranging some deals that serve the Great Satan
America and its protege Israel.
   ``Little did this Satan know that our heroic mujahedeen (holy
warriors) had been watching him,'' it said.
   The statement warned Saudi officials to stop ``tracking down our
mujahedeen and serving the hypocrites. Otherwise, you will be justly
punished.''
   Last week, the Soldiers of Justice claimed responsibility for the
attempted assassination of Saudi Arabia's consul in Karachi,
Pakistan.
   The group also claimed responsibility in early December for
kidnapping Belgian physician Jan Cools, who disappeared in south
Lebanon on May 21.
   It also claimed an arson attack on a Jewish club in Copenhagen,
Denmark, on Dec. 11.
   The Islamic Jihad in Hijaz said in its statement the group had
killed ``one of Saudi Arabia's secret service agents, the third
secretary at the Saudi Arabian embassy in Bangkok, Salah Maliki'' to
avenge the killing of four of its followers in Saudi Arabia.
   On Oct. 26, the same group claimed responsibility for the
assassination of a Saudi Arabian diplomat in Ankara, Turkey, saying
it was taking revenge for the deaths of the same four members.
</TEXT>
