<FIRST>r i AM-SolidaritySplit     01-05 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Solidarity Split,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rival Challenges Walesa At News Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa played down a
split in the independent labor movement on Thursday after a longtime
rival appeared uninivited at a news conference to press his
differences.
   Andrzej Gwiazda showed up at the Walesa news conference with a
copy of a statement from the ``Working Group of the National
Commission,'' a hard-line splinter group seeking less conciliation
with the government.
   According to a witness, Walesa appeared agitated when presented
with the group's document at his weekly news conference in Gdansk,
but did not address Gwiazda directly.
   ``What is happening now in Solidarity _ and some people call it a
split _ seems to me to be harmful to Solidarity but it is not really
dangerous and is only marginal,'' Walesa told reporters. ``I will
tolerate it as long as it does not pose a danger to Poland and to
the union.
   ``Today we are fighting for implementation of pluralism in
Poland. Later, after winning pluralism, all those groups will have a
place for themselves. But they should not disturb us in regaining
(legal status for) Solidarity, in reforms and in the struggle ... to
achieve one thing: pluralism for all.''
   Solidarity, which Walesa founded in 1980, is the Soviet bloc's
first independent labor movement.
   Gwiazda was an early colleage of Walesa but split with him and
unsuccessfully sought the union's top post before the government's
1981 crackdown on the union, when martial law was declared.
   The splinter group's name refers to the Solidarity National
Commission, which last met in 1981. It was a nationwide elected
assembly of local union representatives.
   Gwiazda organized the group at a Dec. 18 meeting in Gdansk with
40 people, including 16 former commission members. It advocates that
Solidarity become more confrontational.
   The group passed a resolution urging that the 200-plus commission
members be reassembled, a step that Walesa has dismissed as
unrealistic because many of them have emigrated or drifted away from
Solidarity.
   Solidarity is now governed by a National Executive Commission of
about 20 members called together by Walesa and representing regions.
Each region has its own executive commission.
   Gwiazda could not immediately be reached for comment, and no one
answered the phone at his home. But Gdansk Solidarity activist
Joanna Wojciechowicz read a portion of a statement co-authored by
Gwiazda that was among the papers given to Walesa.
   The statement says Solidarity is in danger of adopting a policy
of reconciliation that inhibits its ability to fight for workers,
and that some Solidarity activists are becoming private business
owners hostile to unions.
   ``Solidarity has become split into activists who trust Lech
Walesa ... and those who remain faithful to Solidarity,'' the
statement said.
   ``We are of the opinion that it is necessary for the good of the
working people and Solidarity's credibility to concentrate all
forces in defense of the economic interests of employees. We propose
a fight for maximum levels of pay increase wherever possible,'' the
statement said.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban and the official PAP news agency
have called attention to the split.
   Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski last month asked the
Communist Party Central Committee to reconsider the party's stance
toward Solidarity and said Walesa was a reliable partner for talks.
The committee members are to meet this month and give a response.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
