<FIRST>u a AM-InmatesReleased     01-05 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inmates Released,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freedom In The Night: $20 And A Bus Ticket</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 600 state prison inmates were
given their freedom just early Thursday under pressure from the
federal courts to ease overcrowding in Louisiana's lockups.
   Most inmates appeared happy to be free, but some complained about
the way they were released and about the midnight hour.
   Robert Dennis Hage, a convicted rapist, said he was taken to a
Baton Rouge Greyhound terminal after getting $20 by the corrections
department.
   ``There was no organization in all of this,'' said Hage. ``You
get $20 and they say `There's the door.' I've already spent $5 here
for a skimpy breakfast.''
   He was in the first contingent of 900 to be released this month
under an updated law that allows early freedom for inmates with good
behavior records.
   The law is one of the few approved by a reluctant Legislature to
ease overcrowding in a system that has more than 12,000 people in
nine institutions, with 4,000 held temporarily in parish jails
awaiting space in state lockups.
   Limits were placed on each state prison by the federal courts in
1975. By 1982 every lockup in Louisiana, incuding 178 local jails,
was under federal court order that prohibited overcrowding and
required better living conditions.
   Under the law, prisoners who have served half their sentences are
eligible for early release for ``good time,'' or exemplary behavior.
Wardens and other penal officials make the final decision on who is
released early.
   The early release law initially was passed in 1986, but it only
affected inmates held in state-operated prisons. That law was
amended in 1988 to cover all state prisoners regardless of where
they were held.
   Red tape and paperwork delayed the first early releases under the
law until Thursday, prison officials said.
   The gates were opened for the inmates at 12:01 a.m. and those
with no family waiting were taken to the Greyhound terminal in Baton
Rouge.
   Martha Jumonville, spokeswoman for the Department of Corrections,
said that the official release date was Jan. 5, which means 12:01
a.m.
   ``I think you'll find most of them wanted to get out as fast as
possible,'' she said. Some inmates disagreed.
   ``A lot of these guys are going to be back because they're going
home with nothing,'' said Hage. ``We were paid 4 cents an hour for
our labor. If they'd pay a little more, maybe they could give each
inmate $1,000.
   ``Sure, some would spend it all on hookers, drugs or booze. But a
lot of them would see that as a start. They wouldn't have to go home
and beg from a little sister for pennies.''
   ``We're up almost all night, get dumped here at 4:30 and there's
no overnight shelters open at this time,'' said another inmate, who
did not identify himself. ``We wait here and spend money we can't
spare.''
   ``I'm not happy with our criminal justice system,'' Gov. Buddy
Roemer said earlier at a news conference, adding that his executive
counsel will head a task force to study it ``all the way from
sentencing to rehabilitation.''
   Of the 575 released Thursday, 270 state prisoners were freed from
parish jails and the rest from the state-operated prisons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890105-0216 </DOCNO>
