<FIRST>r i AM-Morocco-Sahara     01-05 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Morocco-Sahara,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>King Hassan Has Second Meeting With Polisario Guerrilla Delegation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARRAKECH, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A delegation from the Polisario
guerrilla movement, which has been fighting Morocco for 13 years
seeking independence for the Western Sahara, met with King Hassan II
Thursday, official sources said.
   A near total blackout has surrounded the talks since the
Polisario delegation arrived Tuesday from its headquarters in
Algiers, Algeria. Thursday's meeting was the second between the
Polisario and the monarch.
   A brief statement put out by the Information Ministry Wednesday
after the first meeting said only that the discussions involved the
situation in the former Spanish colony ``in the perspective of the
decided referendum.''
   Both Morocco and the guerrilla movement have accepted the
principle of a referendum on the future of the northwest African
territory, annexed by Morocco after the Spanish withdrew at the end
of 1975. But the Polisario has demanded a pullout of Moroccan troops
first, followed by direct negotiations, refused by Morocco.
   The members of the Polisario delegation meeting the king included
Bechir Mustapha Sayed, foreign minister of the Saharan Arab
Democratic Republic declared by the Polisario in 1976. The
delegation also included Mahfoud Ali Beiba, prime minister, and
Brahim Ghali, defense minister.
   On Wednesday, the three Polisario delegates met with Moroccan
Foreign Minister Abdellatif Fillali, Interior Minister Driss Basri,
and Ahmed Reda Guedira, counsellor to the king.
   During their stay in Morocco, the sources said, the Polisario
delegation met with a group of Sahara natives who remain loyal to
the Moroccan monarchy, several of whom occupy official positions.
The sources spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Officials in Marrakech did not say when the Polisario delegation
departed. But the Algerian news agency Algerie Presse Service
reported from Algiers that the delegation left at the end of the
afternoon.
</TEXT>
