<FIRST>u i AM-TrainWreck     01-05 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Train Wreck,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Express Train Hits Truck In Yugoslavia; Seven Killed, 100 Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An express train traveling from West
Germany collided with a truck Thursday and derailed, killing at
least seven people and injuring about 100, the Tanjug news agency
said.
   Earlier in the day, five people were injured when another train
crashed into a bus along the same line, Tanjug said.
   The Munich-to-Belgrade train hit the truck about 25 miles west of
the capital at about 2:25 p.m., Tanjug said. The engine and six of
the 11 cars left the track, it said.
   Tanjug reported seven deaths and at least 100 injuries. Thirty
people were seriously hurt and had to be hospitalized, it said.
   Witnesses said the train was carrying about 400 people when the
crash occurred. Workers trying to recover casualties from the
tangled wreckage were hampered by thick fog and sub-freezing
temperatures.
   Cynthia Davis of Louisville, Ky., who works as a cook at a
Frankfurt, West Germany, hotel, suffered a broken arm in the crash.
   ``There were two sudden stops and then the crash,'' Davis, 24,
said by telephone from the Sremska Mitrovica hospital.
   Tanjug said the collision took place between the towns of
Golubinci and Putinci in Vojvodina.
   The truck's driver, Jure Gaspar, was arrested on suspicion of
having been responsible for the accident, Tanjug said.
</TEXT>
