<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Economy     01-05 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Economy,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabinet Approves Budget Cuts, Israeli Austerity Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cabinet on Thursday approved budget cuts
that will slash $67 million from defense allocations as part of an
economic austerity program designed to cut inflation and promote
growth, Israel radio said.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin resisted the move, which comes as
the army tries to put down a 13-month-old Palestinian uprising
against Israeli rule in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Communications Minister Gad Yakobi, who was on a special Cabinet
committee that hammered out the compromise, told Israel television:
``I think this is a fair compromise. Despite the economic crisis, it
does the maximum not to affect the army's degree of preparedness.''
   The military cutback is part of $611 million in spending cuts
proposed for education, health and other government services.
   The vote was 18-to-2, the radio said, with Education Minister
Yitzhak Navon and Industry Minister Ariel Sharon opposed.
   It said Navon strongly opposed cuts in school spending, and
Sharon felt the overall budget plan does not allocate enough money
for new Jewish settlements in the occupied territories or for
collective farms.
   Finance Minister Shimon Peres said the goal is to hold the
deficit in the new budget year, beginning April 1, to the same level
as in the current year. This year's budget deficit is projected at
about $722 million.
   The government has not yet released figures on what actual
spending for the new fiscal year will be. The current budget totals
$29 billion.
   Peres, who assumed office with the new Cabinet in December, began
his austerity program last week by devaluing the shekel 5 percent
against the dollar. On Sunday, he announced a further devaluation of
8 percent.
   The shekel was adjusted to boost Israel's flagging exports and to
stop a run on the dollar that was draining the nation's foreign
currency reserves.
   Peres also announced a sharp cut in government subsidies on such
basics as milk, chicken and public transport to keep this year's
deficit under control.
   He has proposed revenue-raising measures that include higher
taxes on new and luxury cars, larger health insurance payments, new
fees at medical clinics, registration fees for high school students
and higher tuitions at universities.
   Peres initially hoped to cut as much as $166 million from
defense, but ran into strong resistance from Rabin.
   Rabin told Israel radio he was agreeing to the cut because he
couldn't ignore Israel's economic difficulties. But he said his
ministry would have to shift funds from other military programs to
face the high cost of handling the Palestinian insurrection.
   A Defense Ministry official said on condition of anonymity that
the estimated cost of handling the uprising from the time it started
in December 1987 through next March was $222 million.
   Police Minister Bar Lev said 200 officers will lose their jobs
because of the $3.3 million reduction in his budget and pledged to
keep his officers focused on security duties, Israel radio said.
   Navon objected strongly to the proposal that the government
introduce high school registration fees ranging from 100 to 800
shekels ($55 to $440) a year.
   Such fees, he told Israel radio, ``will lead to dropouts.''
   Peres has set an inflation target of 9 percent by the end of
1989, about half the current rate. He also hopes to stimulate
greater economic growth in Israel. The nation's gross national
product grew just 1 percent this past year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
