<FIRST>u i AM-Gandhi-Assassins 3rdLd-Writethru   01-05 0808</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gandhi-Assassins, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0825,0830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ghandi Assassins Hang</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 16th, `Defense lawyers...;' to add grounds
for Satwant's appeal; Pick up 17th graf, `A third...' Adds byline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Sikhs were hanged Friday for the 1984
assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, whose death triggered
a wave of separatist violence that continues to plague the nation.
   Kehar Singh and Satwant Singh were pronounced dead at 8:15 a.m.
(9:45 p.m. EST), less than half an hour after they were taken from
their tiny cells on death row and marched to the chilly, rain-soaked
gallows at New Delhi's Tihar Central Jail, said a police official
who received confirmation from the prison.
   Two panels of five Supreme Court justices on Thursday each turned
down last-minute appeals by Satwant Singh, the only assassin who
survived, and Kehar Singh, convicted of helping plot the murder.
   The executions capped four years of legal maneuvering that began
after Mrs. Gandhi was gunned down on Oct. 31, 1984, apparently in
revenge for an army raid she ordered on the Golden Temple, the
holiest Sikh shrine.
   Hours before the executions, human rights activists and
opposition politicians appealed to Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi to
spare the lives of the men convicted in her mother's death. There
was no response.
   Satwant Singh, a 30-year-old former bodyguard of Mrs. Gandhi, and
Kehar Singh, a 54-year-old former government clerk, are not related.
Like all Sikhs, they take the Singh name, which means lion.
   Shortly before 8 a.m., the two men were taken from their 8-foot
by 8-foot prison cells. With their hands tied behind their backs and
their legs bound with iron chains, they were escorted by guards to
the scaffold in the open courtyard, 25 steps away.
   Caps were put on their heads and inch-thick ropes placed around
their necks. With the signal from prison Superintendent Jaidev
Ssarangi, the two hangmen pulled the bolts that released the
trapdoors.
   Satwant Singh and Kehar Singh spent their final hours visiting
with relatives and lawyers.
   ``He's happy and laughing,'' said Jasbi Kaur, Kehar Singh's wife,
after a 50-minute meeting with her husband. ``He told me to take
care of the family.''
   Satwant Singh's lawyer, R.S. Sodhi, described his client as
``very, very composed'' and then read a handwritten statement from
his client.
   ``There is no greater privilege for a Sikh to lay down his life
for the protection'' of the Sikh faith, the statement said. ``I wish
I could be born again and again and each time lay down my life for
this.''
   Fearing the executions could trigger a new outbreak of communal
violence, heavily-armed security forces were placed on maximum alert
in the capital and the northern states of Haryana, Himachal Pradesh
and Punjab, where Sikh militants have been waging a bloody,
6-year-old campaign for independence.
   Police were posted at bus and rail stations, often targets of
Sikh extremists. Many schools were ordered closed as a precaution.
   Preparations for the executions were completed last October after
the black-rimmed death warrants were signed.
   Defense lawyers had filed several appeals this week in a third
attempt to block the executions. All were rejected.
   Satwant Singh's appeal sought prosecution of two of Mrs. Gandhi's
security guards. He claimed the guards shot him after he was
disarmed and said their actions amounted to attempted murder.
   He did not appeal for clemency, but under Indian law his death
sentence was delayed automatically as Kehar Singh appealed.
   A third Sikh, Balbir Singh, also had been arrested, tried and
convicted on conspiracy charges and sentenced to death in the
assassination, but the Supreme Court overturned the conviction in
August for lack of evidence.
   More than 1,200 people were killed, most of them Sikhs, in the
raid to rout Sikh militants from the Golden Temple in Amritsar four
months before Mrs. Gandhi was killed.
   As Mrs. Gandhi lay dying, a guard named Beant Singh threw down
his gun and shouted: ``I have done what I had to do! Now, you do
what you must do!''
   Other guards opened fire, killing Beant Singh and wounding
Satwant Singh. Beant Singh is revered as a matryr by many Sikh
militants.
   Kehar Singh, a government clerk who was Beant's uncle, was
arrested a month later and charged with helping plot the
assassination, which caused anti-Sikh riots in northern India by
members of the Hindu majority. More than 2,700 people were killed,
nearly all of them Sikhs.
   Sikh violence has increased since, and at least 2,440 people were
killed last year in Punjab, the only Indian state in which Sikhs are
the majority. That was more than double the 1,032 victims in 1987.
   Sikh militants have fought since 1982 for a separate nation in
Punjab. They claim discrimination by Hindus, who make up more than
80 percent of India's 880 million people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
