<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Digital Equipment Corp. will roll out new lines
of desktop computers next week, demonstrating its growing conviction
that the world's second biggest computer maker cannot live on
minicomputers alone.
   Company officials revealed plans Wednesday for a three-pronged
attack that will include industry-standard personal computers,
high-powered technical workstations and software.
   ``It's probably the most significant desktop announcement we've
ever made,'' Donald McInnis, vice president of Digital's engineering
systems group, said in a telephone interview.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Travelers Corp. insurance companies
covering 22,000 California drivers are exercising a ``basic American
right to choose'' by pulling out of the state because of the
Proposition 103 insurance revolt measure, a company lawyer said.
   The statement was made Wednesday during a hearing called by the
state Department of Insurance in the aftermath of the November
passage of the measure, which would roll back premiums and place
other limits on the insurance industry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporate takeover activity in the United States
hit a record 3,310 completed transactions worth $282.4 billion last
year, a leading financial information service says.
   Statistics compiled by IDD Information Services said Wednesday
that the 1988 level of takeover action rose 28.6 percent over the
1987 level and 14.3 percent over the $247.1 billion in transactions
completed in 1986, the previous record year.
   IDD statistics also showed foreign investors, encouraged by a
weaker dollar, snapped up 325 U.S. companies valued at $54.8
billion, a 30 percent increase over the $42.3 billion spent in 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ELMHURST, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Keebler Co. said it will eliminate tropical
oils and lard from its cookies, crackers and snack foods to help
reduce cholesterol.
   The announcement Wednesday came a week after Pepperidge Farm Inc.
promised to removed tropical oils from its products, including its
popular ``Original Goldfish'' crackers, due to strong consumer
health concerns.
   Keebler said snack foods made without tropical oils and lard
should begin appearing on grocery and supermarket shelves in March.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank is raising interest rates for
more prosperous Third World countries to 7.65 percent annually, the
first such increase since the bank began lending at variable rates
in 1982.
   The rate will apply during the first six months of this year on
$37 billion worth of loans to about 70 countries, Sheldon Rappaport,
a spokesman for the bank, said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices staged a sharp rally Wednesday, as the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials climbed 33.04 to 2,177.68.
   The dollar advanced, bolstered by tension in the Mediterranean
and market expectations of strong U.S. employment data. Gold prices
declined.
   Bond prices were mixed.
   Copper futures prices rose sharply; precious metals futures
retreated; grain and soybean futures surged; energy futures were
mixed; cattle futures rose while pork futures fell; and stock-index
futures advanced.
</TEXT>
