<FIRST>r f PM-EconomyRdp     01-05 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Factory Orders Up Modestly; Stocks, Dollar Jump</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's report of a modest increase in factory orders in
November has led analysts to conclude that the economy is continuing
to grow moderately.
   Orders to U.S. factories for manufactured goods increased by 0.3
percent during the month, the Commerce Department said Wednesday.
   The economic report had relatively little impact on the financial
markets, which were looking ahead to what the Labor Department would
report on Friday about the nation's December unemployment rate.
   Stock prices staged a sharp rally Wednesday, rebounding from the
losses they suffered in the first session of 1989. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials, which fell 23.93 on Tuesday, climbed
33.04 points to 2,177.68.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 3 to 1 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks. But
demand for stocks was limited by fears that Friday's unemployment
report would show a big job gain, leading the Federal Reserve to
tighten credit to stave off inflation.
   The bond market responded indecisively Wednesday, helped by gains
in the dollar but showing concern about the possibility of a big
gain in December employment. The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond
fell 1-16 point as its yield edged up to 9.08 percent.
   Analysts said the dollar rose in response to news that U.S.
planes shot down two Libyan fighter jets over the Mediterranean Sea.
Investors take refuge in dollars in troubled times.
   The downing of the Libyan jets also sent oil prices higher, but
the gains quickly evaporated and the market ended the day on the
down side.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the February contract for
West Texas Intermediate oil, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, fell
28 cents to close at $17.08 a barrel.
   Before November's 0.3 percent gain in factory orders, orders had
risen 2 percent in October and fallen 1.9 percent a month earlier.
For the first 11 months of the year, orders were up 9.3 percent over
the comparable period in 1987.
   Cynthia Latta, an economist with Data Resources Inc. of
Lexington, Mass., said the factory orders added to evidence that the
economy is continuing to grow, although slower growth is expected
during 1989.
   In other economic news, Congress' budget agency said Wednesday
that unless new taxes or spending cuts are approved, the federal
deficit next year will be $141 billion, $14 billion higher than the
White House estimates and well in excess of deficit-reduction goals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
