<FIRST>r f PM-OilPrices     01-05 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Prices,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Fall, Gasoline Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures rose briefly on word that U.S. Navy
fighter jets had downed two Libyan planes, but prices closed lower
after traders' initial concerns subsided.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the February contract for
West Texas Intermediate oil, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, fell
28 cents Wednesday to close at $17.08 a barrel.
   Richard Redoglia, a trader with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures,
said the Mediterranean Sea incident led investors to snap up energy
futures in overseas trading and at the start of the day in New York.
Hostilities in the Middle East usually spark buying of energy
contracts because of the possibility of a disruption in oil supplies.
   In Wednesday's incident, U.S. officials said the Navy fighters
shot down two Libyan MiG-23 jets after the Americans were approached
at high speed in what Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci called ``a
hostile manner'' in international airspace.
   After the initial concern over the incident began to fade, prices
retreated, Redoglia said.
   ``While the market was strong through most of the day, by day's
end, the buyers were out and we found the market coming off,'' he
said, adding, ``The market seemed to be a little overbought.''
   Among refined products traded on the mercantile exchange, the
February contract for home heating oil fell 0.58 cent to settle at
52.65 cents a gallon.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline prices were little changed, with the
February contract gaining 0.05 cent to finish at 47.32 cents a
gallon.
</TEXT>
