<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 0205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Steelworkers Bjt   01-05 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steelworkers, Bjt,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profit-Sharing Dispute Settled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Steelworkers announced a settlement in a
dispute with LTV Steel Corp. over profit sharing and said that in
upcoming talks with other producers, profit sharing may be
appropriate but a basic wage increase is better.
   ``We certainly are opposed to the idea that while the CEOs and
executives and everybody else (are) making out pretty well, that the
workers should somehow be prevented from having an improvement in
their basic standard,'' USW President Lynn Williams said Wednesday.
   ``Our members were willing to make sacrifices in times of
trouble,'' he said. ``Our workers have a right to have an input into
their companies and share in things on the upside.''
   At a news conference outlining the union's philosophical stance
for talks later this year with Bethlehem Steel Corp., Inland Steel
Industries Inc., Armco Inc. and National Steel Corp., USW leaders
announced the settlement with LTV that will distribute an estimated
$100 million to about 18,000 active union members.
   They will be paid in April an average of $1.80 for each hour they
worked in 1988. In addition, LTV will distribute stock worth an
estimated 70 cents for each hour worked.
   A year of full-time work amounts to 2,080 hours per worker, so
the payments would amount to about $5,200 in cash and stock for a
fulltime worker.
   The company will also reimburse 38,000 retired union members for
payments they made last year toward health insurance coverage.
   Union officials said the profit sharing would be worth about $100
million, although the figure is tentative.
   ``It's really a vindication of our position,'' Bernard Kleiman,
chief counsel for the union, said at a news conference.
   ``Neither party achieved all of what it sought,'' David H. Hoag,
LTV Steel president and chief executive, said in a printed statement.
   LTV claimed its $1.3 billion third-quarter net loss would result
in a distribution of stock but no cash to the USW members. The union
argued the company's financial condition warranted a cash payout,
despite writedowns that contributed to the third-quarter loss.
   Local union presidents voted overwhelmingly Tuesday in Pittsburgh
to accept the settlement, but no announcement of the results was
made until Wednesday.
   The presidents were assembled to help set goals for upcoming
contract negotiations with four major producers. As union leaders
have declared previously, negotiators want the producers to give
back at least a portion of the wages and benefits USW members
sacrificed during two previous rounds of contract bargaining since
1983.
   With major steelmakers entering what is expected to be their
third consecutive year of significant profits, ``The opportunity ...
is so much better than what it otherwise might have been'' for union
members, said USW President Lynn Williams.
   The 134-member wage and policy committee did not prioritize its
goals for wage and benefit increases, job security and work rules,
he said.
   The timing of contract negotiations at LTV and
Wheeling-Pittsburgh will depend on the two companies' reorganization
in bankruptcy court. USX, the largest steelmaker, has a contract
that runs into 1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
