<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 0740EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     01-05 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises Against Yen, Shares Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar gained ground against the Japanese
yen today, while share prices declined on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 125.33 yen, up 1.28 yen from Wednesday's
close of 124.05 yen. After opening at 125.00 yen, the currency
fluctuated in a range between 124.92-125.60 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which reached a
record high of 30,243.66 points the previous day, lost 59.87 points
or 0.20 percent to finish trading at 30,183.79.
   The dollar has risen overseas in the wake of reports Wednesday
that U.S. planes shot down two Libyan reconnaissance aircraft over
the Mediterranean Sea.
   The U.S. dollar is considered a safe investment in times of
international tension and subsequent dollar-buying leads to a rise
in its value against other currencies.
   A Bank of Tokyo dealer, however, said the incident in the
Mediterranean was expected to yield only a ``temporary effect'' on
the exchange market.
   Michiyasu Yamashita of the Mitsubishi Bank in Tokyo said market
players began buying the dollar following the news that Emperor
Hirohito's condition had declined.
   ``The dollar has been in an upward trend since this morning and
investors were buying it due to uncertainty over the emperor's
condition,'' he said.
</TEXT>
