<FIRST>r f BC-Venezuela-Inflation     01-05 0111</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Venezuela-Inflation,0117</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venezuela Inflation Reached 35.5 percent in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inflation reached 35.5 percent in 1988
following a 6.8 percent increase in December consumer prices, the
Central Bank reported Thursday.
   The annual rate is the second highest in recent Venezuelan
history, after the 1987 record inflation level of 40.3 percent.
   The government had set 15 percent inflation as its goal for 1988.
   The Central Bank said December inflation, the highest on a
monthly basis all year, was led by rising prices for perishable
foods.
   Last year, food and tobacco prices rose by 52 percent while the
cost of shoes and clothing increased 35.2 percent, the bank said.
</TEXT>
