<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   01-05 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Open Lower; Grains Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices opened modestly lower today
amid profit-taking on the Chicago Board of Trade while grain futures
were narrowly mixed in early trading.
   Reports and rumors of new export business gave the markets a
healthy boost late Wednesday.
   The wheat market has been especially strong in recent weeks.
Wheat futures prices rose to new 7{-year highs Wednesday on news
that China had purchased 440,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at
subsidized prices.
   But analysts said the bullish trend also has brought a sharp rise
in speculative buying and open interest, which refers to the total
number of buy and sell orders that have not yet been cancelled out
by opposing orders.
   ``A lot of new longs (or buy orders) went into the market
yesterday and open interest went up dramatically, and I think that
spooked a few people,'' said Cathy Leow, a grain market analyst with
Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York. ``That's the reason
for a little softness in terms of price.''
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1 cent lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.46{ a bushel; corn was } cent
lower to { cent higher with March at $2.83} a bushel; oats were
unchanged to { cent higher with March at $2.46 a bushel; soybeans
were 1 cent to 4\ cents lower with January at $8.12{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .08 cent to .15 cent higher with February at
73.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .13 cent higher
with January at 84.20 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent to .45
cent higher with February at 46.82 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .68 cent to .88 cent higher with February at 44.25
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures fell on Wednesday while pork futures advanced.
</TEXT>
