<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1259EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv07   01-05 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 07,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For Release AMs Saturday, Jan 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Investors, Look To The Future!</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the economic expansion shows signs of
submitting to the unending pressure of Federal Reserve restraints,
many investors are growing concerned about the near-term performance
of stocks.
   They reason that if interest rates continue to rise _ short-term
government notes already yield well over 9 percent _ they will draw
funds from stocks. And if a recession comes, corporate earnings will
face big obstacles.
   The solution? Forget the near term; keep your eyes on the future.
Attach yourself to the long-term growth patterns and forget the
short-term squiggles. Spare yourself worries, save on broker's
commissions, defer capital gains.
   This is a segment of the long-term record, compiled by investment
adviser G.W. Perritt, a former college professor and founder of
Investment Information Services.
   Since 1944, per-share earnings of the Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock
index are 21.7 times higher, representing a 7 percent compound
annual growth rate. Annual dividends have grown too, by 6.5 percent
a year, or 15.6 times greater.
   The course wasn't steady; earnings fell at times. But overall, an
upward trend persisted. Per-share earnings averaged $1 between 1940
and 1945, grew to $2.84 in the next five years, doubled by 1968 and
doubled again by 1978.
   Today, the S&amp;P is around 270. Per-share index earnings are $21.70
and per-share dividends are about $10.11. Now project these figures
11 years into the future at the growth rates of the past
four-and-a-half decades.
   The result: By the dawn of the year 2000, per-share earnings,
growing at a 7 percent compound annual rate, become $45.35.
Per-share dividends swell to $20.22.
   We are just getting warmed up, says Perritt. Consider: if the
average price-earnings multiple of the S&amp;P index is applied to these
projections the index will be valued at 621 by the year 2000. That's
2.29 times the current level.
   Alternatively, a 22.9 multiple applied to a Dow Jones industrial
average of 2,150 points yields an average of 4,923.
   Remember, these aren't idle dreams; they are projections based on
what has happened in the past. And they do not even tell the entire
story.
   ``There's more good news,'' says Perritt in his newsletter,
``Investment Horizons.''
   If the index continually provides an annual dividend yield of 3.6
percent, and if you reinvest dividends when earned, you tack on
another 47 percent increment. It adds up to a total return of 237
percent.
   While 7 percent represents actual earnings growth over more than
four decades, some people might consider it too optimistic a goal
for the future. But step it down to 5 percent and you still get a
507 S&amp;P and a 4,035 Dow.
   It is difficult to stand pat in the stock market, considering the
daily excitement, the constant flow of investment advice, the
telephone calls of the brokers, the warnings, the fears, the fads,
the media's need for something new.
   But among many patient, reasonable folks, figures such as these
overwhelm the short-term fluctuations, and repeated studies of model
portfolios document the case.
   The in-and-out trader pays commissions to sell and then to rebuy;
the long-term investor keeps his money. Should there be profits, the
in-and-out trader must pay capital gains taxes; the long-termer
defers those taxes indefinitely.
   The wonderful irony of it is that the long-termer works less and
worries less, and gets paid better for the pleasure of it.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Saturday, Jan. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
