<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing index;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished stronger but below the day's
highs Thursday on the London Stock Exchange, boosted by speculative
buying of leading British stocks and by successive rises on Wall
Street.
   The stronger dollar continued to underpin the London market,
producing more gains in blue-chip shares. Takeover speculation
continued to enliven the market, generating some healthy trading
volumes in the food and oil sectors.
   The Financial Times 30-share index closed 11.7 points higher at
1,471.5. Volume totaled 448.0 million shares, up from 353.1 million
shares on Wednesday.
   The market opened on a stronger note following Wednesday's
33-point surge in the Dow Jones industrial average. The dollar
continued its upward move in European trading Thursday, supplying
further impetus for the major British dollar-earning stocks.
   Wall Street opened higher Thursday, providing a firm undertone to
the London market during the afternoon trading session. The Dow
average was up another 5.71 points at 2,183.39 when the London
market closed.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed up 6.5
points, or 0.36 percent, at 1,799.5, below the day's high of
1,803.2, up 10.2, which came just after noon.
   The Financial Times 500-share index ended at 1,013.09, up 4.53.
</TEXT>
