<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 2026EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Pipeline-Settlement     01-05 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pipeline-Settlement,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Eastern Expects $10.8 Million in Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Eastern Corp. and three partners in a
southwestern coal pipeline project have reached a $60 million
out-of-court settlement with Kansas City Southern Railway Co.,
company officials said Thursday.
   The settlement stems from a 1984 antitrust lawsuit involving
Houston-based Texas Eastern and subsidiaries of Bechtel Group Inc.,
Enron Corp. and KN Energy Inc., all partners in the ETSI Pipeline
Project.
   The lawsuit alleged that Kansas City Southern conspired with
other railroads to block the proposed $3 billion pipeline project
designed to transport coal slurry from Wyoming to Midsouth and Gulf
Coast utilities.
   ETSI agreed to settlements with Union Pacific and the Chicago and
Northwestern Railroads in late 1987 and with Burlington-Northern
Railroad Co. last November.
   The Santa Fe Railroad also is a defendant in the October 1984
lawsuit, but has yet to reach a settlement. A trial involving that
company is scheduled next Wednesday in U.S. District Court in
Beaumont.
   Texas Eastern is involved in natural gas and petroleum pipelines,
refining and marketing and real estate development.
</TEXT>
