<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 2054EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-Murdoch     01-05 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Murdoch,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publisher Moves Step Closer To Winning Hostile Bid For Collins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publisher Rupert Murdoch's News International PLC
continued to press its $725 million hostile bid for William Collins
PLC Thursday after a rival suitor dropped out of the fight.
   J. Henry Schroder Wagg &amp; Co., the merchant bank advising Collins,
a Scottish publishing group, held talks Thursday with Charterhouse,
the advisers to News International, after Groupe de la Cite,
France's second largest book publisher, withdrew a friendly bid on
Wednesday.
   Trade and Industry Secretary Lord Young said he would not refer
the News International bid to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission,
which could block the proposed deal.
   The French firm pulled out Wednesday because not enough
institutional shareholders were prepared to give irrevocable
undertakings to accept its proposed offer, Collins said.
   Mark Bogard, a Schroder executive, said Thursday's discussions
centered on ``what the nature of the assurances that News feel they
could give would be,'' regarding the future of Collins' business
within News International.
   Collins wants a commitment that it will be an autonomous unit
within News, that its core businesses would be expanded and that
Collins management would stay in London and Glasgow. Collins also
wants an assurance that it would spearhead News International's
English-language publishing interests worldwide, he said.
   It had received similar assurances from Groupe de la Cite, he
said.
   After Collins receives an answer from News International, Bogard
said, ``the board of Collins will have to decide whether those are
adequate'' and whether to recommend the bid.
   Groupe de la Cite had indicated in December it was prepared to
pay 880 pence, or $15.84, for each Collins voting share, valuing the
entire company at around 403 million pounds, or $725 million. Just
before Christmas, News International sweetened its own offer to
match exactly the French bid.
   Groupe de la Cite had approached News International Wednesday
with an improved offer for Collins on condition the Murdoch group
sell its 41.7 percent voting stake in Collins. But News
International refused and the French firm withdrew its offer.
   Murdoch and Collins jointly own Harper &amp; Row Publishers Inc. in
New York.
   News of the French withdrawal came after the London stock market
closed on Wednesday. News International shares finished unchanged on
Thursday at 213 pence, or $3.83, while Collins shares closed down 3
pence, 5 cents, at 882 pence, or $15.88.
</TEXT>
