<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pushed ahead Thursday to its
highest level since the October 1987 crash as traders awaited the
government's monthly report on the employment situation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 12.86 to 2,190.54,
surpassing its 1988 closing peak of 2,183.50 reached on Oct. 21.
   On Oct. 16, 1987, just before taking a 508-point drop on ``Black
Monday,'' the average stood at 2,246.74.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 3 in the
daily tally of nationwide trading in New York Stock Exchange-listed
stocks, with 837 up, 611 down and 509 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 174.04 million
shares, up from 149.70 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those
stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,
totaled 208.41 million shares.
   The data from the Labor Department Friday on employment for
December are expected to show continued strength in the economy.
   That presumably would give the Federal Reserve extra cause to
consider a further tightening of credit in its campaign to keep
inflationary pressures from reviving.
   Indeed, the Fed is thought by some analysts to have pulled in the
reins a bit this week ing in the parade will be nearly 12,000 people, from
bell
ringers to bagpipers, from baton twirlers to the California Raisins,
Mickey Mouse, Goofy and 47 members of the Alaska National Guard
Eskimo Scouts, dressed in Arctic gear with beaver hats.
   Daniel Denning, managing director of the inaugural parade, said
there will be 78 floats, 53 bands, 20 marching units, 24 horse
units, 3 choirs, 4 dancing units, 35 military units and one helium
balloon of Popeye the Sailor, official Boy Scouts spokesman.
   Bob Hope and pioneering pilot Chuck Yeager will lead the parade
as honorary grand marshals.
   The first float will feature a rippling replica of the American
flag, 20 feet high and 40 feet long. Pulling up the rear will be the
320 members of the Mormon Tabernacle Choir, seated eight abreast on
risers on a 100-foot float.
   In between will be a float depicting Washington's crossing of the
Delaware River, a Cinderella carriage pulled by two large white
horses and a Texas entry that will be ``practically as big as the
state itself,'' said one press release.
   Texas will be represented by a 10,000-gallon hat pulling a size
100 40E cowboy boot, followed by ``a corral of hootin' Texas
two-steppers'' and a matching boot, all strung out over 100 feet.
   The Indiana float is entitled ``Hoosier Pride,'' the same name
that Quayle gave his campaign plane. It will include a peace dove,
the Stars and Stripes and the inaugural theme of peace, prosperity
and independence.
   Among the 457 horses in the parade will be a mounted posse of
U.S. marshals on 30 golden palominos and six Belgian draft horses
pulling a Conestoga wagon.
