<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1734EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     01-05 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM, Ford Report Year-End Sales Surges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Corp. car
sales jumped in the last 10 days of December, contributing to
overall sales increases for the Big Three automakers in 1988, the
companies said Thursday.
   GM sold an average of 14,656 cars daily in the nine selling days
from Dec. 21-31, up 42.2 percent from the same nine-day period last
year.
   Ford said it sold an average of 8,781 cars daily for the period,
a 26.4 percent increase.
   Chrysler Corp. reported selling 3,497 cars a day in the late
December period, slipping 1.7 percent from late December of 1987.
   For the year, GM said it sold 3.641 million cars, an average of
11,823 a day for the year's 308 sales days, up 2.1 percent from
3.556 million _ an 11,581-a-day average _ in the 307 selling days of
1987.
   Ford said it sold 2.205 million cars, or 7,160 a day, in 1988, up
8.8 percent from 2.019 million or 6,579 a day, in 1987.
   Chrysler's 1988 car sales of 1.063 million or 3,450 a day, were
up 10.1 percent from 962,057, or 3,133 daily, in 1987, the company
said.
   GM said it set a light-truck sales record for the year,
delivering 1.741 million trucks, an average of 5,651 daily, for a
12.6 percent increase over 1987.
   Ford sold 1.462 million trucks, averaging 4,747 a day, up 4.2
percent. Chrysler reported sales of 955,619 light trucks, a daily
average of 3,102, for a 14.6 percent increase.
</TEXT>
