<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     01-05 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up; Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against most major currencies
Thursday, gathering momentum from its gains in the previous session.
   The U.S. currency rose on Wednesday following news that U.S. jet
fighters had shot down two Libyan war planes over the Mediterranean
Sea. The dollar tends to rise in times of world unrest because it is
seen as a safe investment.
   Audrey McNiff, a vice president at Irving Trust Co., said
Thursday the dollar retained the strength it drew from the
U.S.-Libyan incident.
   Analysts said traders' bullishness regarding the dollar was
dampened somewhat by comments from Helmut Schlesinger, vice
president of the West German central bank. He said the bank would
maintain a slightly restrictive monetary policy to thwart
inflationary pressures in the economy.
   Dealers took Schlesinger's remarks as a call for higher interest
rates in West Germany, which would boost the mark and lower the
dollar.
   But the dollar still managed strong gains.
   The currency began its day in Tokyo, rising 1.28 Japanese yen to
a closing 125.33 yen. Later, in London, it was quoted at 124.50 yen,
and in New York, it rose 1 yen to 125.975 yen from late Wednesday's
124.975.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.7985 West German marks, up from
1.7874; 1.5380 Swiss francs, up from 1.52815; 6.1415 French francs,
up from 6.0910; 1,318.50 Italian lire, up from 1,314.50; and 1.19025
Canadian dollars, down from 1.19265.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday's
prices, included: 1.7955 West German marks, up from 1.7875; 1.5195
Swiss francs, up from 1.5180; 6.1155 French francs, up from 6.0985;
2.0220 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0140; 1,316.25 Italian lire, up
from 1,313.00; and 1.1877 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1927.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7970 from $1.8065
Wednesday, and in later New York trading, sterling slipped to
$1.7940 from late Wednesday's $1.8090.
   Gold prices fell on domestic and overseas markets. In New York,
Republic National Bank quoted a bid of $408.25 for a troy ounce of
gold as of 4 p.m. EST, down from $408.50 late Wednesday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold edged down to $407.90
from late Wednesday's $408.70.
   Gold traded in London at a late bid price of $407.75 a troy
ounce, down from $409.75 late Wednesday, and in Zurich, Switzerland,
the late bid price was $407.20, down from late Wednesday's $409.40.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.22 to close at a bid $410.94.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.97 a troy ounce,
down from Wednesday's $6.01. However, in New York, a troy ounce of
silver rose to $5.965 from late Wednesday's $5.937.
</TEXT>
