<FIRST>r f AM-Drexel-Wisconsin     01-05 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drexel-Wisconsin,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wisconsin Suspends Business Ties With Drexel</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drexel Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Investment Board on Thursday
suspended business with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., the Wall Street
company that agreed last month to plead guilty to widespread
securities fraud charges.
   Marshall Burkes, the board's executive director, said the action
was consistent with a policy against doing business with a company
that admits or is found guilty of a felony.
   The Investment Board, which manages $18 billion in retirement and
other funds, paid slightly more than $500,000 a year in commissions
to Drexel Burnham, less than 5 percent of its annual bill for
commissions.
   ``They are a substantial dealer, but by no means a major
dealer,'' he said. He said the suspension was indefinite.
   ``We will reconsider the suspension if and when Drexel can make a
case that they have corrected their problems,'' Burkes said.
   Last week New York City suspended Drexel from participation in an
upcoming sale of municipal bonds, in what was seen as a signal that
other governmental money-raising authorities may take similar action
in the aftermath of the firm's agreement to settle criminal charges.
   Drexel agreed Dec. 21 to pay the government a record $650 million
in fines and restitution and plead guilty to six felony counts after
a two year criminal investigation of the firm by federal prosecutors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
