<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 1816EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneySupply     01-05 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Supply,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Supply Measures Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two narrower measures of the nation's money
supply rose in late December while a third, broader money supply
gauge fell, the Federal Reserve Board reported Thursday.
   The Fed said its narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, rose
$900 million to a seasonally-adjusted average of $786.3 billion in
the week ended Dec. 26 from a revised $785.4 billion in the previous
week. The previous week's figure had been reported initially as
$785.5 billion.
   It said the measure known as M2 rose to a seasonally adjusted
$3,065.7 billion in the same week from $3,065.2 billion the previous
week.
   But the central bank said a broader measure, M3, fell to a
seasonally adjusted $3,900.0 billion from $3,902.4 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates as well as
trends in the broader money measures, M2 and M3.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks rose $173 million in
the week ended Dec. 28, compared with a gain of $720.0 million a
week earlier.
   _The Federal Reserve said discount window borrowings, excluding
extended credit, averaged $1.372 billion a day in the week ended
Wednesday, up from $438 million the previous week.
   The latest week's average was the highest since the week ended
Jan. 6, 1988 when borrowings averaged $2.46 billion a day.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the monetary
base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at
Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation,
was $285.0 billion in the two-week period ended Wednesday, up from
$284.9 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
