<FIRST>u f AM-CampeauAds     01-05 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Campeau Ads,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Campeau Turns To Newspaper Ads To Boost Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Campeau, the Canadian who created a U.S.
retail empire by taking over two huge department store chains, took
to some of the nation's biggest newspapers Thursday to boast of his
achievements and promise continued strength.
   But the ads _ headlined ``Nothing Succeeds Like Success'' _
painted a picture of Campeau Corp. that differs from the view
presented by the company's disappointing sales and losses during
1988.
   ``Having met all of our financial obligations in 1988, we project
operating results for 1989 and beyond that are more than adequate to
service all of our remaining obligations,'' Campeau said in the
advertisement, which appeared in such papers as the New York Times,
the Atlanta Journal, the Atlanta Constitution, the Los Angeles Times
and the Wall Street Journal.
   ``Because we have achieved so much in this last year, it has been
difficult for some to track and monitor our progress,'' the ad said.
``But you should know that we have had a truly outstanding 1988.''
   Last year, Campeau defeated R.H. Macy &amp; Co. Inc. in a takeover
battle for Federated Department Stores Inc. Campeau paid $8.8
billion for the company whose divisions included Bloomingdale's,
Filene's, Foley's, Burdine's, Rich's and Lazarus department store
chains and Ralph's grocery stores in California.
   In December 1986, the Canadian company purchased Allied Stores
Corp. for $3.4 billion.
   Analysts have suggested the debt caused by the two purchases
weakened Campeau's operation.
   The ad reported a 36 percent increase in operating earnings for
the third quarter ``despite a retail environment we knew would be
difficult. And we expect strong results in the fourth quarter as
well.''
   Earlier this month, Campeau Corp. reported operating profit of
$437 million for the nine months ended Oct. 31, 1988. However, the
company also said it had a net loss of $14 million, compared to a
net loss of $123 million for the same 1987 period.
   Allied divisions lost $18.3 million in the three months ended
Oct. 29, while the Federated stores lost $35.2 million.
   Thursday's advertisement also boasted of ``resounding'' Christmas
sales season. Separately, Campeau reported a 6 percent increase in
Christmas business.
   That performance was in line with overall estimates for the
retail industry, but below increases reported by other retailers.
For example, Sears, Roebuck and Co. reported Thursday its December
sales rose 8.4 percent. At May Department Stores Co., one of
Campeau's biggest compeititors, sales were up 10 percent.
   The ad hinted at thousands of layoffs at Federated divisions,
saying ``1988 was neither easy nor painless'' and, ``we had to make
some hard decisions and take some difficult actions.'' But it also
promised there would be no more sales of assets from Campeau's
retail holdings.
   During 1988, Campeau trimmed Federated, selling several
department store chains: Foley's, Filene's, Bullock's and I. Magnin.
   Robert Campeau also sold several specialty store chains and
Federated's Gold Circle-Richway discount stores.
   Additionally, 17 of Allied's 24 store units have been sold off in
the two years since Campeau acquired the retailer, leaving a handful
of department store chains.
   The advertisement said the divestitures had brought in $4.1
billion and reduced original debt by $3.4 billion.
   There were reports during the year that a planned sale of
high-yield bonds to help pay for the Federated acquisition was
postponed because of a lackluster response by investors.
   Investors were said to be uncertain about the high-yield bond
market in the wake of RJR Nabisco Inc. and Kraft Inc. takeovers. But
analysts said there also were concerns about Campeau's own
performance.
   Campeau denied the reports, but in late October scaled back to
$750 million a planned $1.15 billion junk bond offering.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
