<FIRST>u f AM-WhirlpoolMoves     01-05 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Whirlpool Moves,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whirlpool Sells Kitchen Cabinet Business to Private Partnership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENTON HARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whirlpool Corp. said Thursday it
agreed to sell its kitchen cabinet business for an undisclosed
amount to a partnership made up of Bund Capital in Washington, D.C.,
and John Malaspina of Virginia Beach, Va.
   The transaction, subject to a definitive agreement and to
government approval, is expected to be completed within two months,
said David R. Whitwam, Whirlpool's chairman and chief executive
officer.
   Whitwam had announced previously that Whirlpool would sell the
kitchen and bathroom cabinet operation _ Whirlpool Kitchens Inc. _
to devote more resources to its primary appliance business.
   Whirlpool became the world's largest appliance company with the
purchase of a majority share of Dutch electronics giant NV Philips.
The purchase, announced in August and consummated Jan. 2, forms a
joint venture with expected sales of about $2 billion a year,
augmenting Whirlpool net sales that totaled $4.2 billion in 1987.
   Revenues of the kitchen cabinet business were not available
separately, Whirlpool spokeswoman Donna F. McLean said Thursday.
   Whirlpool Kitchens was included in Whirlpool's 1987 annual report
under ``other products and services,'' a category that accounted for
2 percent of the net sales, Ms. McLean said.
   Bund Capital, headed by Malcolm Bund and Bob Putnam, specializes
in acquiring medium-sized building materials and automobile
aftermarket companies. Malespina was previously associated with
Riviera Cabinets and was on the board of the National Kitchen
Cabinet Association for six years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
