<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 2136EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-BIS-Loans     01-05 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BIS-Loans,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Banks Increase Credit to Soviet Bloc, Cut Third World Claims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BASEL, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western commercial banks expanded
lending to the Soviet bloc and further reduced their exposure in the
debt-ridden Third World during the first half of last year, a survey
showed Thursday.
   Outstanding international claims by banks in 16 advanced
industrial economies that report to the Bank for International
Settlements declined 4 percent in nominal terms to $649.9 billion in
the first semester of 1988, a BIS semi-annual survey said.
   Total claims showed a slight rise of $1.2 billion when adjusted
for currency exchange-rate movements, though the report did not list
an adjusted total figure.
   New credit to centrally-planned East European economies jumped $5
billion when adjusted for currency fluctuations, compared with a
rise of $1 million in the last half of 1987, BIS analysts said.
   The Soviet Union received $4 billion in new loans. Claims on
Bulgaria and East Germany also increased.
   In Latin America, Western banks reduced their adjusted exposure
by $5.7 billion as credits to commercial debtors slumped, the survey
said. Banks cut outstanding claims on Mexico by $2.7 billion and
those on Brazil by $2.2 billion, the report said.
   Among developed countries outside the BIS area, credit to
Australia increased a record $4.3 billion.
   Banks' involvement with South Africa remained virtually unchanged
after outstanding claims were reduced by $100 million during the
period.
   The Basel-based BIS is an international institution also known as
the central bankers' bank. Reporting countries are the United
States, Canada, Britain, West Germany, Italy, Belgium, the
Netherlands, Sweden, Japan, France, Denmark, Finland, Ireland,
Luxembourg, Austria and Spain.
</TEXT>
