<FILEID>AP-NR-01-05-89 2107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   01-05 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Up 20.7 Percent in Late December, 7.5 Percent for the Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Booming year-end car and truck sales at General
Motors Corp. and a jump in car sales at Ford Motor Co. contributed
to overall increases in domestic sales in 1988, the auto companies
said Thursday.
   Manufacturers said sales of U.S.-made cars and light trucks
averaged 44,477 a day in the Dec. 21-31 period. That represents a
20.7 percent increase from the same late December period in 1987.
   For the year, domestic car and light-truck sales reached 11.7
million, averaging 38,060 a day in 1988, up 7.5 percent from 1987
when 10.9 million were sold, or an average of 35,408 a day.
   Imported car and light truck sales in 1988 slumped to 3.7
million, an average of 12,087 a day, compared with 4.1 million, or
13,229 a day.
   High employment and low inflation helped keep boost overall
sales, said Jeanette Garretty, auto analyst with the Bank of America
in San Francisco.
   ``It's been a good year for the economy,'' Garretty said.
   Combined domestic and foreign car and light truck sales totaled
15.4 million in 1988, up from 14.9 million in 1987 and approaching
the 15.7 million of 1985, the second-best sales year ever. The
record year was 1986, when 16.3 million vehicles were sold.
   Industry analysts believe 1988 will move into second place after
sales figures for heavy trucks and medium-duty imported trucks
become available in several weeks, said Ray Windecker, a veteran
Ford Motor Co. analyst.
   In previous years, sales of those trucks have approached the
300,000 mark, and Windecker said that when the overall figures for
1988 are tallied, sales will have surpassed those in 1985.
   Between Dec. 21-31, GM sold an average of 14,656 cars a day, an
increase of 42.2 percent over the same period last year. Ford said
it sold an average of 8,781 cars a day for the period, a 26.4
percent increase.
   But Chrysler Corp. reported selling 3,497 cars a day, slipping
1.7 percent from late December of 1987.
   For the year, GM said it sold 3.64 million cars, an average of
11,823 a day, up 2.1 percent from 3.55 million, an 11,581-a-day
average, in 1987.
   Ford said it sold 2.2 million cars, or 7,160 a day, in 1988, up
8.8 percent on a dalily sales basis from 1987 when it sold 2.0
million, or 6,579 a day.
   Chrysler's 1988 car sales of 1.1 million, or 3,450 a day, were up
10.1 percent from 962,057, or 3,133 a day, in 1987, the company said.
   GM said it set a light-truck sales record for the year,
delivering 1.7 million trucks, an average of 5,651 a day, for a 12.6
percent increase over 1987.
   Ford sold 1.5 million trucks, averaging 4,747 a day, up 4.2
percent, and Chrysler reported sales of 955,619 light trucks, a
daily average of 3,102, for a 14.6 percent increase.
   Among Japanese carmakers, Toyota sales increased in 1988 to
616,529 from 583,809 in 1987.
   Honda saw 1988 import sales drop to 393,360 from 421,688 the
previous year, but sales of its U.S.-made cars jumped to 375,625
from 316,618 in 1987.
   The top-selling European manufacturer was Volkswagen, though its
sales of 168,800 cars were down from 191,705 the year before,
followed by Volvo, which saw sales drop to 97,848 for the year from
105,087 in 1987.
</TEXT>
